{"title_page": "Death of Jairo Mora Sandoval", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{good article}}\n{{update|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jairo Mora Sandoval\n| image = Jairo Mora Sandoval WIDECAST.jpg\n| alt  = Jairo Mora Sandoval overlooks a group of WIDECAST volunteers\n| caption = Mora supervising a WIDECAST event in 2010\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1987|03|22}} \n| birth_place = [[Lim\u00f3n]], [[Costa Rica]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2013|05|31|1987|03|22}}\n| death_place = Mo\u00edn Beach, [[Lim\u00f3n province]], Costa Rica\n| death_cause = Murder by [[asphyxiation]] and head trauma\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} -->\n| residence = \n| other_names = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = environmentalist\n| employer = Paradero Eco-Tour\n| organization = Wider Caribbean Sea Turtle Conservation Network\n| known_for = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Jairo Mora Sandoval''' (March 22, 1987 \u2013 May 31, 2013) was a Costa Rican environmentalist who was murdered while attempting to protect [[leatherback turtle]] nests. Just before midnight on May 30, 2013, Mora and four female volunteers were abducted by a group of masked men. The women eventually escaped and informed the police. Mora's bound and beaten body was found on the beach the next morning. An [[autopsy]] determined he died by [[asphyxiation]] after suffering a blow to the head.\n\nSea turtles are protected by law in Costa Rica, but [[poaching]] remains common. Locals take eggs, which are believed to be an [[aphrodisiac]], and sell them on the black market. The egg trade has been linked to drug trafficking and organized crime. Environmentalists working in [[Lim\u00f3n]] say they are often threatened for trying to protect turtle eggs. Jairo Mora was one such environmentalist working in the area.\n\nIn the wake of Mora's death, the organization he worked with cancelled beach patrol efforts in Costa Rica. His death attracted international attention, including a statement from the [[United Nations]] and multiple rewards for information on the case. In Costa Rica, his death led to calls for reform of environmental policy. On June 4, the government met with environmentalists to discuss potential changes to policy. A plan submitted by environmentalists and endorsed by Environment Minister [[Ren\u00e9 Castro]] would set up a new protected area and grant park rangers more authority to stop poachers, among other changes. On June 5, vigils were held across Costa Rica in honor of Mora. On June 18, the government announced the allocation of [[Costa Rican col\u00f3n|\u20a1]]20 million (US$40,000), which was later upped to \u20a130 million (US$60,000), to memorialize Mora.\n\n==Background==\nCosta Rica has a good reputation for [[wildlife conservation]] in general, and sea turtles have been protected by national legislation in Costa Rica since 1966.<ref name=Independent /><ref name=Conservation />  The country prides itself on its natural beauty and the nation's economy depends heavily on [[ecotourism]]. Tens of thousands of people visit the country every year to observe its sea turtles.<ref name=Conservation />  The turtles of Costa Rica include the [[leatherback turtle]], a [[critically endangered]] species.<ref name=ABC />\n\nThe Marine Turtle Population Law of 2002 assigns a three-year prison sentence to anyone who \"kills, hunts, captures, decapitates, or disturbs marine turtles\".<ref name=Independent />  Even so, it is common for locals to harvest eggs for personal use or for sale in local bars due to supposed [[aphrodisiac]] qualities.<ref name=chased>{{cite news|title=Murdered Costa Rican conservationist had been chased by AK-47-wielding poachers|date=June 2, 2013|author= Lindsay Fendt|work=Tico Times|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Murdered-Costa-Rican-conservationist-had-been-chased-by-AK-47-wielding-poachers_Sunday-June-02-2013|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>  A poacher can make up to $300 in one night, selling eggs for about $1 each on the black market.<ref name=BBC />  Eggs obtained from poaching are often sold to drug dealers or traded for drugs. Poachers are often armed, usually with knives, but sometimes with assault rifles.<ref name=CRTimes>{{cite news|title=CR Conservationist Killed by Drug Traffickers?|author=Dan Stevens|date=June 1, 2013|work=The Costa Rican Times|url=http://www.costaricantimes.com/costa-rica-turtle-conservationist-killed-by-drug-traffickers/16382|accessdate=June 8, 2013}}</ref>  In the impoverished [[Lim\u00f3n]] area, locals claim that police are either colluding with, or afraid of, drug traffickers and poachers.<ref name=Conservation>{{cite web|title=Conservationist Killed in Costa Rica, Where Illegal Wildlife + Drug Trades Threaten Security|author=Sebastian Troeng|publisher=humanature Conversation International Blog|date=June 3, 2013|url=http://blog.conservation.org/2013/06/conservationist-killed-in-costa-rica-where-illegal-wildlife-drug-trades-threaten-security/|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>  Poaching has been cited as a major reason for declining sea turtle populations around the world.<ref name=chased />\n\nAlthough poaching is not new, conservationists report that it is on the rise in Costa Rica.<ref name=Tico />  In the period leading up to Mora's death, poaching became an attractive side income for drug traffickers.<ref name=NewSci /><ref>{{cite news|title=Delincuentes acaban con la tortuga marina en Lim\u00f3n|trans-title=Criminals are destroying the marine turtle in Lim\u00f3n|date=April 28, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|author=Michelle Soto M.|url=http://www.nacion.com/nacional/comunidades/Delincuentes-acaban-tortuga-marina-Limon_0_1338266307.html|accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref> In 2012, a group of six men used assault rifles and hand guns to break into a protected nursery run by the nonprofit environmentalist group Wider Caribbean Sea Turtle Conservation Network (WIDECAST). The men tied up and gagged the volunteers, then  smashed or stole a total 1520 sea turtle eggs.<ref name=Independent>{{cite news|title=Turtle conservationist shot dead 'by poachers' on Costa Rica beach|author=Ian Burrell|work=The Independent|date=June 2, 2013|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/turtle-conservationist-shot-dead-by-poachers-on-costa-rica-beach-8640815.html|accessdate=June 2, 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref name=NewSci /> After the incident, police began accompanying environmentalists on their nightly beach walks.<ref name=chased />  It was later revealed that the incident was intended as a warning for environmentalists to stay off the beaches, according to WIDECAST's Latin American director Didiher Chac\u00f3n.<ref name=NewSci />  According to Lim\u00f3n police chief Erick Calder\u00f3n, 21 people were arrested in 2012 on charges related to turtle poaching.<ref name=captura />\n\n==Life and career of Jairo Mora==\nJairo Mora was a research assistant who worked for Paradero Eco-Tour, a state-sponsored animal rescue group run by Vanessa Lizano.<ref name=Independent /><ref name=BBC />  He was born in Lim\u00f3n on March 22, 1987, to a Nicaraguan father and a Costa Rican mother. From an early age, he was involved in volunteer work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jairo Mora denunci\u00f3 el peligro al que se expon\u00edan en playa Mo\u00edn |trans-title=Jairo Mora denounced the danger that was exposed in beach Moin |work=Repretel |date=May 31, 2013 |url=http://www.repretel.com/jairo-mora-denunci\u00f3-el-peligro-al-que-se-expon\u00ed-en-playa-mo\u00edn |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130616004209/http://www.repretel.com/jairo-mora-denunci%C3%B3-el-peligro-al-que-se-expon%C3%AD-en-playa-mo%C3%ADn |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 16, 2013 |accessdate=June 7, 2013 |language=Spanish }}</ref>\n\nMora regularly volunteered with WIDECAST, which coordinates efforts to protect turtle eggs across [[Central America]]. Mora and other WIDECAST volunteers walked Costa Rican beaches nightly to ward off egg thieves.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica poachers 'kill turtle activist'|publisher=BBC|date=May 31, 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-22738304|accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref>  In 2011, the group protected about 3% of all turtle nests in Costa Rica; in 2012, it increased to 30%.<ref name=CRTimes />  Conservation efforts on Mo\u00edn Beach, which Mora headed, collected 1,500 leatherback turtle nests, the most from any beach in Costa Rica.<ref name=still_no />\n\nAccording to Lizano, her organization often receives threats from poachers because of its conservation efforts.<ref name=BBC />  In 2012, Mora was personally threatened at gunpoint \"to back off and stop the walks\".<ref name=chased />  He and Lizano were also subject to intimidation efforts throughout the 2012 nesting season. \"Both Jairo and I were being followed by motorbikes with guys carrying AK-47s,\" Lizano recalled.<ref name=chased />  After a threat against her family, Lizano relocated from Lim\u00f3n to [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].<ref name=chased />\n\nAt the start of the 2013 leatherback turtle nesting season in April, police decreased their involvement with conservation efforts. Guards were on duty four days a week, but no longer personally escorted volunteers.<ref name=chased /> On April 23, 2013, Mora asked supporters on [[Facebook]] to petition the police for more help. \"Send messages to the police so they come to Mo\u00edn Beach\", he wrote. \"Tell them not to be afraid but to come armed&nbsp; ... we need help and fast.\"<ref name=Tico>{{cite news|title=Turtle conservationist Jairo Mora Sandoval found murdered on Playa Mo\u00edn in Costa Rica |author=Lindsay Fendt |date=May 31, 2013 |work=Tico Times |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-Sandoval-found-murdered-on-Playa-Moin-in-Costa-Rica_Friday-May-31-2013 |accessdate=June 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602044146/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-Sandoval-found-murdered-on-Playa-Moin-in-Costa-Rica_Friday-May-31-2013 |archivedate=June 2, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>  On April 28, Mora told ''[[La Naci\u00f3n (San Jos\u00e9)|La Naci\u00f3n]]'' that environmentalists were being threatened \"by a mafia that was looting the nests for eggs\".<ref name=Independent /> According to friends, Mora received frequent death threats, including an incident just weeks before his death where he was threatened at gunpoint.<ref name=NewSci /><ref name=teletica>{{cite news|title=Testimonio de extranjeras es clave para esclarecer crimen de ambientalista asesinado|trans-title=Testimony of foreigners is key to clarify the crime of environmentalist murder|publisher=Teletica|date=June 3, 2013|author=Natalia Garc\u00eda|url=http://www.teletica.com/Noticias/12570-Testimonio-de-extranjeras-es-clave-para-esclarecer-crimen-de-ambientalista-asesinado.note.aspx|accessdate=June 5, 2013|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611134709/http://www.teletica.com/Noticias/12570-Testimonio-de-extranjeras-es-clave-para-esclarecer-crimen-de-ambientalista-asesinado.note.aspx|archive-date=June 11, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, ''La Naci\u00f3n'' accompanied Mora and Lizano on a typical night's work. Mora spoke about feeling alone and unprotected in his struggle to save the turtles.<ref name=Nacion_accompany>{{cite news|title=Jairo Mora: \u2018Si un polic\u00eda dice que nos apoya,est\u00e1 mintiendo\u2019|trans-title=Jairo Mora: 'If a cop says he supports us, he is lying'|author=Esteban Mata|date=June 1, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-01/Sucesos/Jairo-Mora---Si-un-policia-dice-que-nos-apoya-esta-mintiendo-.aspx|accessdate=June 2, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  Denying reports that police had stepped up their efforts he said: \"If a guard or policeman says he supports us, he is lying.\"<ref name=Nacion_accompany />  ''La Naci\u00f3n'' confirmed that no police were assigned to patrol the beach that evening. When asked if he was afraid, Mora said \"Yes, it's scary, the worst could happen at any time.\"<ref name=Nacion_accompany />  After a May 6 incident where poachers stole a large number of nests, Lim\u00f3n police and the Coast Guard began patrolling Mo\u00edn Beach more thoroughly.<ref name=Tico />\n\n==Death==\nOn the evening of May 30, 2013, Mora and four female volunteers \u2013 three from the United States and one from Spain \u2013 were patrolling Mo\u00edn Beach in [[Lim\u00f3n province]], Costa Rica.<ref name=Tico /> At approximately 11:30&nbsp;pm Mora stepped out of his jeep to move a tree trunk and was ambushed by at least five masked men carrying guns. The men drove the car with the four women to a nearby abandoned house and took their phones, money, and other belongings.<ref name=Nacion />  Three of the men drove off with Mora.<ref name=Tico /> The women were tied up and left in an abandoned house; they eventually freed themselves and went to the police.<ref name=ABC>{{cite news|title=Murder of Activist Threatens Turtle Projects in Costa Rica|author=Santiago Wells|date=June 11, 2013|publisher=ABC\\Univision|url=http://abcnews.go.com/ABC_Univision/News/murder-costa-rican-environmentalist-jairo-mora-sandoval-stirs/story?id=19365519|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFive police officers were on duty the night of Mora's murder, and they had been in radio contact with him about an hour before his death. However, according to Calder\u00f3n, the police were present to increase \"the number of eyes and ears on the beach\", not to protect the conservationists. He also noted that the beach is too large to constantly monitor all of it in the dark.<ref name=Tico />\n\nMora's naked body was found on the beach the next morning.<ref name=Nacion>{{cite news|title=Defensor de tortugas asesinado suplic\u00f3 por patrullaje en Lim\u00f3n|trans-title=Defender of turtles who pleaded for patrols in Lim\u00f3n killed|author=Hulda Miranday|author2=Diego Bosque|work=La Naci\u00f3n|date=June 1, 2013|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-01/Sucesos/Defensor-de-tortugas-asesinado-suplico-por-patrullaje-en-Limon.aspx|accessdate=June 2, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  His body was found beaten and with his hands tied behind his back.<ref name=AP />  [[Autopsy]] results revealed that he had died from [[asphyxiation]] after being struck in the back of the head, likely with an object found at the site of his murder. Earlier reports incorrectly stated he had been shot.<ref name=asfixiado>{{cite news|title=OIJ confirma que Jairo Mora muri\u00f3 asfixiado en la arena y de golpe en el cr\u00e1neo|trans-title=OIJ confirms Jairo Mora suffocated in the sand from a blow to the skull|author=Hugo Solano|date=June 4, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-04/Sucesos/OIJ-confirma-que-Jairo-Mora-murio-asfixiado-en-la-arena-y-de-golpe-en-el-craneo.aspx|accessdate=June 4, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  Mora was 26 at the time of his death.<ref name=AP>{{cite news|title=Jairo Mora Sandoval Dead: Noted Costa Rican Environmentalist Killed|agency=Associated Press|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/01/jairo-mora-sandoval-dead_n_3371679.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=June 2, 2013|date=June 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reaction==\n[[File:Jairo Mora Sandoval WIDECAST 2.jpg|thumb|alt=Jairo Mora Sandoval crouches on a beach partitioned for a conservation survey|Mora in the beach hatchery at Ostional beach on the Pacific coast with fellow volunteers[[circa|.]] 2011]]\n[[Judicial Investigation Department|Judicial Investigation Police]] were unable to immediately determine a motive for Mora's death. Lizano suspects poachers were involved, saying Mora was targeted for protecting the turtle nests.<ref name=BBC />  Chac\u00f3n said [[drug trafficker]]s, who often are also poachers, were likely behind the killing.<ref name=Tico /> Given Mora's recent calls for police help, \"it seems like it was an act of revenge\", he said.<ref name=Tico />\n\nChac\u00f3n said he was \"very hurt\" by Mora's death. \"It's not possible that citizens who protect nature have to suffer from this type of attacks\", he said.<ref name=BBC /> President [[Laura Chinchilla]] called on police and the judicial system to solve what she described as the \"despicable murder\" of Mora.<ref name=Nacion />  A statement from the [[United States Embassy in Costa Rica]] remembered Mora as \"a committed Costa Rican environmentalist\" and called his death \"senseless\".<ref name=AP />  The United Nations released a statement sending condolences and recognizing Mora's \"noble work\" to protect \"an essential part of Costa Rica's and the world's biodiversity.\"<ref name=chased />\n\nTodd Steiner, executive director of the [[Turtle Island Restoration Network]] raised money for a $10,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of those responsible.<ref name=chased /><ref>{{cite news|title=Costa Rican Turtle Defender Found Slain on the Beach He Patrolled|date=June 1, 2013|work=Dot Earth Blog|publisher=New York Times|url=http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/01/costa-rican-turtle-defender-found-slain-on-the-beach-he-patrolled/|accessdate=June 2, 2013|first=Andrew C.|last=Revkin}}</ref> \"Jairo\u2019s murderers must be brought to justice so that [people] know that this will never be tolerated,\" said Steiner in a statement. \"The whole world is watching to make sure the Costa Rican government brings these thugs to justice and makes sea turtle nesting beaches safe for conservationists to do their work.\"<ref name=chased />  A petition started by the [[Sea Turtle Restoration Project]] calling for swift justice generated more than 10,000 signatures within two weeks.<ref name=suspects>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica Prosecutor's Office says it has suspects in turtle conservationist murder|date=June 12, 2013|work=Tico Times|author=Lindsay Fendt|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-Prosecutor-s-Office-says-it-has-suspects-in-turtle-conservationist-murder_Wednesday-June-12-2013/|accessdate=June 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624212740/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-Prosecutor-s-Office-says-it-has-suspects-in-turtle-conservationist-murder_Wednesday-June-12-2013/|archive-date=June 24, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMora death raised fears that the country's economy would be hurt by reduced tourism, leading [[Univision]] to describe the situation as \"an internal crisis\".<ref name=ABC />  Commentary published by the ''[[Costa Rican Times]]'' alleged that the true culprits would never be found, saying whoever was blamed would be a scapegoat offered up by the drug traffickers.<ref name=CRTimes />  The government \"is happy letting the Caribbean side of Costa Rica lose all tourism\" continued the commentary by Dan Stevens. \"Maybe the group ''Sea Turtle Conservation with Guns'' should be formed to fight back.\"<ref name=CRTimes />  An editorial published by the ''[[Tico Times]]'' asked why it took a murder to get the government to act. \"Mora reached out for help before he was killed, and no one came to the rescue, no matter what political spin is put on it\", said the author.<ref name=TTeditorial>{{cite news|title=A World Environment Day in mourning |work=Tico Times |date=June 5, 2013 |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/Opinion/A-World-Environment-Day-in-mourning |accessdate=June 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608084755/http://www.ticotimes.net/Opinion/A-World-Environment-Day-in-mourning |archivedate=June 8, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>  Mora's death, suggested the author, shows that \"the drug traffickers are winning\", that crime is out of control in Lim\u00f3n, and that \"the bad guys operate with near impunity.\"<ref name=TTeditorial />  The editorial concluded by imploring Costa Ricans to re-evaluate their personal environmental habits and support environmental groups that keep fighting.<ref name=TTeditorial />  The Gu\u00e1piles Biofestival, an arts festival held each year during early June, was also dedicated to Mora.<ref>{{cite news|title=Festival de arte en Gu\u00e1piles recuerda labor ambiental de Jairo Mora|trans-title=Gu\u00e1piles art festival remembers the environmental work of Jairo Mora|date=June 9, 2013|work=CR Hoy|author=Jimena Soto|url=http://www.crhoy.com/festival-de-arte-en-guapiles-recuerda-labor-ambiental-de-jairo-mora/|accessdate=June 30, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, Vice President [[Alfio Piva]] described Mora's death as an \"accident\" due to Lim\u00f3n's high crime rate on live TV.<ref name=promises />  He quickly retracted the statement, saying his words had been misunderstood.<ref name=captura /> \"I only meant to recognize that the area where this happened unfortunately has a high murder rate and that there is high risk when working in an area where there is drug trafficking\", he explained.<ref name=promises />  Unsatisfied by the explanation, environmental groups called for a public apology.<ref name=promises />  On June 4, members of the Legislative Assembly said that Piva's comments had \"dishonored the entire country\".<ref name=Diputados>{{cite news|title=Diputados responsabilizan al Ejecutivo de asesinato de Jairo Mora; ecologistas y legisladores piden renuncia de Alfio Piva|trans-title=Deputies blame the Executive for murder of Jairo Mora; environmentalists and lawmakers ask for the resignation of Alfio Piva|work=CR Hoy|author=Jimena Soto|date=June 4, 2013|url=http://www.crhoy.com/diputados-responsabilizan-al-ejecutivo-de-asesinato-de-jairo-mora-y-piden-renuncia-de-alfio-piva/|accessdate=June 30, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  Led by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Villalta]] and [[Juan Carlos Mendoza]], opposition party members called for Piva's resignation. \"We are really full of anger and annoyance. We are embarrassed as a nation\", said Mendoza.<ref name=Diputados />\n\nOn June 5, [[vigil]]s in honor of Mora were held in at least six Costa Rica cities to coincide with [[World Environment Day]]. Ecologist Federation president Mauricio \u00c1lvarez, who helped organize the vigils, said \"We are asking for justice for Jairo\u2019s murder and&nbsp;...demand a halt to the impunity that has reigned over too many threats to ecologists, farmers and indigenous groups.\"<ref name=promises /> Despite rainy weather, hundred of people showed up to carry signs, light candles, and place stuffed turtles on the beach. Leaflets blamed police and the government for Mora's death and demanded swift justice.<ref name=peaceful>{{cite news|title=In Costa Rica, a peace vigil for slain turtle conservationist Jairo Mora|work=Tico Times|date=June 5, 2013|author=Lindsay Fendt|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/In-Costa-Rica-a-peace-vigil-for-slain-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-June-05-2013|accessdate=June 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607183426/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/In-Costa-Rica-a-peace-vigil-for-slain-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-June-05-2013/|archive-date=June 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Among those in attendance were Roberto Molina, secretary general of the Environmental Ministry's labor union, and Jos\u00e9 Lino Chavez, Vice Minister of Waters and Oceans.<ref name=peaceful />\n\nOn June 6, [[Sea Shepherd Conservation Society]] founder [[Paul Watson]] offered an additional $30,000 reward for information leading to the capture of Mora's murderer.<ref name=ofrece />  He said the money would come from his personal wealth, not from Sea Shepherd, and that he had sold a vehicle to fund the reward.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paul Watson says Costa Rica is in Japan\u2019s pocket; blames Jairo Mora\u2019s death on government|work=Inside Costa Rica|date=June 27, 2013|url=http://insidecostarica.com/2013/06/27/paul-watson-says-costa-rica-is-in-japans-pocket-blames-jairo-moras-death-on-government/|accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref>  Watson's pledge, together with additional funds raised by Steiner, brought the total reward to $56,000. A separate memorial fund to assist Mora's family and continue conservation efforts in his name raised $7,000.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Global Outcry Over Murdered Sea Turtle Activist Intensifies: Reward for Information Leading to Arrest, Conviction of Killers Now $56,000|author=Todd Steiner|publisher=Center for Biological Diversity|date=June 12, 2013|url=http://www.biologicaldiversity.org/news/press_releases/2013/jairo-mora-sandoval-06-12-2013.html|accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> In early July, Costa Rican businessman [[Roy Rivera]] said he was working to raise funds to increase the information reward.<ref name=memory />\n\nWatson, who is wanted by Costa Rica for skipping [[bail]] on charges related to a 2002 incident, said Mora's death proves that his own life would be in \"great danger\" if he ever returned to Costa Rica.<ref name=ofrece>{{cite news|title=Paul Watson ofrece recompensa de $30.000 a quien d\u00e9 informaci\u00f3n del homicidio de conservacionista Jairo Mora|trans-title=Paul Watson offers $30,000 reward to whoever gives information on the murder of conservationist Jairo Mora|work=La Naci\u00f3n|date=June 6, 2013|url=http://www.nacion.com/sucesos/Paul-Watson-conservacionista-Jairo-Mora_0_1346065391.html|accessdate=June 29, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  \"The authorities were very quick to respond to Japan and issued an arrest warrant for the protection of sharks&nbsp;... however, when it comes to a horrible murder of a compassionate conservationist, the government does nothing.\"<ref name=ofrece /> Later in June, Watson announced that his organization's next boat would be named the S.S. ''Jairo Mora Sandoval''. \"We do not want the name of this courageous and passionate young man to be forgotten\", he said on Facebook.<ref name=names>{{cite news|title=Sea Shepherd's Paul Watson names new ship after slain Costa Rican turtle activist|date=June 27, 2013|work=Tico Times|author=L. Arias|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Sea-Shepherd-s-Paul-Watson-names-new-ship-after-slain-Costa-Rican-turtle-activist_Thursday-June-27-2013|accessdate=June 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701044405/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Sea-Shepherd-s-Paul-Watson-names-new-ship-after-slain-Costa-Rican-turtle-activist_Thursday-June-27-2013|archive-date=July 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, the [[Ocean Futures Society]] joined the chorus of international voices calling for swift justice. \"This crime, in the Lim\u00f3n province, has shaken the consciousnesses of many internationally,\" wrote Ruben Arviz\u00fa, the society's Latin American director.<ref name=suspects />  Arviz\u00fa said that Costa Rica should make the case a national priority.<ref name=suspects />  On June 18, Costa Rican rapper Yaco released a song entitled \"Playa Roja\" (Red Beach) about Mora. Yaco, who is known for using his songs as social commentary, released the song via social media, saying it was \"not a commercial release\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Yaco mueve las redes con tema dedicado al ambientalista Jairo Mora|trans-title=Yaco moves the networks with a song dedicated to the environmentalist Jairo Mora|date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2013|work=CR Hoy|url=http://www.crhoy.com/yaco-mueve-las-redes-con-tema-dedicado-al-ambientalista-jairo-mora/|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nAt the June 26\u201328 Inter-American Convention on the Protection and Conservation of Sea Turtles (IAC), Mora's death was a popular subject. A declaration from the Mexican delegation read, \"As sea turtles are a shared resource, criminal activity that prevents [on-site] protection efforts from taking place in one country presents an urgent concern to all range states.\"<ref name=another>{{cite news|title=Another meeting, yet no news on investigation into turtle conservationist Jairo Mora's murder|author=Lindsay Fendt|work=Tico Times|date=July 2, 2013|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Another-meeting-yet-no-news-on-investigation-into-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-s-murder-_Tuesday-July-02-2013|accessdate=July 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707134719/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Another-meeting-yet-no-news-on-investigation-into-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-s-murder-_Tuesday-July-02-2013|archive-date=July 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>  A convention floor speech and a second written declaration also discussed Mora's death.<ref name=another />\n\n==Aftermath==\nFollowing Mora's death, WIDECAST suspended beach patrol operations.<ref name=AP />  \"We can\u2019t risk human lives for this project,\" Chac\u00f3n said. \"But this is probably the exact result that the killers were hoping for.\"<ref name=Tico />  Many volunteers quit the project after Mora's death, leaving the organization 200 people short staffed.<ref name=chased />  Organizations such as WIDECAST depend heavily on foreign volunteers. According to Chac\u00f3n, the future of his organization will be in jeopardy if the situation continues.<ref name=NewSci>{{cite news|title=Turtle conservationist murdered in Costa Rica|author=Peter Aldhous|date=June 3, 2013|work=New Scientist|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23639-turtle-conservationist-murdered-in-costa-rica.html|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> Aimee Leslie, who oversees sea turtle efforts for the [[World Wildlife Foundation]] called the situation \"a critical point for conservation\" in Costa Rica and \"a national security issue.<ref name=ABC />  She said that conservation efforts were already difficult without being scared for one's life.<ref name=ABC /> Lizano said she was in negotiations with the police for armed escorts on future patrols, but vowed to continue to work even if they refused. \"If we forget about this beach, then Jairo died for nothing,\" she said.<ref name=chased />\n\nOn June 3, Calder\u00f3n remarked that police would continue to support environmentalists and increase their presence on Mo\u00edn Beach.<ref name=captura>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00eda captura a hueveros armados en playa Mo\u00edn|trans-title=Police capture armed poachers on Mo\u00edn Beach|author=Diego Bosque G.|date=June 4, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-04/Portada/Policia-captura-a-hueveros-armados-en-playa-Moin.aspx|accessdate=June 5, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  The next day police arrested two armed men who were allegedly trying to steal turtle eggs from the same beach where Mora was killed. Also on June 4, a group of three men and a minor was arrested on similar charges.<ref name=captura />  Subsequently, Lim\u00f3n began to dispatch twenty police officers nightly to escort conservationists and patrol the beaches. In spite of increased police presence Lizano remarked, on June 11, \"Every night all of the [turtle] nests are raided. It is still pretty much the same even though we walk with police.\"<ref name=still_no>{{cite news|title=Still no arrests in slaying of Costa Rican conservationist |author=Lindsay Fendt |work=Tico Times |date=June 11, 2013 |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Still-no-arrests-in-slaying-of-Costa-Rican-conservationist_Tuesday-June-11-2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627032427/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Still-no-arrests-in-slaying-of-Costa-Rican-conservationist_Tuesday-June-11-2013 |archivedate=June 27, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nPrompted by the death of Mora, dozens of environmentalists met with the [[Ministry of Environment, Energy and Telecommunications]] (MINAE), headed by [[Ren\u00e9 Castro]], to discuss their dissatisfaction with current conservation efforts on June 4. Their requests included punishing those responsible for Mora's death, greater criminal penalties for poaching, and more efforts by MINAE to fight egg poachers.<ref name=celebracion />  Castro suggested implementing a plan submitted by WIDECAST. The plan would give park rangers jurisdiction to arrest poachers on Mo\u00edn Beach and create a code of conduct for beach visitors nationwide. It would also increase penalties for poaching, name a new protected area after Mora, and set up a memorial fund in his name.<ref name=promises>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica's environment minister promises action in wake of conservationist's murder|author=Lindsay Fendt|work=Tico Times|date=June 4, 2013|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-s-environment-minister-promises-action-in-wake-of-conservationist-s-murder-_Tuesday-June-04-2013|accessdate=July 6, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709125857/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-s-environment-minister-promises-action-in-wake-of-conservationist-s-murder-_Tuesday-June-04-2013/|archive-date=July 9, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The proposal was initially met with enthusiasm, but it later gave way to complaints about lax environmental enforcement nationwide. \"This isn\u2019t only happening in Mo\u00edn and this not only happening with turtle conservation,\" remarked Molina.<ref name=promises /> Deputy Minister of Security [[Celso Gamboa]], who was also in attendance, promised to increase security forces in Lim\u00f3n.<ref name=celebracion>{{cite news|title=Celebraci\u00f3n del D\u00eda Mundial del Ambiente estar\u00e1 marcada por luto, dice Defensor\u00eda|trans-title=Environmentalists call for greater protection and stronger legislation to continue its work|author=Hugo Solano|date=June 4, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-04/AldeaGlobal/Celebracion-del-Dia-Mundial-del-Ambiente-estara-marcada-por-luto--dice-Defensoria.aspx|accessdate=June 4, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, the Legislative Assembly unanimously passed a motion to form a special committee investigating Mora's death. \"It is important to acknowledge that the death of Jairo is not only the fault of these bands of criminals, but also the fault of the state,\" remarked the motion's sponsor [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Villalta]]<ref name=still_no />  On June 19, Castro, Ch\u00e1vez, the heads of several environmental groups, and members of Mora's family, met to work out the details of the earlier proposals. After the meeting, Castro announced that [[Costa Rican col\u00f3n|\u20a1]]20 million (approximately US$40,000) would be allocated for a monument in Mora's honor in the form of either a new turtle observation area or an online tribute with video of nesting sea turtles. Castro also confirmed that the government had plans to turn Mo\u00edn Beach into a protected park. However, the plan to name the park after Mora was abandoned at the request of his family. MINAE also plans to allocate \"specialized units\" armed with equipment to protect Costa Rica's coasts from environmental threats.<ref name=designate>{{cite news|title=Officials will designate Costa Rican beach where conservationist was murdered as a protected wildlife area |author=Lindsay Fendt |work=Tico Times |date=June 19, 2013 |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Officials-will-designate-Costa-Rican-beach-where-conservationist-was-murdered-as-a-protected-wildlife-area_Wednesday-June-19-2013/ |accessdate=June 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624172537/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Officials-will-designate-Costa-Rican-beach-where-conservationist-was-murdered-as-a-protected-wildlife-area_Wednesday-June-19-2013 |archivedate=June 24, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nTourism to Costa Rica was down sharply during the first half of June 2013. Jorge Molina, president of The Southern Caribbean Tourism Chamber, said Mora's death was affecting reservations and would likely continue to do so for several months. Aurora G\u00e1mez, who owns a [[Manzanillo Beach]] hotel, said her occupancy rate normally runs at 50% in June, but was at just 10% in the weeks after Mora's death. She said she had received cancellations that specifically cited Mora's death as a factor. [[Cahuita]] hotel owner Eddie Ryan echoed G\u00e1mez, saying he had two patrons cite Mora's death when cancelling. Restaurants, bars, tour guides, and transportation companies were also affected. Some entrepreneurs blamed WIDECAST for the lost business saying the organization was aware of the risks but continued to patrol anyway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Asesinato de Jairo Mora golpea el turismo en el Caribe sur|trans-title=Murder of Jairo Mora hits the southern Caribbean tourism|date=June 16, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/sucesos/Asesinato-Jairo-Mora-turismo-Caribe_0_1348065337.html|accessdate=June 29, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, a nationwide protest was held to draw attention to a wide variety of issues. Environmental groups joined the protests, again calling for justice to be served to Mora's murderers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Several groups plan a national protest in 25 cantons next week |date=June 19, 2013 |work=Tico Times |author=L. Arias |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Several-groups-plan-a-national-protest-in-25-cantons-next-week_Wednesday-June-19-2013/ |accessdate=June 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627083944/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Several-groups-plan-a-national-protest-in-25-cantons-next-week_Wednesday-June-19-2013/ |archivedate=June 27, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, MINAE again met with more than 30 environmental groups to discuss the situation.<ref name=comision>{{cite news|title=A m\u00e1s de un mes del asesinato de Jairo Mora Ecologistas piden una 'comisi\u00f3n de la verdad'|trans-title=More than a month after the murder of Jairo Mora, ecologists call for a 'truth commission'|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=Columbia|url=http://www.columbia.co.cr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8439:a-mas-de-un-mes-del-asesinato-de-jairo-mora-ecologistas-piden-una-comision-de-la-verdad&catid=46:nacionales&Itemid=116|accessdate=July 6, 2013|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205540/http://www.columbia.co.cr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8439:a-mas-de-un-mes-del-asesinato-de-jairo-mora-ecologistas-piden-una-comision-de-la-verdad&catid=46:nacionales&Itemid=116|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Castro said that plans to make Mo\u00edn Beach a protected area were moving forward. However, he said, making the area a national park was not feasible because of the number of people living on the beach. \"A national park is too closed off for this particular beach\", he explained.<ref name=another />  Environmentalists requested that the [[Gandoca-Manzanillo Wildlife Refuge]], one of Mora's favorite places, be renamed in honor of him. The plan was endorsed by his family.<ref name=avanzan>{{cite news|title=Ambientalistas avanzan en creaci\u00f3n de \u00e1rea protegida en Mo\u00edn en honor a Jairo Mora|trans-title=Environmentalists advance in the creation of protected area in Mo\u00edn in honor of Jairo Mora|date=June 3, 2013|work=El Pais|author=Oriana Ortiz Vindas|url=http://www.elpais.cr/frontend/noticia_detalle/1/83116|accessdate=July 6, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  They also requested the formation of a \"truth commission\" to investigate Mora's murder and eight other deaths from the past 20 years.<ref name=comision />  Government officials said they were in the process of installing radar systems across Costa Rica to detect drug trafficking and illegal fishing, and that they would launch a plan to patrol Mo\u00edn beach with the assistance of the [[Costa Rican Petroleum Refinery]] (RECOPE).<ref name=memory>{{cite news|title=In Memory of Jairo Mora: A Wildlife Refuge in Costa Rica|url=http://news.co.cr/in-memory-of-jairo-mora-a-wildlife-refuge-in-costa-rica/22722/|date=July 4, 2013|work=Costa Rica Star|author=Jaime Lopez|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=avanzan />  MINAE said that \u20a130 million (US$60,000) had been allocated for Mora's memorial and environmental education done in his name.<ref name=avanzan />\n\nAs of July 4, no arrests had been made in relation to the murder of Mora. Ministries of Public Safety Vice Minister Celso Gamboa called the investigation ongoing.<ref name=memory />  In mid-June, Castro had said the investigation was proceeding well and he had \"every reason to be optimistic that we will solve this crime.\"<ref name=designate />  On July 10, the prosecutor's office said two suspects had been identified and that the case would \"advance significantly\" over the coming week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Costa Rican chief prosecutor: Investigators have identified two suspects in slaying of conservationist Jairo Mora|work=Tico Times|date=July 10, 2013|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rican-chief-prosecutor-Investigators-have-identified-two-suspects-in-slaying-of-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-July-10-2013|accessdate=July 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130713160842/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rican-chief-prosecutor-Investigators-have-identified-two-suspects-in-slaying-of-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-July-10-2013|archive-date=July 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, Costa Rican police raided several locations near [[Tortuguero, Costa Rica#Mo\u00edn|Mo\u00edn]] and the city of [[Lim\u00f3n]], and arrested several suspects believed to be involved in Mora's murder, as well as other crimes, including robbery and turtle egg poaching. Police said that more arrests are expected.<ref name=ticotimesmora>{{cite web|last=Fendt |first=Lindsay |title=Costa Rican police sweep nets several suspects in Jairo Mora murder case |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/BREAKING-Costa-Rican-police-sweep-nets-several-suspects-in-Jairo-Mora-murder-case_Wednesday-July-31-2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130731164819/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/BREAKING-Costa-Rican-police-sweep-nets-several-suspects-in-Jairo-Mora-murder-case_Wednesday-July-31-2013 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2013 |work=The Tico Times |accessdate=July 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe first trial of the alleged perpetrators ended in a mistrial and a second trial was held in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2015/01/29/united-nations-environmental-groups-condemn-verdict-in-jairo-mora-murder-case|title=United Nations, environmental groups condemn verdict in Jairo Mora murder case|work=The Tico Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2015/08/05/costa-rican-appeals-court-calls-re-trial-jairo-mora-murder-case|title=Murder of Costa Rican conservationist Jairo Mora headed for retrial|work=The Tico Times}}</ref> In January 2016, a court found seven men accused of Mora's murder not guilty based on reasonable doubt.  Four of the men were, however, sentenced to lengthy prison terms due to assault, kidnapping and aggravated robbery for a crime that occurred on the same beach shortly before Mora's murder.  (Donald Salm\u00f3n: 27 years in prison for aggravated robbery, rape and kidnapping; H\u00e9ctor Cash: 23 years for aggravated robbery, kidnapping and sexual abuse; Jos\u00e9 Bryan Delgado: 17 years for aggravated robbery and kidnapping; Ernesto Centeno: 17 years for aggravated robbery and kidnapping.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2015/01/26/not-guilty-7-men-acquitted-of-murder-of-costa-rica-sea-turtle-conservationist-jairo-mora|title=NOT GUILTY: 7 men acquitted of murder of Costa Rica sea turtle conservationist Jairo Mora|work=The Tico Times}}</ref> Subsequently, the not guilty verdict was overturned on appeal and the four men were convicted of Mora's murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2016/03/29/4-convicted-jairo-mora-murder-trial|title=4 convicted, 3 acquitted in Jairo Mora murder trial|work=The Tico Times}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2016, the Marine Section of the [[Society for Conservation Biology]] (SCB Marine) announced the \"Jairo Mora Sandoval Bravery Award.\" The award is for bravery associated with an outstanding contribution to the field of marine conservation, with particular emphasis on responsible and educated scientific endeavor, public engagement and conservation activism. The initiative to honor Jairo's commitment to marine conservation was instigated by the SCB Marine Policy Committee, and includes a $1,000 financial component.\n\nIt is given biennially and the winner is announced at the International Marine Conservation Congress (IMCC). The 2018 Awardee will be announced at IMCC5, that will be held in Kuching (Malaysia) in June 24\u201329. The inaugural Award was given, posthumously to Jairo Mora Sandoval at the 2016 IMCC in St Johns, Newfoundland, Canada, with his mother receiving the funds to set up an NGO to continue his work to protect the sea turtles of Costa Rica.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.crhoy.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/DSCF5078.jpg Photo] of the crime scene\n* [http://www.biologicaldiversity.org/news/press_releases/2013/jairo-mora-sandoval-06-03-2013.html Press release] on a reward fund\n* [https://conbio.org/mini-sites/jairoaward/ Jairo Award] offered by the Marine Section of the Society for Conservation Biology.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandoval, Jairo Mora}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lim\u00f3n Province]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Murdered animal activists]]\n[[Category:Environmental killings]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:2013 crimes in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:2013 murders in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{good article}}\n{{update|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jairo Mora Sandoval\n| image = Jairo Mora Sandoval WIDECAST.jpg\n| alt  = Jairo Mora Sandoval overlooks a group of WIDECAST volunteers\n| caption = Mora supervising a WIDECAST event in 2010\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1987|03|22}} \n| birth_place = [[Lim\u00f3n]], [[Costa Rica]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2013|05|31|1987|03|22}}\n| death_place = Mo\u00edn Beach, [[Lim\u00f3n province]], Costa Rica\n| death_cause = Murder by [[asphyxiation]] and head trauma\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} -->\n| residence = \n| other_names = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = environmentalist\n| employer = Paradero Eco-Tour\n| organization = Wider Caribbean Sea Turtle Conservation Network\n| known_for = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Jairo Mora Sandoval''' (March 22, 1987 \u2013 May 31, 2013) was a Costa Rican environmentalist who was murdered while attempting to protect [[leatherback turtle]] nests. Just before midnight on May 30, 2013, Mora and four female volunteers were abducted by a group of masked men. The women eventually escaped and informed the police. Mora's bound and beaten body was found on the beach the next morning. An [[autopsy]] determined he died by [[asphyxiation]] after suffering a blow to the head.\n\nSea turtles are protected by law in Costa Rica, but [[poaching]] remains common. Locals take eggs, which are believed to be an [[aphrodisiac]], and sell them on the black market. The egg trade has been linked to drug trafficking and organized crime. Environmentalists working in [[Lim\u00f3n]] say they are often threatened for trying to protect turtle eggs. Jairo Mora was one such environmentalist working in the area.\n\nIn the wake of Mora's death, the organization he worked with cancelled beach patrol efforts in Costa Rica. His death attracted international attention, including a statement from the [[United Nations]] and multiple rewards for information on the case. In Costa Rica, his death led to calls for reform of environmental policy. On June 4, the government met with environmentalists to discuss potential changes to policy. A plan submitted by environmentalists and endorsed by Environment Minister [[Ren\u00e9 Castro]] would set up a new protected area and grant park rangers more authority to stop poachers, among other changes. On June 5, vigils were held across Costa Rica in honor of Mora. On June 18, the government announced the allocation of [[Costa Rican col\u00f3n|\u20a1]]20 million (US$40,000), which was later upped to \u20a130 million (US$60,000), to memorialize Mora.\n\n==Background==\nCosta Rica has a good reputation for [[wildlife conservation]] in general, and sea turtles have been protected by national legislation in Costa Rica since 1966.<ref name=Independent /><ref name=Conservation />  The country prides itself on its natural beauty and the nation's economy depends heavily on [[ecotourism]]. Tens of thousands of people visit the country every year to observe its sea turtles.<ref name=Conservation />  The turtles of Costa Rica include the [[leatherback turtle]], a [[critically endangered]] species.<ref name=ABC />\n\nThe Marine Turtle Population Law of 2002 assigns a three-year prison sentence to anyone who \"kills, hunts, captures, decapitates, or disturbs marine turtles\".<ref name=Independent />  Even so, it is common for locals to harvest eggs for personal use or for sale in local bars due to supposed [[aphrodisiac]] qualities.<ref name=chased>{{cite news|title=Murdered Costa Rican conservationist had been chased by AK-47-wielding poachers|date=June 2, 2013|author= Lindsay Fendt|work=Tico Times|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Murdered-Costa-Rican-conservationist-had-been-chased-by-AK-47-wielding-poachers_Sunday-June-02-2013|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>  A poacher can make up to $300 in one night, selling eggs for about $1 each on the black market.<ref name=BBC />  Eggs obtained from poaching are often sold to drug dealers or traded for drugs. Poachers are often armed, usually with knives, but sometimes with assault rifles.<ref name=CRTimes>{{cite news|title=CR Conservationist Killed by Drug Traffickers?|author=Dan Stevens|date=June 1, 2013|work=The Costa Rican Times|url=http://www.costaricantimes.com/costa-rica-turtle-conservationist-killed-by-drug-traffickers/16382|accessdate=June 8, 2013}}</ref>  In the impoverished [[Lim\u00f3n]] area, locals claim that police are either colluding with, or afraid of, drug traffickers and poachers.<ref name=Conservation>{{cite web|title=Conservationist Killed in Costa Rica, Where Illegal Wildlife + Drug Trades Threaten Security|author=Sebastian Troeng|publisher=humanature Conversation International Blog|date=June 3, 2013|url=http://blog.conservation.org/2013/06/conservationist-killed-in-costa-rica-where-illegal-wildlife-drug-trades-threaten-security/|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>  Poaching has been cited as a major reason for declining sea turtle populations around the world.<ref name=chased />\n\nAlthough poaching is not new, conservationists report that it is on the rise in Costa Rica.<ref name=Tico />  In the period leading up to Mora's death, poaching became an attractive side income for with drug traffickers.<ref name=NewSci /><ref>{{cite news|title=Delincuentes acaban con la tortuga marina en Lim\u00f3n|trans-title=Criminals are destroying the marine turtle in Lim\u00f3n|date=April 28, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|author=Michelle Soto M.|url=http://www.nacion.com/nacional/comunidades/Delincuentes-acaban-tortuga-marina-Limon_0_1338266307.html|accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref> In 2012, a group of six men used assault rifles and hand guns to break into a protected nursery run by the nonprofit environmentalist group Wider Caribbean Sea Turtle Conservation Network (WIDECAST). The men tied up and gagged the volunteers, then  smashed or stole a total 1520 sea turtle eggs.<ref name=Independent>{{cite news|title=Turtle conservationist shot dead 'by poachers' on Costa Rica beach|author=Ian Burrell|work=The Independent|date=June 2, 2013|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/turtle-conservationist-shot-dead-by-poachers-on-costa-rica-beach-8640815.html|accessdate=June 2, 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref name=NewSci /> After the incident, police began accompanying environmentalists on their nightly beach walks.<ref name=chased />  It was later revealed that the incident was intended as a warning for environmentalists to stay off the beaches, according to WIDECAST's Latin American director Didiher Chac\u00f3n.<ref name=NewSci />  According to Lim\u00f3n police chief Erick Calder\u00f3n, 21 people were arrested in 2012 on charges related to turtle poaching.<ref name=captura />\n\n==Life and career of Jairo Mora==\nJairo Mora was a research assistant who worked for Paradero Eco-Tour, a state-sponsored animal rescue group run by Vanessa Lizano.<ref name=Independent /><ref name=BBC />  He was born in Lim\u00f3n on March 22, 1987, to a Nicaraguan father and a Costa Rican mother. From an early age, he was involved in volunteer work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jairo Mora denunci\u00f3 el peligro al que se expon\u00edan en playa Mo\u00edn |trans-title=Jairo Mora denounced the danger that was exposed in beach Moin |work=Repretel |date=May 31, 2013 |url=http://www.repretel.com/jairo-mora-denunci\u00f3-el-peligro-al-que-se-expon\u00ed-en-playa-mo\u00edn |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130616004209/http://www.repretel.com/jairo-mora-denunci%C3%B3-el-peligro-al-que-se-expon%C3%AD-en-playa-mo%C3%ADn |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 16, 2013 |accessdate=June 7, 2013 |language=Spanish }}</ref>\n\nMora regularly volunteered with WIDECAST, which coordinates efforts to protect turtle eggs across [[Central America]]. Mora and other WIDECAST volunteers walked Costa Rican beaches nightly to ward off egg thieves.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica poachers 'kill turtle activist'|publisher=BBC|date=May 31, 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-22738304|accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref>  In 2011, the group protected about 3% of all turtle nests in Costa Rica; in 2012, it increased to 30%.<ref name=CRTimes />  Conservation efforts on Mo\u00edn Beach, which Mora headed, collected 1,500 leatherback turtle nests, the most from any beach in Costa Rica.<ref name=still_no />\n\nAccording to Lizano, her organization often receives threats from poachers because of its conservation efforts.<ref name=BBC />  In 2012, Mora was personally threatened at gunpoint \"to back off and stop the walks\".<ref name=chased />  He and Lizano were also subject to intimidation efforts throughout the 2012 nesting season. \"Both Jairo and I were being followed by motorbikes with guys carrying AK-47s,\" Lizano recalled.<ref name=chased />  After a threat against her family, Lizano relocated from Lim\u00f3n to [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].<ref name=chased />\n\nAt the start of the 2013 leatherback turtle nesting season in April, police decreased their involvement with conservation efforts. Guards were on duty four days a week, but no longer personally escorted volunteers.<ref name=chased /> On April 23, 2013, Mora asked supporters on [[Facebook]] to petition the police for more help. \"Send messages to the police so they come to Mo\u00edn Beach\", he wrote. \"Tell them not to be afraid but to come armed&nbsp; ... we need help and fast.\"<ref name=Tico>{{cite news|title=Turtle conservationist Jairo Mora Sandoval found murdered on Playa Mo\u00edn in Costa Rica |author=Lindsay Fendt |date=May 31, 2013 |work=Tico Times |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-Sandoval-found-murdered-on-Playa-Moin-in-Costa-Rica_Friday-May-31-2013 |accessdate=June 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602044146/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-Sandoval-found-murdered-on-Playa-Moin-in-Costa-Rica_Friday-May-31-2013 |archivedate=June 2, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>  On April 28, Mora told ''[[La Naci\u00f3n (San Jos\u00e9)|La Naci\u00f3n]]'' that environmentalists were being threatened \"by a mafia that was looting the nests for eggs\".<ref name=Independent /> According to friends, Mora received frequent death threats, including an incident just weeks before his death where he was threatened at gunpoint.<ref name=NewSci /><ref name=teletica>{{cite news|title=Testimonio de extranjeras es clave para esclarecer crimen de ambientalista asesinado|trans-title=Testimony of foreigners is key to clarify the crime of environmentalist murder|publisher=Teletica|date=June 3, 2013|author=Natalia Garc\u00eda|url=http://www.teletica.com/Noticias/12570-Testimonio-de-extranjeras-es-clave-para-esclarecer-crimen-de-ambientalista-asesinado.note.aspx|accessdate=June 5, 2013|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611134709/http://www.teletica.com/Noticias/12570-Testimonio-de-extranjeras-es-clave-para-esclarecer-crimen-de-ambientalista-asesinado.note.aspx|archive-date=June 11, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, ''La Naci\u00f3n'' accompanied Mora and Lizano on a typical night's work. Mora spoke about feeling alone and unprotected in his struggle to save the turtles.<ref name=Nacion_accompany>{{cite news|title=Jairo Mora: \u2018Si un polic\u00eda dice que nos apoya,est\u00e1 mintiendo\u2019|trans-title=Jairo Mora: 'If a cop says he supports us, he is lying'|author=Esteban Mata|date=June 1, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-01/Sucesos/Jairo-Mora---Si-un-policia-dice-que-nos-apoya-esta-mintiendo-.aspx|accessdate=June 2, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  Denying reports that police had stepped up their efforts he said: \"If a guard or policeman says he supports us, he is lying.\"<ref name=Nacion_accompany />  ''La Naci\u00f3n'' confirmed that no police were assigned to patrol the beach that evening. When asked if he was afraid, Mora said \"Yes, it's scary, the worst could happen at any time.\"<ref name=Nacion_accompany />  After a May 6 incident where poachers stole a large number of nests, Lim\u00f3n police and the Coast Guard began patrolling Mo\u00edn Beach more thoroughly.<ref name=Tico />\n\n==Death==\nOn the evening of May 30, 2013, Mora and four female volunteers \u2013 three from the United States and one from Spain \u2013 were patrolling Mo\u00edn Beach in [[Lim\u00f3n province]], Costa Rica.<ref name=Tico /> At approximately 11:30&nbsp;pm Mora stepped out of his jeep to move a tree trunk and was ambushed by at least five masked men carrying guns. The men drove the car with the four women to a nearby abandoned house and took their phones, money, and other belongings.<ref name=Nacion />  Three of the men drove off with Mora.<ref name=Tico /> The women were tied up and left in an abandoned house; they eventually freed themselves and went to the police.<ref name=ABC>{{cite news|title=Murder of Activist Threatens Turtle Projects in Costa Rica|author=Santiago Wells|date=June 11, 2013|publisher=ABC\\Univision|url=http://abcnews.go.com/ABC_Univision/News/murder-costa-rican-environmentalist-jairo-mora-sandoval-stirs/story?id=19365519|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFive police officers were on duty the night of Mora's murder, and they had been in radio contact with him about an hour before his death. However, according to Calder\u00f3n, the police were present to increase \"the number of eyes and ears on the beach\", not to protect the conservationists. He also noted that the beach is too large to constantly monitor all of it in the dark.<ref name=Tico />\n\nMora's naked body was found on the beach the next morning.<ref name=Nacion>{{cite news|title=Defensor de tortugas asesinado suplic\u00f3 por patrullaje en Lim\u00f3n|trans-title=Defender of turtles who pleaded for patrols in Lim\u00f3n killed|author=Hulda Miranday|author2=Diego Bosque|work=La Naci\u00f3n|date=June 1, 2013|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-01/Sucesos/Defensor-de-tortugas-asesinado-suplico-por-patrullaje-en-Limon.aspx|accessdate=June 2, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  His body was found beaten and with his hands tied behind his back.<ref name=AP />  [[Autopsy]] results revealed that he had died from [[asphyxiation]] after being struck in the back of the head, likely with an object found at the site of his murder. Earlier reports incorrectly stated he had been shot.<ref name=asfixiado>{{cite news|title=OIJ confirma que Jairo Mora muri\u00f3 asfixiado en la arena y de golpe en el cr\u00e1neo|trans-title=OIJ confirms Jairo Mora suffocated in the sand from a blow to the skull|author=Hugo Solano|date=June 4, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-04/Sucesos/OIJ-confirma-que-Jairo-Mora-murio-asfixiado-en-la-arena-y-de-golpe-en-el-craneo.aspx|accessdate=June 4, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  Mora was 26 at the time of his death.<ref name=AP>{{cite news|title=Jairo Mora Sandoval Dead: Noted Costa Rican Environmentalist Killed|agency=Associated Press|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/01/jairo-mora-sandoval-dead_n_3371679.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=June 2, 2013|date=June 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reaction==\n[[File:Jairo Mora Sandoval WIDECAST 2.jpg|thumb|alt=Jairo Mora Sandoval crouches on a beach partitioned for a conservation survey|Mora in the beach hatchery at Ostional beach on the Pacific coast with fellow volunteers[[circa|.]] 2011]]\n[[Judicial Investigation Department|Judicial Investigation Police]] were unable to immediately determine a motive for Mora's death. Lizano suspects poachers were involved, saying Mora was targeted for protecting the turtle nests.<ref name=BBC />  Chac\u00f3n said [[drug trafficker]]s, who often are also poachers, were likely behind the killing.<ref name=Tico /> Given Mora's recent calls for police help, \"it seems like it was an act of revenge\", he said.<ref name=Tico />\n\nChac\u00f3n said he was \"very hurt\" by Mora's death. \"It's not possible that citizens who protect nature have to suffer from this type of attacks\", he said.<ref name=BBC /> President [[Laura Chinchilla]] called on police and the judicial system to solve what she described as the \"despicable murder\" of Mora.<ref name=Nacion />  A statement from the [[United States Embassy in Costa Rica]] remembered Mora as \"a committed Costa Rican environmentalist\" and called his death \"senseless\".<ref name=AP />  The United Nations released a statement sending condolences and recognizing Mora's \"noble work\" to protect \"an essential part of Costa Rica's and the world's biodiversity.\"<ref name=chased />\n\nTodd Steiner, executive director of the [[Turtle Island Restoration Network]] raised money for a $10,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of those responsible.<ref name=chased /><ref>{{cite news|title=Costa Rican Turtle Defender Found Slain on the Beach He Patrolled|date=June 1, 2013|work=Dot Earth Blog|publisher=New York Times|url=http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/01/costa-rican-turtle-defender-found-slain-on-the-beach-he-patrolled/|accessdate=June 2, 2013|first=Andrew C.|last=Revkin}}</ref> \"Jairo\u2019s murderers must be brought to justice so that [people] know that this will never be tolerated,\" said Steiner in a statement. \"The whole world is watching to make sure the Costa Rican government brings these thugs to justice and makes sea turtle nesting beaches safe for conservationists to do their work.\"<ref name=chased />  A petition started by the [[Sea Turtle Restoration Project]] calling for swift justice generated more than 10,000 signatures within two weeks.<ref name=suspects>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica Prosecutor's Office says it has suspects in turtle conservationist murder|date=June 12, 2013|work=Tico Times|author=Lindsay Fendt|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-Prosecutor-s-Office-says-it-has-suspects-in-turtle-conservationist-murder_Wednesday-June-12-2013/|accessdate=June 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624212740/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-Prosecutor-s-Office-says-it-has-suspects-in-turtle-conservationist-murder_Wednesday-June-12-2013/|archive-date=June 24, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMora death raised fears that the country's economy would be hurt by reduced tourism, leading [[Univision]] to describe the situation as \"an internal crisis\".<ref name=ABC />  Commentary published by the ''[[Costa Rican Times]]'' alleged that the true culprits would never be found, saying whoever was blamed would be a scapegoat offered up by the drug traffickers.<ref name=CRTimes />  The government \"is happy letting the Caribbean side of Costa Rica lose all tourism\" continued the commentary by Dan Stevens. \"Maybe the group ''Sea Turtle Conservation with Guns'' should be formed to fight back.\"<ref name=CRTimes />  An editorial published by the ''[[Tico Times]]'' asked why it took a murder to get the government to act. \"Mora reached out for help before he was killed, and no one came to the rescue, no matter what political spin is put on it\", said the author.<ref name=TTeditorial>{{cite news|title=A World Environment Day in mourning |work=Tico Times |date=June 5, 2013 |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/Opinion/A-World-Environment-Day-in-mourning |accessdate=June 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608084755/http://www.ticotimes.net/Opinion/A-World-Environment-Day-in-mourning |archivedate=June 8, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>  Mora's death, suggested the author, shows that \"the drug traffickers are winning\", that crime is out of control in Lim\u00f3n, and that \"the bad guys operate with near impunity.\"<ref name=TTeditorial />  The editorial concluded by imploring Costa Ricans to re-evaluate their personal environmental habits and support environmental groups that keep fighting.<ref name=TTeditorial />  The Gu\u00e1piles Biofestival, an arts festival held each year during early June, was also dedicated to Mora.<ref>{{cite news|title=Festival de arte en Gu\u00e1piles recuerda labor ambiental de Jairo Mora|trans-title=Gu\u00e1piles art festival remembers the environmental work of Jairo Mora|date=June 9, 2013|work=CR Hoy|author=Jimena Soto|url=http://www.crhoy.com/festival-de-arte-en-guapiles-recuerda-labor-ambiental-de-jairo-mora/|accessdate=June 30, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, Vice President [[Alfio Piva]] described Mora's death as an \"accident\" due to Lim\u00f3n's high crime rate on live TV.<ref name=promises />  He quickly retracted the statement, saying his words had been misunderstood.<ref name=captura /> \"I only meant to recognize that the area where this happened unfortunately has a high murder rate and that there is high risk when working in an area where there is drug trafficking\", he explained.<ref name=promises />  Unsatisfied by the explanation, environmental groups called for a public apology.<ref name=promises />  On June 4, members of the Legislative Assembly said that Piva's comments had \"dishonored the entire country\".<ref name=Diputados>{{cite news|title=Diputados responsabilizan al Ejecutivo de asesinato de Jairo Mora; ecologistas y legisladores piden renuncia de Alfio Piva|trans-title=Deputies blame the Executive for murder of Jairo Mora; environmentalists and lawmakers ask for the resignation of Alfio Piva|work=CR Hoy|author=Jimena Soto|date=June 4, 2013|url=http://www.crhoy.com/diputados-responsabilizan-al-ejecutivo-de-asesinato-de-jairo-mora-y-piden-renuncia-de-alfio-piva/|accessdate=June 30, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  Led by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Villalta]] and [[Juan Carlos Mendoza]], opposition party members called for Piva's resignation. \"We are really full of anger and annoyance. We are embarrassed as a nation\", said Mendoza.<ref name=Diputados />\n\nOn June 5, [[vigil]]s in honor of Mora were held in at least six Costa Rica cities to coincide with [[World Environment Day]]. Ecologist Federation president Mauricio \u00c1lvarez, who helped organize the vigils, said \"We are asking for justice for Jairo\u2019s murder and&nbsp;...demand a halt to the impunity that has reigned over too many threats to ecologists, farmers and indigenous groups.\"<ref name=promises /> Despite rainy weather, hundred of people showed up to carry signs, light candles, and place stuffed turtles on the beach. Leaflets blamed police and the government for Mora's death and demanded swift justice.<ref name=peaceful>{{cite news|title=In Costa Rica, a peace vigil for slain turtle conservationist Jairo Mora|work=Tico Times|date=June 5, 2013|author=Lindsay Fendt|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/In-Costa-Rica-a-peace-vigil-for-slain-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-June-05-2013|accessdate=June 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607183426/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/In-Costa-Rica-a-peace-vigil-for-slain-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-June-05-2013/|archive-date=June 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Among those in attendance were Roberto Molina, secretary general of the Environmental Ministry's labor union, and Jos\u00e9 Lino Chavez, Vice Minister of Waters and Oceans.<ref name=peaceful />\n\nOn June 6, [[Sea Shepherd Conservation Society]] founder [[Paul Watson]] offered an additional $30,000 reward for information leading to the capture of Mora's murderer.<ref name=ofrece />  He said the money would come from his personal wealth, not from Sea Shepherd, and that he had sold a vehicle to fund the reward.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paul Watson says Costa Rica is in Japan\u2019s pocket; blames Jairo Mora\u2019s death on government|work=Inside Costa Rica|date=June 27, 2013|url=http://insidecostarica.com/2013/06/27/paul-watson-says-costa-rica-is-in-japans-pocket-blames-jairo-moras-death-on-government/|accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref>  Watson's pledge, together with additional funds raised by Steiner, brought the total reward to $56,000. A separate memorial fund to assist Mora's family and continue conservation efforts in his name raised $7,000.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Global Outcry Over Murdered Sea Turtle Activist Intensifies: Reward for Information Leading to Arrest, Conviction of Killers Now $56,000|author=Todd Steiner|publisher=Center for Biological Diversity|date=June 12, 2013|url=http://www.biologicaldiversity.org/news/press_releases/2013/jairo-mora-sandoval-06-12-2013.html|accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> In early July, Costa Rican businessman [[Roy Rivera]] said he was working to raise funds to increase the information reward.<ref name=memory />\n\nWatson, who is wanted by Costa Rica for skipping [[bail]] on charges related to a 2002 incident, said Mora's death proves that his own life would be in \"great danger\" if he ever returned to Costa Rica.<ref name=ofrece>{{cite news|title=Paul Watson ofrece recompensa de $30.000 a quien d\u00e9 informaci\u00f3n del homicidio de conservacionista Jairo Mora|trans-title=Paul Watson offers $30,000 reward to whoever gives information on the murder of conservationist Jairo Mora|work=La Naci\u00f3n|date=June 6, 2013|url=http://www.nacion.com/sucesos/Paul-Watson-conservacionista-Jairo-Mora_0_1346065391.html|accessdate=June 29, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  \"The authorities were very quick to respond to Japan and issued an arrest warrant for the protection of sharks&nbsp;... however, when it comes to a horrible murder of a compassionate conservationist, the government does nothing.\"<ref name=ofrece /> Later in June, Watson announced that his organization's next boat would be named the S.S. ''Jairo Mora Sandoval''. \"We do not want the name of this courageous and passionate young man to be forgotten\", he said on Facebook.<ref name=names>{{cite news|title=Sea Shepherd's Paul Watson names new ship after slain Costa Rican turtle activist|date=June 27, 2013|work=Tico Times|author=L. Arias|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Sea-Shepherd-s-Paul-Watson-names-new-ship-after-slain-Costa-Rican-turtle-activist_Thursday-June-27-2013|accessdate=June 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701044405/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Sea-Shepherd-s-Paul-Watson-names-new-ship-after-slain-Costa-Rican-turtle-activist_Thursday-June-27-2013|archive-date=July 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, the [[Ocean Futures Society]] joined the chorus of international voices calling for swift justice. \"This crime, in the Lim\u00f3n province, has shaken the consciousnesses of many internationally,\" wrote Ruben Arviz\u00fa, the society's Latin American director.<ref name=suspects />  Arviz\u00fa said that Costa Rica should make the case a national priority.<ref name=suspects />  On June 18, Costa Rican rapper Yaco released a song entitled \"Playa Roja\" (Red Beach) about Mora. Yaco, who is known for using his songs as social commentary, released the song via social media, saying it was \"not a commercial release\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Yaco mueve las redes con tema dedicado al ambientalista Jairo Mora|trans-title=Yaco moves the networks with a song dedicated to the environmentalist Jairo Mora|date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2013|work=CR Hoy|url=http://www.crhoy.com/yaco-mueve-las-redes-con-tema-dedicado-al-ambientalista-jairo-mora/|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nAt the June 26\u201328 Inter-American Convention on the Protection and Conservation of Sea Turtles (IAC), Mora's death was a popular subject. A declaration from the Mexican delegation read, \"As sea turtles are a shared resource, criminal activity that prevents [on-site] protection efforts from taking place in one country presents an urgent concern to all range states.\"<ref name=another>{{cite news|title=Another meeting, yet no news on investigation into turtle conservationist Jairo Mora's murder|author=Lindsay Fendt|work=Tico Times|date=July 2, 2013|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Another-meeting-yet-no-news-on-investigation-into-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-s-murder-_Tuesday-July-02-2013|accessdate=July 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707134719/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Another-meeting-yet-no-news-on-investigation-into-turtle-conservationist-Jairo-Mora-s-murder-_Tuesday-July-02-2013|archive-date=July 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>  A convention floor speech and a second written declaration also discussed Mora's death.<ref name=another />\n\n==Aftermath==\nFollowing Mora's death, WIDECAST suspended beach patrol operations.<ref name=AP />  \"We can\u2019t risk human lives for this project,\" Chac\u00f3n said. \"But this is probably the exact result that the killers were hoping for.\"<ref name=Tico />  Many volunteers quit the project after Mora's death, leaving the organization 200 people short staffed.<ref name=chased />  Organizations such as WIDECAST depend heavily on foreign volunteers. According to Chac\u00f3n, the future of his organization will be in jeopardy if the situation continues.<ref name=NewSci>{{cite news|title=Turtle conservationist murdered in Costa Rica|author=Peter Aldhous|date=June 3, 2013|work=New Scientist|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23639-turtle-conservationist-murdered-in-costa-rica.html|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> Aimee Leslie, who oversees sea turtle efforts for the [[World Wildlife Foundation]] called the situation \"a critical point for conservation\" in Costa Rica and \"a national security issue.<ref name=ABC />  She said that conservation efforts were already difficult without being scared for one's life.<ref name=ABC /> Lizano said she was in negotiations with the police for armed escorts on future patrols, but vowed to continue to work even if they refused. \"If we forget about this beach, then Jairo died for nothing,\" she said.<ref name=chased />\n\nOn June 3, Calder\u00f3n remarked that police would continue to support environmentalists and increase their presence on Mo\u00edn Beach.<ref name=captura>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00eda captura a hueveros armados en playa Mo\u00edn|trans-title=Police capture armed poachers on Mo\u00edn Beach|author=Diego Bosque G.|date=June 4, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-04/Portada/Policia-captura-a-hueveros-armados-en-playa-Moin.aspx|accessdate=June 5, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  The next day police arrested two armed men who were allegedly trying to steal turtle eggs from the same beach where Mora was killed. Also on June 4, a group of three men and a minor was arrested on similar charges.<ref name=captura />  Subsequently, Lim\u00f3n began to dispatch twenty police officers nightly to escort conservationists and patrol the beaches. In spite of increased police presence Lizano remarked, on June 11, \"Every night all of the [turtle] nests are raided. It is still pretty much the same even though we walk with police.\"<ref name=still_no>{{cite news|title=Still no arrests in slaying of Costa Rican conservationist |author=Lindsay Fendt |work=Tico Times |date=June 11, 2013 |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Still-no-arrests-in-slaying-of-Costa-Rican-conservationist_Tuesday-June-11-2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627032427/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Still-no-arrests-in-slaying-of-Costa-Rican-conservationist_Tuesday-June-11-2013 |archivedate=June 27, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nPrompted by the death of Mora, dozens of environmentalists met with the [[Ministry of Environment, Energy and Telecommunications]] (MINAE), headed by [[Ren\u00e9 Castro]], to discuss their dissatisfaction with current conservation efforts on June 4. Their requests included punishing those responsible for Mora's death, greater criminal penalties for poaching, and more efforts by MINAE to fight egg poachers.<ref name=celebracion />  Castro suggested implementing a plan submitted by WIDECAST. The plan would give park rangers jurisdiction to arrest poachers on Mo\u00edn Beach and create a code of conduct for beach visitors nationwide. It would also increase penalties for poaching, name a new protected area after Mora, and set up a memorial fund in his name.<ref name=promises>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica's environment minister promises action in wake of conservationist's murder|author=Lindsay Fendt|work=Tico Times|date=June 4, 2013|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-s-environment-minister-promises-action-in-wake-of-conservationist-s-murder-_Tuesday-June-04-2013|accessdate=July 6, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709125857/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rica-s-environment-minister-promises-action-in-wake-of-conservationist-s-murder-_Tuesday-June-04-2013/|archive-date=July 9, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The proposal was initially met with enthusiasm, but it later gave way to complaints about lax environmental enforcement nationwide. \"This isn\u2019t only happening in Mo\u00edn and this not only happening with turtle conservation,\" remarked Molina.<ref name=promises /> Deputy Minister of Security [[Celso Gamboa]], who was also in attendance, promised to increase security forces in Lim\u00f3n.<ref name=celebracion>{{cite news|title=Celebraci\u00f3n del D\u00eda Mundial del Ambiente estar\u00e1 marcada por luto, dice Defensor\u00eda|trans-title=Environmentalists call for greater protection and stronger legislation to continue its work|author=Hugo Solano|date=June 4, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/2013-06-04/AldeaGlobal/Celebracion-del-Dia-Mundial-del-Ambiente-estara-marcada-por-luto--dice-Defensoria.aspx|accessdate=June 4, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, the Legislative Assembly unanimously passed a motion to form a special committee investigating Mora's death. \"It is important to acknowledge that the death of Jairo is not only the fault of these bands of criminals, but also the fault of the state,\" remarked the motion's sponsor [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Villalta]]<ref name=still_no />  On June 19, Castro, Ch\u00e1vez, the heads of several environmental groups, and members of Mora's family, met to work out the details of the earlier proposals. After the meeting, Castro announced that [[Costa Rican col\u00f3n|\u20a1]]20 million (approximately US$40,000) would be allocated for a monument in Mora's honor in the form of either a new turtle observation area or an online tribute with video of nesting sea turtles. Castro also confirmed that the government had plans to turn Mo\u00edn Beach into a protected park. However, the plan to name the park after Mora was abandoned at the request of his family. MINAE also plans to allocate \"specialized units\" armed with equipment to protect Costa Rica's coasts from environmental threats.<ref name=designate>{{cite news|title=Officials will designate Costa Rican beach where conservationist was murdered as a protected wildlife area |author=Lindsay Fendt |work=Tico Times |date=June 19, 2013 |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Officials-will-designate-Costa-Rican-beach-where-conservationist-was-murdered-as-a-protected-wildlife-area_Wednesday-June-19-2013/ |accessdate=June 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624172537/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Officials-will-designate-Costa-Rican-beach-where-conservationist-was-murdered-as-a-protected-wildlife-area_Wednesday-June-19-2013 |archivedate=June 24, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nTourism to Costa Rica was down sharply during the first half of June 2013. Jorge Molina, president of The Southern Caribbean Tourism Chamber, said Mora's death was affecting reservations and would likely continue to do so for several months. Aurora G\u00e1mez, who owns a [[Manzanillo Beach]] hotel, said her occupancy rate normally runs at 50% in June, but was at just 10% in the weeks after Mora's death. She said she had received cancellations that specifically cited Mora's death as a factor. [[Cahuita]] hotel owner Eddie Ryan echoed G\u00e1mez, saying he had two patrons cite Mora's death when cancelling. Restaurants, bars, tour guides, and transportation companies were also affected. Some entrepreneurs blamed WIDECAST for the lost business saying the organization was aware of the risks but continued to patrol anyway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Asesinato de Jairo Mora golpea el turismo en el Caribe sur|trans-title=Murder of Jairo Mora hits the southern Caribbean tourism|date=June 16, 2013|work=La Naci\u00f3n|url=http://www.nacion.com/sucesos/Asesinato-Jairo-Mora-turismo-Caribe_0_1348065337.html|accessdate=June 29, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, a nationwide protest was held to draw attention to a wide variety of issues. Environmental groups joined the protests, again calling for justice to be served to Mora's murderers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Several groups plan a national protest in 25 cantons next week |date=June 19, 2013 |work=Tico Times |author=L. Arias |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Several-groups-plan-a-national-protest-in-25-cantons-next-week_Wednesday-June-19-2013/ |accessdate=June 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627083944/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Several-groups-plan-a-national-protest-in-25-cantons-next-week_Wednesday-June-19-2013/ |archivedate=June 27, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, MINAE again met with more than 30 environmental groups to discuss the situation.<ref name=comision>{{cite news|title=A m\u00e1s de un mes del asesinato de Jairo Mora Ecologistas piden una 'comisi\u00f3n de la verdad'|trans-title=More than a month after the murder of Jairo Mora, ecologists call for a 'truth commission'|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=Columbia|url=http://www.columbia.co.cr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8439:a-mas-de-un-mes-del-asesinato-de-jairo-mora-ecologistas-piden-una-comision-de-la-verdad&catid=46:nacionales&Itemid=116|accessdate=July 6, 2013|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205540/http://www.columbia.co.cr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8439:a-mas-de-un-mes-del-asesinato-de-jairo-mora-ecologistas-piden-una-comision-de-la-verdad&catid=46:nacionales&Itemid=116|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Castro said that plans to make Mo\u00edn Beach a protected area were moving forward. However, he said, making the area a national park was not feasible because of the number of people living on the beach. \"A national park is too closed off for this particular beach\", he explained.<ref name=another />  Environmentalists requested that the [[Gandoca-Manzanillo Wildlife Refuge]], one of Mora's favorite places, be renamed in honor of him. The plan was endorsed by his family.<ref name=avanzan>{{cite news|title=Ambientalistas avanzan en creaci\u00f3n de \u00e1rea protegida en Mo\u00edn en honor a Jairo Mora|trans-title=Environmentalists advance in the creation of protected area in Mo\u00edn in honor of Jairo Mora|date=June 3, 2013|work=El Pais|author=Oriana Ortiz Vindas|url=http://www.elpais.cr/frontend/noticia_detalle/1/83116|accessdate=July 6, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>  They also requested the formation of a \"truth commission\" to investigate Mora's murder and eight other deaths from the past 20 years.<ref name=comision />  Government officials said they were in the process of installing radar systems across Costa Rica to detect drug trafficking and illegal fishing, and that they would launch a plan to patrol Mo\u00edn beach with the assistance of the [[Costa Rican Petroleum Refinery]] (RECOPE).<ref name=memory>{{cite news|title=In Memory of Jairo Mora: A Wildlife Refuge in Costa Rica|url=http://news.co.cr/in-memory-of-jairo-mora-a-wildlife-refuge-in-costa-rica/22722/|date=July 4, 2013|work=Costa Rica Star|author=Jaime Lopez|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=avanzan />  MINAE said that \u20a130 million (US$60,000) had been allocated for Mora's memorial and environmental education done in his name.<ref name=avanzan />\n\nAs of July 4, no arrests had been made in relation to the murder of Mora. Ministries of Public Safety Vice Minister Celso Gamboa called the investigation ongoing.<ref name=memory />  In mid-June, Castro had said the investigation was proceeding well and he had \"every reason to be optimistic that we will solve this crime.\"<ref name=designate />  On July 10, the prosecutor's office said two suspects had been identified and that the case would \"advance significantly\" over the coming week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Costa Rican chief prosecutor: Investigators have identified two suspects in slaying of conservationist Jairo Mora|work=Tico Times|date=July 10, 2013|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rican-chief-prosecutor-Investigators-have-identified-two-suspects-in-slaying-of-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-July-10-2013|accessdate=July 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130713160842/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/Costa-Rican-chief-prosecutor-Investigators-have-identified-two-suspects-in-slaying-of-conservationist-Jairo-Mora_Wednesday-July-10-2013|archive-date=July 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, Costa Rican police raided several locations near [[Tortuguero, Costa Rica#Mo\u00edn|Mo\u00edn]] and the city of [[Lim\u00f3n]], and arrested several suspects believed to be involved in Mora's murder, as well as other crimes, including robbery and turtle egg poaching. Police said that more arrests are expected.<ref name=ticotimesmora>{{cite web|last=Fendt |first=Lindsay |title=Costa Rican police sweep nets several suspects in Jairo Mora murder case |url=http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/BREAKING-Costa-Rican-police-sweep-nets-several-suspects-in-Jairo-Mora-murder-case_Wednesday-July-31-2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130731164819/http://www.ticotimes.net/More-news/News-Briefs/BREAKING-Costa-Rican-police-sweep-nets-several-suspects-in-Jairo-Mora-murder-case_Wednesday-July-31-2013 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2013 |work=The Tico Times |accessdate=July 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe first trial of the alleged perpetrators ended in a mistrial and a second trial was held in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2015/01/29/united-nations-environmental-groups-condemn-verdict-in-jairo-mora-murder-case|title=United Nations, environmental groups condemn verdict in Jairo Mora murder case|work=The Tico Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2015/08/05/costa-rican-appeals-court-calls-re-trial-jairo-mora-murder-case|title=Murder of Costa Rican conservationist Jairo Mora headed for retrial|work=The Tico Times}}</ref> In January 2016, a court found seven men accused of Mora's murder not guilty based on reasonable doubt.  Four of the men were, however, sentenced to lengthy prison terms assault, kidnapping and aggravated robbery for a crime that occurred on the same beach shortly before Mora's murder.  (Donald Salm\u00f3n: 27 years in prison for aggravated robbery, rape and kidnapping; H\u00e9ctor Cash: 23 years for aggravated robbery, kidnapping and sexual abuse; Jos\u00e9 Bryan Delgado: 17 years for aggravated robbery and kidnapping; Ernesto Centeno: 17 years for aggravated robbery and kidnapping.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2015/01/26/not-guilty-7-men-acquitted-of-murder-of-costa-rica-sea-turtle-conservationist-jairo-mora|title=NOT GUILTY: 7 men acquitted of murder of Costa Rica sea turtle conservationist Jairo Mora|work=The Tico Times}}</ref> Subsequently, the not guilty verdict was overturned on appeal and the four men were convicted of Mora's murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2016/03/29/4-convicted-jairo-mora-murder-trial|title=4 convicted, 3 acquitted in Jairo Mora murder trial|work=The Tico Times}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2016, the Marine Section of the [[Society for Conservation Biology]] (SCB Marine) announced the \"Jairo Mora Sandoval Bravery Award.\" The award is for bravery associated with an outstanding contribution to the field of marine conservation, with particular emphasis on responsible and educated scientific endeavor, public engagement and conservation activism. The initiative to honor Jairo's commitment to marine conservation was instigated by the SCB Marine Policy Committee, and includes a $1,000 financial component.\n\nIt is given biennially and the winner is announced at the International Marine Conservation Congress (IMCC). The 2018 Awardee will be announced at IMCC5, that will be held in Kuching (Malaysia) in June 24\u201329. The inaugural Award was given, posthumously to Jairo Mora Sandoval at the 2016 IMCC in St Johns, Newfoundland, Canada, with his mother receiving the funds to set up an NGO to continue his work to protect the sea turtles of Costa Rica.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.crhoy.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/DSCF5078.jpg Photo] of the crime scene\n* [http://www.biologicaldiversity.org/news/press_releases/2013/jairo-mora-sandoval-06-03-2013.html Press release] on a reward fund\n* [https://conbio.org/mini-sites/jairoaward/ Jairo Award] offered by the Marine Section of the Society for Conservation Biology.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandoval, Jairo Mora}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lim\u00f3n Province]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Murdered animal activists]]\n[[Category:Environmental killings]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:2013 crimes in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:2013 murders in North America]]\n", "name_user": "Edigodiuss", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_of_Jairo_Mora_Sandoval"}
{"title_page": "Peyton List (actress, born 1998)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American actress and model}}\n{{For|the actress from ''[[FlashForward]]'' and ''[[Mad Men]]''|Peyton List (actress, born 1986<!--This refers to another actress - please don't change the year-->)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peyton List\n| image              = Peyton Roi List.JPG\n| alt                = Portrait image of Peyton List\n| caption            = List in 2013\n| birth_name         = Peyton Roi List\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1998|4|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Florida]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actress\n* model\n<!-- Please DO NOT list \"singer\" unless/until she meets the notability guidelines for that, per WP:NSINGER -->\n}}\n| years_active       = 2002\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[Spencer List]] (twin brother)\n}}\n\n'''Peyton Roi List'''<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/peyton-roi-list-58405847/ |title=Peyton Roi List |website=Hollywood.com |accessdate=June 15, 2018 |archivedate=August 14, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814164943/http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/peyton-roi-list-58405847/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> (born April 6, 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900077&type=list|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616173906/http://www.disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900077&type=list|title=Peyton List|work=[[Disney Channel]]|archivedate=June 16, 2012|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref>) is an American actress and model. List began her career as a child model, modeling for [[tween]] magazines and companies. She made her acting debut with the film ''[[27 Dresses]]'' (2008), and soon became recognized for playing [[Greg Heffley#Holly Hills|Holly Hills]] in the [[Diary of a Wimpy Kid (film series)|''Diary of a Wimpy Kid'' film series]]. \n\nList rose to international attention for portraying Emma Ross on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' (2011\u20132015), the eldest of four siblings that are being cared for by a young nanny, a role which she reprised in the spinoff series ''[[Bunk'd]]'' (2015\u20132018). She has since starred as Olivia Richmond on the [[Hulu]] [[web series]] [[Light as a Feather (TV series)|''Light as a Feather'']] (2018), and portrayed [[List of The Karate Kid characters#Tory|Tory]] in the [[YouTube Premium]] series ''[[Cobra Kai]]'' (2019). \n\nList's other works in film include starring in [[Remember Me (2010 film)|''Remember Me'']] (2010), [[The Sorcerer's Apprentice (2010 film)|''The Sorcerer's Apprentice'']] (2010), [[Bereavement (film)|''Bereavement'']] (2010), [[Something Borrowed (film)|''Something Borrowed'']] (2011), ''[[The Seventh Dwarf]]'' (2014), ''[[The Thinning]]'' (2016), [[The Outcasts (2017 film)|''The Outcasts'']] (2017), and ''[[The Thinning: New World Order]]'' (2018). List has also appeared in the [[Television film|television films]] ''[[Secrets in the Walls]]'' (2010) and [[The Swap (2016 film)|''The Swap'']] (2016).\n\n==Early life==\nList was born April 6, 1998.<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\"/> She has two brothers, her twin [[Spencer List|Spencer]],<ref name=TribuneChronicle>{{cite web|first = Andy | last = Gray | newspaper = [[Tribune Chronicle]] |url=http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/554977/Peyton-List-is-no-wimpy-kid.html|title=Peyton List is no wimpy kid | location = Warren, Ohio |date=March 28, 2011 |accessdate=June 15, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712143223/http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/554977/Peyton-List-is-no-wimpy-kid.html|archivedate=July 12, 2015|url-status=dead|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and a younger brother,<ref name=TeenVogue>Keiser, Amanda. [http://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/peyton-list-room-makeover#7 \"Peyton List Just Got the Ultimate Room Makeover and We Have the Exclusive First Look!\"]. ''[[Teen Vogue]]''. Retrieved May 2, 2017.</ref> Phoenix, both of whom are actors.<ref name=TribuneChronicle/>\n\nShe attended The Carroll School (P.S. 58) for elementary school, and the New Voices School for Academic and Creative Arts (M.S. 443) for middle school, both in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lo|first1=Danica|title=Peyton List's Favorite New York City Hotspots|url=http://www.epicurious.com/archive/blogs/editor/2014/07/peyton-list-new-york-city.html|website=The Epicurious Blog|publisher=Conde Nast|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> She attended [[Oak Park High School (California)|Oak Park High School]] in [[Oak Park, California]], where she graduated in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kowalski|first1=Kristine Hope|title=Class of 2016: Spencer and Peyton List Graduate High School|url=http://www.twistmagazine.com/posts/spencer-peyton-list-graduate-high-school-103529/photos/peyton-spencer-list-146083|website=Twist Magazine|publisher=Bauer Teen Group|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Peyton_R._List_at_27_Dresses_Premiere_1.jpg|right|thumb|Upright|List at the ''[[27 Dresses]]'' premiere in January 2008]]\nList first began her career as a child model, and in 2009 appeared on the cover of the ''[[American Girl (magazine)|American Girl]]'''s 2009 Back to School issue. In 2011, she modeled for [[Tween Brands|''Justice'' magazine]]. She had also appeared in over four hundred advertisements in various formats for various companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kontrolgirl.com/2013/03/14/introducing-the-spring-issue-of-kontrol-girl-magazine-featuring-peyton-list-mindless-behavior/|title=Introducing... The Spring Issue of Kontrol Girl Magazine Featuring Peyton List & Mindless Behavior!|date=March 14, 2013|work=Kontrol Girl magazine|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockycoastnews.blogspot.com/2012/01/meet-insider-raising-actress.html|title=Rocky Coast News: MEET INSIDER: Raising Actress & Fashionable Peyton List|last=Mills|first=David|date=January 21, 2012|work=Meet Insider&nbsp;\u2013 Rocky Coast News|location=Maine|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nList first began acting with television and film appearances. She first made an uncredited appearance on the [[soap opera]] ''[[As the World Turns]]'' in 2002.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2004, she appeared on the television show ''[[All My Children]]'' as Bess, and in the same year made a cameo appearance in the feature film ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'', which went uncredited.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2008, she appeared in the feature film ''[[27 Dresses]]'', starring as the young version of the character Jane Nichols. The film was a commercial success,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1229030913/?landingModalImageUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fm.media-amazon.com%2Fimages%2FG%2F01%2FIMDbPro%2Fimages%2Fhome%2FwelcomeToBomojov2._CB1571421611_.png|title=27 Dresses|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> and served as her acting debut. \n\nList began to appear in more feature films, and in 2010 was cast alongside [[Robert Pattinson]] in the film ''[[Remember Me (2010 film)|Remember Me]]'' as Samantha, a girl who bullies Pattinson's character's little sister. The film was a box-office success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2859304449/?landingModalImageUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fm.media-amazon.com%2Fimages%2FG%2F01%2FIMDbPro%2Fimages%2Fhome%2FwelcomeToBomojov2._CB1571421611_.png|title=Remember Me|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> In the same year, List had begun her work with [[Disney]], and appeared as the younger version of Becky in the [[fantasy]] film ''[[The Sorcerer's Apprentice (2010 film)|The Sorcerer's Apprentice]]'', which turned to be a financial failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2540733953/?landingModalImageUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fm.media-amazon.com%2Fimages%2FG%2F01%2FIMDbPro%2Fimages%2Fhome%2FwelcomeToBomojov2._CB1571421611_.png|title=The Sorcerer's Apprentice|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> She also was cast in the [[Lifetime Movie Network|Lifetime]] [[television film]] ''[[Secrets in the Walls]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediamikes.com/2011/09/dvd-review-secrets-in-the-walls/|title=DVD Review \"Secrets in the Walls\"|date=September 11, 2011|website=MediaMikes|language=en-US|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and played Wendy Miller in the [[Crime fiction|crime]] [[Horror film|horror]] film [[Bereavement (film)|Bereavement]], which was a [[Box office|box-office]] success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2554627585/|title=Bereavement|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, List starred as [[List of Diary of a Wimpy Kid characters|Holly Hills]], the crush of [[Greg Heffley]], in the [[comedy]] film ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules]]'', the second installment of the [[Diary of a Wimpy Kid (film series)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid film series]]. The film performed well commercially,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/article/ed3531342852/|title=Weekend Report: 'Wimpy Kid' Blindsides 'Sucker Punch'|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and List later reprised her role for its sequel, ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days]]''. The film was a success alike to its prequels, and the acting ensemble, including List, had won a [[Young Artist Award]].<ref name=\"YoungArtistAwards_3\" /> List next had a role in the [[romantic comedy]] film [[Something Borrowed (film)|''Something Borrowed'']] in 2011,<ref>{{Citation|title=Something Borrowed (2011)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/something_borrowed_2011|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> which was received negatively.\n[[File:Jessie Cast.jpg|left|thumb|The cast of ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' in 2011|alt=]]In 2011, List began her work on [[Disney Channel]], and was cast as Emma Ross, the eldest of four affluent children, on the Disney Channel series ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' alongside [[Debby Ryan]] and her ''Diary of a Wimpy Kid'' co-star [[Karan Brar]]. The show attained millions of viewers on average per episode,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-25-friday-cable-originals-11-28-2014.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 25 Friday Cable Originals (& Network Update): 11.28.2014 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and soon became List's biggest role at the time. The show ran for four seasons, and ended on February 25, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/jessie-cancelled-spinoff-peyton-list-karan-brar-skai-jackson-disney-channel-1201380940/|title=Disney Channel\u2019s \u2018Jessie\u2019 Ending Run, But Spinoff Series Set With Stars Peyton List, Karan Brar & Skai Jackson|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=February 25, 2015|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> At the same time, it was announced that List, along with Brar and [[Skai Jackson]], would reprise their roles in the spinoff series ''[[Bunk'd]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/jessie-cancelled-spinoff-peyton-list-karan-brar-skai-jackson-disney-channel-1201380940/ |title=Disney Channel's 'Jessie' Ending Run, But Spinoff Series Set With Stars Peyton List, Karan Brar & Skai Jackson |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 25, 2015 |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/jessie-ending-debby-ryan-peyton-list-spinoff|title=Exclusive! 'Jessie' Is Ending, but Don't Worry\u2014There's a Spin-off Series on the Way|last=Firman|first=Tehrene|website=Teen Vogue|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The show began airing in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2015/04/24/jessie-spinoff-bunkd-peyton-list-skai-jackson-karan-brar/|title=Disney Channel's Jessie Spinoff Gets Title, Premise, Cast Additions|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|last2=Mitovich|first2=Matt Webb|date=April 24, 2015|website=TVLine|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Along with reprising the role on Bunk'd, she also had appeared as Emma Ross on other Disney Channel shows, such as [[Austin & Ally|''Austin & All''y]] and [[I Didn't Do It (TV series)|''I Didn't Do It'']].\n\nAlong with her television work, List continued her work in films. In 2012, she appeared in the [[drama]] film ''[[The Trouble with Cali]]'', which was received negatively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nepascene.com/2015/07/movie-review-trouble-with-cali-awful-people-say-why-should-see-it/|title=MOVIE REVIEW: 'The Trouble with Cali' is as awful as people say - which is why you should see it|date=July 10, 2015|website=NEPA Scene|language=en-US|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> From 2013 to 2014, she co-hosted the Disney Channel program ''[[Pass the Plate]]'', a segment focusing on healthy eating,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810224246/http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=3114203&type=lead|title=Disney Channel Medianet|date=August 10, 2011|website=web.archive.org|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> with Karan Brar. In 2014, she voiced Princess Rose in the English dub of the German [[Animation|animated]] film ''[[The Seventh Dwarf]]''. Though the film was a moderate financial success,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2914892/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=The Seventh Dwarf|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> it was received unfavorably by critics.<ref>{{Citation|last=Filmstarts|title=Die Filmstarts-Kritik zu Der 7bte Zwerg|url=http://www.filmstarts.de/kritiken/208559/kritik.html|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In 2015, List performed with [[Ingrid Michaelson]] at one of Michaelson's concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/hot-pics/those-pants-tho-2015126|title=Hot Pics!-Those Pants Tho!|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> \n[[File:10.8.16PeytonListByLuigiNovi1.jpg|thumb|List in 2016]]\nIn 2016, List co-starred along with [[Jacob Bertrand]] in the [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] [[The Swap (2016 film)|''The Swap'']], appearing as Ellie O'Brien.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/disney-channel-original-movie-the-swap-dcom-marathon-1201741163/|title=Disney Channel Original Movie \u2018The Swap\u2019 Set As Network Plans 100-Pic Celebration|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|date=April 20, 2016|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The premiere averaged over two million viewers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-7-2016.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Friday Cable Originals\u00a0& Network Finals: 10.7.2016 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and had a mixed reception. In the same year, she appeared as Laina Michaels in the [[YouTube Premium]] film ''[[The Thinning]]'', starring alongside [[Logan Paul]] and [[Lia Marie Johnson]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2017, List appeared in the teen comedy film [[The Outcasts (2017 film)|''The Outcasts'']] as Mackenzie Smith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/cannes-victoria-justice-starring-in-high-school-comedy-1201180198/|title=CANNES: Victoria Justice Starring in High-School Comedy|last=McNary|first=Dave|last2=McNary|first2=Dave|date=May 14, 2014|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Production had initially began in 2014 under its original title ''The Outskirts'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809200534/http://www.disneydreaming.com/2014/07/06/madness-on-the-set-of-victoria-justice-and-eden-shers-movie-the-outskirts/|title=Madness On The Set Of Victoria Justice and Eden Sher\u2019s Movie \u201cThe Outskirts\u201d {{!}} Disney Dreaming|date=August 9, 2014|website=web.archive.org|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and was not released until three years later. It was originally released [[direct-to-video]], but was eventually picked up for a theatrical release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/swen-group-distribution-victoria-justice-outcasts-exclusive-1202004189/|title=Swen Group Moves Into U.S. Distribution With Victoria Justice\u2019s \u2018Outcasts\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=McNary|first=Dave|last2=McNary|first2=Dave|date=March 8, 2017|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The film was commercially unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=outskirts2015.htm|title=Box Office Mojo|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was announced that List would leave the show, and depart from her work on Disney Channel entirely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/will-smith-jada-pinkett-smith-dominate-top-actors-social-media-ranking-1138669/item/priyanka-chopra-mvp-9-5-1138571|title=6. Priyanka Chopra - Will Smith, Jada Pinkett Smith Dominate Top Actors Social Media Ranking|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2019/07/16/why-did-peyton-list-leave-bunkd-season-4-disney-channel/|title=Why did Peyton List leave Bunk'd? Disney actress has more in store!|last=Weston|first=Christopher|date=July 16, 2019|website=HITC|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> When she still worked with the network, she was an active member of the [[Disney Channel Circle of Stars]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fanlala.com/news/26-disney-channel-stars-sing-do-you-want-build-snowman-frozen|title=26 Disney channel stars sing do you want build snowman frozen|date=July 18, 2014 |accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref> List reprised her role as Laina Michaels in ''[[The Thinning: New World Order]]'', the sequel to ''The Thinning'', which was released in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2018/10/18/thinning-new-world-order-youtube-surprise-launches-shamed/|title=The Telegraph|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the same year, she starred alongside [[Asa Butterfield]] in the romantic drama film [[Then Came You (2018 film)|''Then Came You'']] as Ashley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/then-came-you-trailer-asa-butterfield-maisie-williams-nina-dobrev-coming-of-age-1202520208/|title=\u2018Then Came You\u2019 Trailer: Asa Butterfield, Maisie Williams & Nina Dobrev In Coming-Of-Age Pic|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|date=December 14, 2018|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> List was soon cast in the main role of Olivia Richmond in the first season of the [[supernatural]] [[web series]] [[Light as a Feather (TV series)|''Light as a Feather'']], which was released through [[Hulu]] on October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/light-as-a-feather-cast-liana-liberato-haley-ramm-peyton-list-hulu-awesomenesstv-1202403357/|title=\u2018Light As A Feather\u2019 Cast Set: Liana Liberato, Haley Ramm, Peyton List, Others Join Hulu & AwesomenessTV Drama|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|date=June 4, 2018|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Also in 2018, she made her singing debut with the single \"Liar Liar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Actress-Peyton-List-Drops-New-Pop-Anthem-LIAR-LIAR-20181102|title=Actress Peyton List Drops New Pop Anthem LIAR LIAR|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, List voiced [[Barbara Gordon|Barbara Gordon / Batgirl]] in the direct-to-video [[superhero]] film [[Batman: Hush (film)|''Batman: Hush'']].<ref>{{Citation|title=Batman: Hush Movie - Exclusive First Look Photo and Voice Cast News - IGN|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/27/batman-hush-exclusive-first-look-photo-and-voice-cast-news|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In the same year, she was cast in the recurring role of [[List of The Karate Kid characters|Tory]] in the YouTube Premium action series ''[[Cobra Kai]]'', which she played throughout the second season. List will next appear in the [[Music genre|musical]] film [[Valley Girl (2020 film)|''Valley Girl'']], a remake of the [[Valley Girl (1983 film)|1983 film]], which is slated for release in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/valley-girl-peyton-list-mgm-1202106616/|title=MGM\u2019s \u2018Valley Girl\u2019 Remake Adds Peyton List|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|last2=N'Duka|first2=Amanda|date=June 2, 2017|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She will also have a role in the upcoming direct-to-video film ''[[Hubie Halloween]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/adam-sandler-kevin-james-julie-bowen-maya-rudolph-netflix-comedy-1202650376/|title=Adam Sandler Sets Next Netflix Comedy With All-Star Cast Including Kevin James, Julie Bowen, Maya Rudolph & Many More|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|last2=N'Duka|first2=Amanda|date=July 22, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Namefellow==\nPeyton List shares the same name with a fellow actress, [[Peyton List (actress, born 1986)|Peyton List (born 1986)]].<ref name=\"saltman\">{{cite news |last1=Laura |first1=Saltman |title=A Tale Of Two Peytons: Jessie's Peyton List On Sharing Her Famous Name With Other Peyton List |url=https://www.yahoo.com/celebrity/news/tale-two-peytons-jessies-peyton-list-sharing-her-215829849.html |accessdate=November 20, 2019 |work=Access Hollywood |publisher=Yahoo News |date=October 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207024916/https://www.yahoo.com/celebrity/news/tale-two-peytons-jessies-peyton-list-sharing-her-215829849.html |archivedate=February 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=nguyen>{{citation|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/peyton-list-frequency-swap-thinning-1201733445/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[IndieWire]]|title=Peyton List-icle: 6 Ways to Identify Which Peyton List Is Which|first=Hanh|last=Nguyen|date=October 5, 2016|quote='Peyton List is an American actress and model.' This Wikipedia description is accurate and true. The problem? It\u2019s true about two different people. That\u2019s right. Two Peyton Lists are working actresses and models. Two Peyton Lists are, um, listed on IMDb. Two Peyton Lists are currently on our TVs. Two Peyton Lists are confusing our Google searches. Two Peyton Lists are messing with our minds.}}</ref> The younger List was interviewed by ''[[Access Hollywood]]'', saying she uses '''Peyton R. List''' to avoid confusion.<ref name=saltman /> Union [[SAG-AFTRA]]'s policy avoids actors with the same name; this instance went unnoticed.<ref name=saltman/> They appeared in the same scene \u2014 when the older List starred on ''[[As the World Turns]]'' as Lucy Montgomery.<ref name=saltman /><ref name=\":1\">{{citation|url=http://heavy.com/entertainment/2016/10/peyton-list-disney-channel-star-bunkd-who-plays-emma-ross-the-swap-jessie-twin-brother-age-family-movies-photos/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|website=[[Heavy.com]]|title=Peyton List, Disney Channel Star: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|date=October 7, 2016|first=Daniel S.|last=Levine}}</ref> Years later, the younger List cited confusion when they stayed at the same hotel \u2014 they received [[daily call sheet]]s and [[voicemail]]s for each other.<ref name=saltman/> ''[[IndieWire]]'' noted the confusion appeared on the website [[Wikipedia]], where both actresses's articles started out with exactly the same introduction text of: \"Peyton List is an American actress and model.\"<ref name=nguyen/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film performances\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Spider-Man 2]]''\n| Little girl playing on steps\n| Uncredited<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cast of Disney's Jessie talk about swinging by Marvel's Ultimate Spider-Man|url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23486/the_cast_of_disneys_jessie_talk_about_swinging_by_marvels_ultimate_spider-man_web-warriors|publisher=Marvel|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[27 Dresses]]''\n| Young Jane Nichols\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Confessions of a Shopaholic (film)|Confessions of a Shopaholic]]''\n| Shoestore girl #2\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[3 Backyards]]''\n| Emily\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Remember Me (2010 film)|Remember Me]]''\n| Samantha\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''{{sortname|The|Sorcerer's Apprentice|dab=2010 film}}''\n| Young Becky\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Bereavement (film)|Bereavement]]''\n| Wendy Miller\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" | ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules]]''\n| Holly Hills\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Something Borrowed (film)|Something Borrowed]]''\n| Young Darcy Rhone\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''{{sortname|The|Trouble with Cali}}''\n| Young Cali Bluejones\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days]]''\n| Holly Hills\n| [[34th Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Award for Best Performance in a Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Young Ensemble Cast]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403013454/http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 3, 2013 |title=34th Annual Young Artist Awards \u2013 Nominations |publisher=[[Young Artist Award]]s |accessdate=February 1, 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''{{sortname|The|Seventh Dwarf}}''\n| Princess Rose\n| Voice role\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Thinning]]''\n| Laina Michaels\n| <ref name=\":2\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/logan-paul-peyton-list-the-thinning-legendary-1201643508/|title=Digital Star Logan Paul, Peyton List Topline \u2018The Thinning\u2019 Thriller from Legendary Digital (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=November 18, 2015|accessdate=February 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''{{sortname|The|Outcasts|dab=2017 film}}''\n| Mackenzie\n| Originally titled ''The Outskirts''; scheduled for a 2015 release, but held until 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/swen-group-distribution-victoria-justice-outcasts-exclusive-1202004189/|title=Swen Group Moves Into U.S. Distribution With Victoria Justice\u2019s \u2018Outcasts\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=March 8, 2017|accessdate=March 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Thinning: New World Order]]''\n| Laina Michaels\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Then Came You (2018 film)|Then Came You]]''\n| Ashley\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Batman: Hush (film)|Batman: Hush]]''\n| [[Barbara Gordon|Barbara Gordon / Batgirl]]\n| Voice role<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vejvoda |first1=Jim |title=Batman: Hush Movie - Exclusive First Look Photo and Voice Cast News |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/27/batman-hush-exclusive-first-look-photo-and-voice-cast-news |website=[[IGN]] |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Valley Girl (2020 film)|Valley Girl]]''\n| Courtney\n|Upcoming film<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/valley-girl-peyton-list-mgm-1202106616/|title=MGM\u2019s \u2018Valley Girl\u2019 Remake Adds Peyton List|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|last2=N'Duka|first2=Amanda|date=June 2, 2017|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wildaboutmovies.com/2020_movies/valley-girl/|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</r