g of the life and bearing of the mountaineer. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Post Nov 1932\">{{cite news |title=Marin Paintings and Water Colors |author= |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-09 |page=3 |quote=At the Morton Galleries Dorothy Eisner is holding an exhibition of paintings. She is a young artist who has apparently a considerable command of technical facility and the ability to develop a subject freshly and spontaneously, as her painting, \"The Hammock,\" attests. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Sun Nov 1932\">{{cite news |title=Art Displays in Varied Mood |author= |work=New York Sun |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-17 |page= |quote=As social documents, revelations of the life somewhere in the southern mountains, several of the canvases that Dorothy Eisner is showing at the Morton Galleries are vastly entertaining. \"Bird in Buzzard Out\" and the \"Fiddlers' Convention,\" for example. As paintings, \"Curley,\" \"The Hammock\" and the \"Cider Press\" seem to present the young artist at her not too accomplished best. When it comes to that \"Self-Portrait\" one is left in some doubt whether modesty or humor prompted it. Something could be said for either point of view. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 21 1932\">{{cite news |title=Art: Two Important Shows |author=T.C.L. |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-21 |page=26 |quote=In the canvases at her first one-man show at the Morton Galleries, Dorothy Eisner is portraying some aspects of life in the Southern mountain region of this country. Writers have been far in advance of artists in discovering the possibilities of subject-matter in this section. It is not the beauties of mountain landscape that have attracted Miss Eisner, but rather the individuality of people and the interest of their pastimes. A \"Fiddlers' Convention\" and a dance called \"Bird in Buzzard Out\" Miss Eisner evidently watched closely, for she caught something of the characteristic bearing of the Southern mountaineer. Individuals, too, she has portrayed in portrait studies. Although there is some authentic quality of the South in these paintings, they incline toward drabness of color, and the figures have not enough animation to make them live in paint. Most successfully realized are several still-lifes. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times May 1933\">{{cite news |title=The Etchings of Georges Rouault |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1933-05-07 |page=X8 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Oct 1933\">{{cite news |title=Henry V. Poor's Paintings |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1933-10-24 |page=19 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Dec 1933\">{{cite news |title=The Dance in Art Theme of Exhibit: College Association Offers for View 100 Examples in Various Mediums |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1933-12-13 |page=21 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Sun Mar 1934\">{{cite news |title=Attractions in Other Galleries |author= |work=New York Sun |location=New York, New York |date=1934-03-31 |page=13 |quote=Miss Eisner... paints citizens who have a good deal of the soil upon their clothes. She paints them rather roughly, but with a curious instinct for balance that makes the panels, as a whole, attractive. Her most successful improvisation is called 'Franklin's View.' It shows a man, carelessly attired, fishing in a romantic spot, but whether were a portrait of the man or of the place, could not be ascertained. Such things are unimportant anyway when you like the picture. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1934\">{{cite news |title=Seen in the Galleries: Comment on Some of the Exhibitions That Have Opened Recently in This City |author=Howard Devree |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1934-04-01 |page=X9 |quote=Two One-Woman Shows  Oils by Grace Bliss Stewart and Dorothy Eisner are on exhibition at the Delphic Studios...  Dorothy Eisner is gaining strength and sureness, as her Carolina canvases attest. These seem more original and suggest that the artist was more interested in them than in her New York pictures. Her mountain people are convincingly delineated. She makes excellent use of warm reds, in a palette generally low. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Post Jan 1936\">{{cite news |title=O'Keeffe Works Highly Spirited |author= |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1936-01-11 |page=2 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jan 1937\">{{cite news |title=Giotto 600 Years After |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1937-01-17 |page=161 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1937\">{{cite news |title=American Artists Congress |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1937-04-25 |page=171 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Post Feb 1938\">{{cite news |title=Women Artists in Annual Show at Grant Studio |author= |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1938-02-05 |page=30 |quote=Dorothy Eisner has made quite a thing of a 'North Carolina Dough Board.' Its strength of design and color in large scale execution, make it the outstanding canvas of the show. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1938\">{{cite news |title=Moritz Eisner, 84, a Retired Chemist |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1938-06-20 |page=15 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1940\">{{cite news |title=News and Notes of Art |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1940-06-19 |page=21 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times May 1942\">{{cite news |title=Exhibition is Held by Art Federation; Modern Painters and Sculptors Have Large Display at Their Second Annual Show |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1942-05-22 |page=24 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Dec 1954\">{{cite news |title=Woodstock |author= |work=Kingston Daily Freeman |location=Kingston, New York |date=1954-12-15 |page=5 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Jun 1956\">{{cite news |title=The Putnam Story |author=Max Lerner |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1956-06-24 |page=8 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Feb 1961\">{{cite news |title=Art Openings in the Galleries |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1960-02-12 |page=X20 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Aug 1961\">{{cite news |title=Do You Remember |author=Sophie Miller |work=Kingston Daily Freeman |location=Kingston, New York |date=1961-08-30 |page=12 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 1966\">{{cite news |title=What's New in Art: In the Museums Lectures |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1961-11-27 |page=D18 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1969\">{{cite news |title=Display ad: Cisneros Gallery |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1969-04-06 |page=D26 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Sep 1982\">{{cite news |title=Jack Tworkov, Painter And Art Teacher, Dead |author=Michael Brenson |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1982-09-06 |page=32 |quote=Like others of his generation, however, Mr. Tworkov never accepted the idea of pure abstraction. 'I'm trying to make an analogy to the figure,' he said. Mr. Tworkov believed what the next generation of abstract painters would fight against tooth and nail: 'Every painter has a subject whether or not there are objects in his paintings.' }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Boston Globe Nov 2002\">{{cite news |title=Author Tells How He Took on Goliath GM and Won |author=Rich Barlow |work=Boston Globe |location=Boston, Massachusetts |date=2002-11-17 |page=H2 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Portland Press Herald Oct 2008\">{{cite news |title=Shows at Saco Museum, Ogunquit Museum of American Art |author=Bob Keyes |work=Portland Press Herald |location=Portland, Maine |date=2008-10-19 |page=C6 |quote= Her canvases are fluid, orderly and distinct. She painted whatever came before her, be it a horse, a stack of fishing gear, a desk and chair, or even something as mundane as a game of croquet. But she painted with great spirit, and the work on display in Ogunquit seems to express her personality: bold colors, quick strokes and a certain sense of place. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bangor Daily News Mar 2009\">{{cite news |title=Inspiring Isles; Portland Museum of Art highlights the Diversity of a Creative Crew from Maine's Cranberry Isles |author=Jessica Bloch |work=Bangor Daily News |location=Bangor, Maine |date=2009-03-20 |page=7 |quote=In 'Desk II,' Eisner painted an orange desk with a boat schedule, an August calendar, a list of names including Heliker, LaHotan and Kienbusch, and a big black phone prominently displayed &mdash; as if she\u2019s about to invite friends or plan her next party. We get a clue about what that party might have been like in 'Croquet and Hats,' with a line of croquet mallets, balls and a straw hat, awaiting the next round of lawn games. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Boothbay Register May 2017\">{{cite news |title=Dorothy Eisner show at Gleason Fine Art |author=Marty Gleason |work=Boothbay Register |location=Boothbay Harbor, Maine |date=2017-05-24 |page= |url=https://www.boothbayregister.com/article/dorothy-eisner-show-gleason-fine-art/86670 |accessdate=2020-04-15 |quote=Dorothy Eisner's artistic career spanned seven decades. From her Greenwich Village studio, she traveled widely, including to the American West, Mexico, and Europe. However, it was her discovery in 1960 of Cranberry Island, an enchanting small island off Mount Desert and its vibrant community of artists, that was the beginning of Eisner's passion for Maine \u2013 a passion that lasted for 24 summers, until the very end of her life. Eisner relished involving herself in the local art scene. In New York, she exhibited broadly and worked tirelessly to further the careers of her fellow artists. Eisner's time on Cranberry was no different. She befriended and worked with many artists, including William Kienbusch, Carl Nelson, and John Heliker, all of whom summered on Cranberry Island. }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisner, Dorothy}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Women painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Infobox artist| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Dorothy Eisner\n| honorific_suffix =\n| native_name      =\n| native_name_lang =\n| image            =1937PhotoWithTrotskyAndPortrait.jpg\n| image_size       =\n| alt              =Dorothy Eisner and Leon Trotsky\n| caption          =1937 photo of Dorothy Eisner and Leon Trotsky with her portrait of him\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1906|01|17}}\n| birth_place      = New York\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1984|04|28|1906|01|17}}\n| death_place      = [[Pikesville, Maryland]]\n| resting_place    = Baltimore Hebrew Cemetery\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nationality      = U. S. citizen\n| spouse           = \n| known_for        = Artist\n| field            =\n| training         =\n| alma_mater       = \n| movement         =\n| works            =\n| patrons          =\n| awards           =\n| memorials        =\n| elected          =\n| website          =\n| module           =\n}}\n'''Dorothy Eisner''' (1906&ndash;1984) was an American artist whose painting style evolved over many years from an early, quite personal, version of 1930s [[social realism]], through a period of [[abstract expressionism]], and culminating over the last twenty years of her life in a bright painterly style that critics saw as fluid, masterfully composed, and expressionistic.<ref name=\"Ogunquit Museum 2008\"/><ref name=\"New England Today Jan 2009\"/> Throughout her long career Eisner maintained a consistency that a gallerist summarized as derived from European modernism but also grounded in American painting of her own generation and the generation before her.<ref name=\"Gleason Fine Art\"/> Born and raised in [[Manhattan]], she traveled widely and is best known for the late work she made while staying in a summer home off the coast of Maine on [[Great Cranberry Island]].\n\n==Early life and training==\n\nEisner was born and educated in New York City. As a child, she won local children's drawing contests and in her teens attended a school, [[Ethical Culture Fieldston School|Ethical Culture High School]], known for its arts instruction.<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art Mar 2005\"/> Between 1924 and 1929 she studied at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]] where she worked under [[Kenneth Hayes Miller]], [[Boardman Robinson]], and [[Thomas Hart Benton (painter)|Thomas Hart Benton]].<ref name=\"Harvard Review 2006\"/> During the summer months she traveled to Europe and during one of these trips studied at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] in Paris.<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art Mar 2005\"/> She had one additional period of training in the late 1940s when she learned techniques of abstraction and expressionism from [[Jack Tworkov]].<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/>\n\n==Career in art==\n\nWhen she was not traveling, Eisner lived in [[Greenwich Village]] and rented a studio on Cornelia Street.<ref name=\"Harvard Review 2006\"/><ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> In 1930 she contributed a still life in a group show at the Opportunity Gallery that also included works by [[Edith Hamlin]].<ref name=\"New York Times Jan 1930\"/>{{refn|group=note|A group of collectors along with the artist Gifford Beal set up the nonprofit Opportunity Gallery in the fall of 1927.<ref name=\"Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life\"/> Each exhibition was selected by a well-known artist with the overall goal of showing new talent in a wide range of artistic styles.<ref name=\"Brooklyn Daily Eagle Nov 1927\"/> [[Mark Rothko]], [[Milton Avery]], [[Adolph Gottlieb]], and [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] all showed at the gallery during its early years.<ref name=\"The Opportunity Gallery\"/> }} Throughout the rest of the decade her paintings appeared frequently in shows held by nonprofit organizations, including Salons of America (1931, 1932, 1933), the [[Society of Independent Artists]] (1932, 1933, 1935, 1936, 1937), the [[College Art Association]] (traveling exhibitions in 1932 and 1933), the [[National Association of Women Artists|National Association of Women Painters and Sculptors]] (annually, 1933 to 1939), the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]] (1934), and the [[New York Society of Women Artists]] (1935, 1936, 1938).<ref name=\"AskArt Dorothy Eisner\"/><ref name=\"New York Times May 1933\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Oct 1933\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Dec 1933\"/>{{refn|group=note|In 1922 [[Hamilton Easter Field]] founded Salons of America to give artists an alternative to the Society of Independent Artists whose financial and publicity methods he found objectionable. A reporter said he aimed \"to give equal opportunity to every member, whether he or she be a conservative or a post-Dadaist.\"<ref name=\"New York Times Jul 1922\"/>}} In these large shows Eisner's paintings were regularly singled out for praise by New York critics. Thus, for example, in 1936 the ''New York Post'' critic noted her \"thorough and vigorous\" canvases.<ref name=\"New York Post Jan 1936\"/> In 1937 Edward Alden Jewell of the ''Times'' called attention to her free brushwork.<ref name=\"New York Times Jan 1937\"/> In 1938, a ''Post'' critic called one of her paintings \"the outstanding canvas of the show.\"<ref name=\"New York Post Feb 1938\"/>\n\nIn 1932 the Morton Gallery mounted her first solo exhibition. In it, she showed paintings depicting life in the mountains of the [[Carolinas]].<ref name=\"New York Sun Mar 1934\"/> Critics responded favorably to the show. A review in the ''New York Post'' said she had technical facility and showed her subjects freshly and spontaneously.<ref name=\"New York Post Nov 1932\"/> Writing in the ''New York Sun'', a critic wrote that the paintings were social documents that revealed life in the southern mountains in a way that was \"vastly entertaining.\"<ref name=\"New York Sun Nov 1932\"/> A critic for the ''New York Times'' noticed that Eisner showed more interest in the people she encountered than in the scenic environment in which they passed their lives and concluded that \"she caught something of the characteristic bearing of the Southern mountaineer.\"<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 1932\"/>  Her depiction of a fiddler drew attention in both the ''Sun'' and the ''Times''. Late in life, a contemporary of Eisner's, [[Joseph Solman]], said of the [[Social realism|social realist]] style of the time: \"We were all seeking the flat, and the exaggerated, and the expressionist in our own romantic, different ways.\"<ref name=\"Adoph Gottlieb 1995\"/>\n\nTwo years later the Delphic Studio gave Eisner and Grace Bliss Stewart a duo exhibition. On this occasion the ''New York Sun'' featured a photo of another Carolina mountains painting, \"Franklin's View.\"<ref name=\"New York Sun Mar 1934\"/>{{refn|group=note|Journalist and art patron [[Alma Reed]] founded Delphic Studios in 1929. Mainly known for its emphasis on Mexican art, the gallery also showed photographers, such as [[Edward Weston]] and [[Ansel Adams]] as well as Eisner and other contemporary American artists.<ref name=\"Delphic Studio\"/> }} The ''Sun'''s critic, who found her work to be on the whole \"attractive,\" used the label \"communist\" as shorthand for Eisner's social realist style in her mountain paintings. The critic said, \"[she] paints citizens who have a good deal of the soil upon their clothes.\"<ref name=\"New York Sun Mar 1934\"/> Howard Devree of the ''New York Times'' said the paintings showed increased strength and sureness and praised her use of warm reds in a generally low palette.<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1934\"/>\n\n[[File:1937DeweyCommission.jpg|left|thumb|Dorothy Eisner, Dewey Commission, 1937, oil on canvas, 25 x 30 inches]]\nIn the late 1930s Eisner exhibited as a member of a [[popular front]] organization called the [[American Artists' Congress]].<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1937\"/> After the [[Winter War|Soviet invasion of Finland]] in 1940 she and a small group of like-minded artists quit the Congress to found an avowedly non-political organization called the Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors.<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1940\"/><ref name=\"Federation of modern painters and sculptors 2018\"/>{{refn|group=note|A group of New York artists formed the Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors in the spring of 1940. All had resigned from the American Artists' Congress to protest its \"Stalinist line\" after the congress had endorsed the [[Winter War|Soviet invasion of Finland]].<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1940\"/> The federation aimed to be non-political. Its principal goal was to promote artistic independence and its members adhered to no specific style or school of painting. By means of exhibitions, publications, and lectures it set itself to promote the \"general interest of contemporary art.\" In addition to Eisner and her sister Anne, founding members included [[Isabel Bishop]], [[Ilya Bolotowsky]], [[Anne Goldthwaite]], [[Adolph Gottlieb]], [[Balcomb Greene]], and [[Mark Rothko]].<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1940\"/><ref name=\"New York Times May 1942\"/> }} In 1937 Eisner and her husband traveled to Mexico to help the [[Dewey Commission]] investigate charges leveled against [[Leon Trotsky]] by the Soviet government in the [[Moscow Trials]] of 1936\u20131937. Eisner made a painting of commission members interviewing Trotsky in a house on the outskirts of Mexico City owned by Rivera and [[Frida Kahlo]]. The painting (shown at left) contains a view of [[Diego Rivera]] who is making a sketch of the scene.<ref name=\"Trotsky Commission Painting\"/> She also made two portraits of Trotsky. The two of them joked about a time when she scraped off pigment in painting his face. He made an affectionate, albeit macabre joke that she was beheading him.<ref name=\"Harvard Review 2006\"/> This painting is shown in the photo of Trotsky and Eisner at top right.\n\nAfter World War II Eisner traveled widely with her husband. His work as a journalist for [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] magazine and his passion for fishing helped to determine the locations they visited. In 1947 they spent time on [[Cape Breton Island]] and, beginning in 1949 they started to make periodic visits to [[Livingston, Montana]].<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> Returning from Montana in the early 1950s, Eisner began a short period of study with [[Jack Tworkov]] in New York.<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art 2016\"/>{{refn|group=note|Tworkov taught art throughout much of his career. In the early 1930s he taught briefly at the [[Ethical Culture Fieldston School|Ethical Culture High School]] in Manhattan. Between 1948 and 1958 he was a part-time instructor at [[Queens College, City University of New York|Queens College]] and [[Pratt Institute]]. He was also at one time an instructor at [[Black Mountain College]] and in the 1960s taught at the [[Yale School of Art]], becoming chair of the art department in 1963.<ref name=\"Tworkov Papers AAA\"/> }} In 1960 she and her husband began spending summer months on [[Great Cranberry Island]].<ref name=\"Art of Acadia 2016\"/>\n\nDuring these years and continuing into the 1970s she continued exhibiting with the Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors.<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art 2016\"/><ref name=\"AskArt Dorothy Eisner\"/> During this period she also continued to be given solo exhibitions in New York commercial galleries. In 1961 she was given a solo exhibition at the James Gallery and in 1966 and in 1969 at the Cisneros Gallery.<ref name=\"New York Times Feb 1961\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Nov 1966\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1969\"/>\n\nAfter her death in 1984 she was given a succession of retrospective exhibitions. These included the [[Farnsworth Art Museum]] (1992, \"Dorothy Eisner: Paintings and Collages\"), Acme Fine Art (Boston, 2005, \"Late Expressionist Paintings,\" and 2009, \"Dorothy Eisner on Cranberry Island\"), [[Ogunquit Museum of American Art|Ogunquit Museum]] (2008, Cranberry Island paintings), and Gleason Fine Art (Boothbay Harbor Maine, 2017).<ref name=\"Ogunquit Museum 2008\"/><ref name=\"ACME Fine Art Mar 2005\"/><ref name=\"Boothbay Register May 2017\"/> In 2009 her work also appeared in an exhibition called \"The Art of the Cranberry Isles\" in the [[Portland Museum of Art]].<ref name=\"Bangor Daily News Mar 2009\"/>\n\n===Positions in art organizations===\n\nEisner immersed herself in the art world while still young. In 1930, aged twenty-four, she joined the board of the Society of Independent Artists. Not long afterward she became a member of the American Artists' Congress, the National Association of Women Painters and Sculptors, and the New York Society of Women Artists. As noted above, she was a founding member of the Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors in 1941.<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> It seems likely that her marriage, the war, and the birth of a daughter (1942) dampened the impulse to participate in other organizations.\n\n===Artistic style===\n[[File:1931FiddlersConvention.jpg|left|thumb|Dorothy Eisner, Fiddlers' Convention, about 1931, black and white photographic print of an oil painting, 9 x 7 inches]]\n[[File:1958YellowstoneRiver.jpg|right|thumb|Dorothy Eisner, Yellowstone River, about 1958, oil on canvas, 44 x 36 inches]]\n\nIn reviewing shows of the paintings she made in the 1930s, critics noticed that when choosing subjects Eisner favored people over scenery.<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 21 1932\"/> Two of them saw these paintings as lively and entertaining social documents having an authentic quality.<ref name=\"New York Sun Nov 1932\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Nov 21 1932\"/> Others pointed out a muted palette and a tendency to drabness along with strong composition, ability to develop a subject freshly and spontaneously, and overall vigor and thoroughness.<ref name=\"New York Times Dec 1933\"/><ref name=\"New York Post Jan 1936\"/><ref name=\"New York Post Nov 1932\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Nov 1932\"/> For example, a critic for the ''New York Sun'' said Eisner painted her subjects \"roughly, but with a curious instinct for balance that makes the panels, as a whole, attractive.\"<ref name=\"New York Sun Mar 1934\"/> Writing in the ''New York Times'' Howard Devree noted Eisner's skill in delineating subjects convincingly and praised her growing strength and sureness.<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1934\"/> The painting, \"Fiddlers' Convention\" (shown at left) was mentioned as typical of her better 1930s work.<ref name=\"New York Sun Nov 1932\"/><ref name=\"New York Times Nov 21 1932\"/> In 1934 it was reproduced in an article in the ''Philadelphia Record'' reviewing the Pennsylvania Academy's 129th annual exhibition.<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/>\n\nEisner's style changed little during the 1930s and war years. During the post-war period, while most of her work remained realist, she began to study under [[Jack Tworkov]]. Although much [[abstract expressionism|abstract expressionist]] painting was then anti-figurative, Tworkov, like his friend [[Willem de Kooning]], believed that even so-called pure abstraction made, as he said, \"analogy to the figure.\" His obituary in the ''New York Times'' quoted him as saying \"Every painter has a subject whether or not there are objects in his paintings.\"<ref name=\"New York Times Sep 1982\"/> Eisner responded sympathetically to this approach. Later she was quoted as saying, \"Abstract Expressionism made me think differently. I learned from it a language of shapes and color that I was not conscious of when I was young.\"<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art 2016\"/> During this period she produced much work in regular visits to the American [[mountain states]], particularly Livingston, Montana, and nearby [[Yellowstone National Park]]. Her painting \"Yellowstone River\" (seen at right) shows the influence of Tworkov's instruction. While it might be taken as a pure abstraction, the title shows it to be an abstract representation of a real place.\n\n[[File:1965PortraitInLight.jpg|left|thumb|Dorothy Eisner, Portrait in Light, 1965, oil on canvas, 25 x 30 inches]]\n[[File:1981InteriorStillLife.jpg|right|thumb|Dorothy Eisner, Interior Still Life, 1981, oil on canvas, 24 x 30 inches]] \nIn 1960, when Eisner and her husband began spending summers on Great Cranberry Island, her work showed a new [[figurative art|figurative]] style. She often showed people relaxing and engaging in vacation-time pursuits: playing cards or croquet. Just as often her subjects would be inanimate: desks, chairs, windows, a towel rack. Writing in 2008 concerning a retrospective exhibition that showed these paintings, a critic said, \"her subject matter is so seemingly mundane that the viewer is startled by her choice.\"<ref name=\"Ogunquit Museum 2008\"/> Although abstract, her style was firmly grounded in specific places at specific times, and its realist subjects were clearly evident. She made expressionistic use of bold colors, as she had in her 1950s abstractions, but in a style that critics saw as fluid, masterfully composed, and expressionistic.<ref name=\"Ogunquit Museum 2008\"/><ref name=\"New England Today Jan 2009\"/> A critic said the paintings she made on Cranberry Island were orderly, distinct, and painted with great spirit.<ref name=\"Portland Press Herald Oct 2008\"/>\n\nAn early painting from this period, \"Portrait in Light\" (shown at left), has a greater degree of abstraction than a painting, \"Interior Still Life\" (shown at right) made only three years before her death. The latter work seems to show an influence of Matisse that critics saw in her work from the time she spent studying at Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re in the late 1920s.<ref name=\"New England Today Jan 2009\"/><ref name=\"ACME Fine Art 2016\"/> From its inception in the 1930s through to its culmination in the late paintings, Eisner's output maintained a consistency that a gallerist summarized as derived from European modernism but also grounded in American painting of her own generation and the generation before her.<ref name=\"Gleason Fine Art\"/>\n\n==Personal life and family==\n\nEisner was born in New York on January 17, 1906.<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> Her father was William J. Eisner. He was born in San Antonio, Texas, in 1880 and died in New York in 1975.<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> Orphaned while still young, he left school at 13 and later became one of the first makers of wax paper in the United States. Having moved to New York he was for many years president of a business called the Newark Paraffin and Parchment Paper Co.<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Aug 1961\"/> Eisner's mother was Florine Eisner (1883-1974). Florine's father's name was Moritz Eisner. Born in Austria, he studied to be a chemist and after emigrating to the United States founded a business called Eisner-Mendelson Company that sold a malt extract and other health products.<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1938\"/> After her marriage in 1905, Florine Eisner's maiden and married surnames were the same.\n\nEisner had a sister, [[Anne Eisner Putnam]] (1911-1967), who followed in her sister's footsteps. She studied at the Art Students League and served on its board of directors. She showed professionally during the 1940s with the National Association of Women Painters and Sculptors and the National Association of Women Artists. After her marriage to Patrick Putnam she lived in the [[Ituri Rainforest]] within the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Belgian Congo]] in a campsite adjacent to pygmies of the  [[Mbuti people]]. Patrick Putnam, who had an unpaid position as ''agent sanitaire'', ran an informal dispensary and anthropological laboratory. For eight years Anne Eisner Putnam operated a small collection of guest houses from which she rented out rooms to visitors so as to support her husband's work.<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Jun 1956\"/> Following Patrick's death in 1953 she returned to New York where she published a book, ''Madami: My Eight Years of Adventure with the Congo Pygmies'', describing her experiences and celebrating the Mbuti culture which she deeply respected.<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Dec 1954\"/>\n\nIn the 1930s Florine Eisner (1883-1974) followed the example set by both daughters by studying at the Art Students League. Using Florine Rensie as her name, she joined the National Association of Women Painters and Sculptors and became a professional artist (Rensie is Eisner spelled backward).<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> After he retired from business in the early 1950s, William J. Eisner joined the rest of the family in studying art and becoming a professional artist.<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Aug 1961\"/>\n\nWilliam and Florine raised their family in Manhattan. During the warm months of the year they frequently traveled to their country home in Woodstock, New York and, after the children had grown they followed the example they had set and both became serious artists. William exhibited under his own name in galleries in nearby Kingston, New York, while Florine adopted Florine Rensie as her professional name to avoid the appearance of capitalizing on her daughters' artistic successes .<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Aug 1961\"/>\n\nEarly in the 1930s Eisner worked in New York for the [[Resettlement Administration]]. In 1935 she met her future husband, [[John McDonald (journalist)|John Dennis McDonald]] (1906-1998), who was then working for the [[Federal Writers' Project]] and in 1936 they married.<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\"/> Born and raised in Detroit, Michigan, he graduated from the University of Michigan with a master's degree in literature and subsequently immersed himself in the socialist politics of the 1930s, particularly the [[anti-Stalinist left]]. In 1937 he joined the [[Dewey Commission]] as a technical assistant. He and Eisner traveled to Mexico with the commission staff. Chaired by the philosopher [[John Dewey]], the commission aimed to provide [[Leon Trotsky]] with a fair hearing of the charges made against him in the [[Moscow trials|Soviet show trials]] of 1936. While they opposed Stalinism, he and Eisner, like most members of the commission, were not themselves [[Trotskyism|Trotskyists]].<ref name=\"Harvard Review 2006\"/> During the latter part of the 1930s, McDonald worked for the [[Federal Writers' Project]] in Washington, D.C. During World War II he worked in New York for a nonprofit motion picture production company called the American Film Center.{{refn|group=note|Founded by Donald Slesinger, a psychologist and law school dean, and supported by the Rockefeller Foundation, the American Film Center supported producers of educational and documentary films and produced films for the [[Office of Civilian Defense]]. Slesinger's inept management brought the center to bankruptcy in 1946.<ref name=\"Learning With Lights Off 2012\"/>  }} In 1945 he began work as a staff writer at [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] magazine. In 1949 he joined its editorial board and remained in that position until he retired in 1971. His writings showed a wide breadth of his interest, including economic theory and game theory as well as fishing and horse racing.<ref name=\"John McDonald SNAC\"/> The author of scholarly texts as well as journal articles, he was best known for a book that listed him as editor although he was in fact its author: ''My Years with General Motors, by Alfred P. Sloan Jr.'' (1964).<ref name=\"Boston Globe Nov 2002\"/>\n\nMcDonald had a daughter, Joan (born 1929), by a prior, relatively brief, marriage with Lorraine Oven.<ref name=\"John McDonald SNAC\"/> Eisner and McDonald had one child, a daughter, Christie Anne (born 1942), who, at time of this writing, is the Smith Professor of French Language and Literature and Chair of the Department of Romance Languages and Literatures at Harvard.<ref name=\"John McDonald SNAC\"/><ref name=\"Christie McDonald Harvard\"/>\n\nEisner died in New York on April 28, 1984.<ref name=\"John McDonald SNAC\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n|colwidth=30em\n|refs=\n\n<!-- journals -->\n\n<ref name=\"Harvard Review 2006\">{{cite journal |author=Christie McDonald |date=2006 |volume= |issue=30 |pages=142\u2013149 | title=Brushes with History |jstor=27569177 |journal=Harvard Review |location= |publisher= |archive-url= |archive-date= |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<!-- books -->\n\n<ref name=\"Learning With Lights Off 2012\">{{cite book |author1=Devin Orgeron |author2=Marsha Orgeron |author3=Dan Streible |title=Learning with the Lights Off: Educational Film in the United States |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NXxMCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA244 |date=6 January 2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-045251-3 |pages=243\u2013245}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Art of Acadia 2016\">{{cite book |author1=David Little |author2=Carl Little |title=Art of Acadia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GIg1DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA181 |date=1 August 2016 |publisher=Down East Books |isbn=978-1-60893-475-1 |page=181}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_dRU2c1LPcYC |title=Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life |publisher=Upne |year=1989 |format= |page=302 |author=Roxana Robinson |accessdate=2015-12-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Adoph Gottlieb 1995\">{{cite book |author1=Lawrence Alloway |author2=Mary D. MacNaughton |title=Adolph Gottlieb: A Retrospective |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y_XppsXbW5AC&pg=PA16 |year=1995 |publisher=Hudson Hills  |isbn=978-1-55595-125-2 |page=16}}</ref>\n\n<!-- web pages -->\n\n<ref name=\"Trotsky Commission Painting\">{{cite web |url=https://deweycenter.siu.edu/about-dewey/dorothy-painting.php |title=Dorothy Eisner Trotsky Commission Painting  |format= |work=Center for Dewey Studies, Southern Illinois University |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Dorothy Eisner papers\">{{cite web |url=https://archives.yale.edu/repositories/11/resources/835 |title=Collection: Dorothy Eisner papers [finding aid] |format= |work=Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Archives at Yale |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"John McDonald SNAC\">{{cite web |url=https://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w61262qb |title=McDonald, John, 1906-1998 |format= |work=Social Networks and Archival Context |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Christie McDonald Harvard\">{{cite web |url=https://rll-faculty.fas.harvard.edu/christiemcdonald/home |title=Christie McDonald |format= |work=Faculty, Harvard College, Department of Romance Languages & Literatures |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art Mar 2005\">{{cite web |url=http://www.acmefineart.com/modern/show-eisner-press/ |title=Dorothy Eisner, Late Expressionist Paintings |date=2005-03-18 |format= |work=ACME Fine Art |accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Ogunquit Museum 2008\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seacoastonline.com/article/20080925/ENTERTAIN/809250343 |title=Ogunquit Museum of American Art hangs Late Summer Exhibition |format= |work=seacoastonline |date=2008-09-25 |accessdate=2020-04-16 |quote=Eisner\u2019s paintings are inspired by her travels and reflect her reaction to the locales, people and activities that surrounded her. In many cases, her subject matter is so seemingly mundane that the viewer is startled by her choice. Desks, chairs, windows, a towel rack, fish and fishing gear, people playing cards or croquet, children with a garden hose &mdash; all become aesthetically worthy subjects as seen through her eyes. With her masterful compositional skills, her fluid application of paint, and her expressionistic use of bold colors, Eisner creates compelling art from these everyday scenes and items. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New England Today Jan 2009\">{{cite web |url=https://newengland.com/today/living/new-england-environment/eisner/ |title=Dorothy Eisner, Modern Art, Modern Painting |format= |work=New England Today; Living |author=Edgar Allen Beem |date=2009-01-23 |accessdate=2020-04-15 |quote=What you see in Painting My World is Eisner\u2019s evolution from a social realist who studied under Boardman Robinson, Kenneth Hayes Miller, and Thomas Hart Benton at the Art Students League in the 1920s through the Abstract Expressionist influence of Jack Tworkov, with whom she studied after World War II, to her blossoming as a painterly realist in the 1970s and 1980s. It was quite a journey and one well worth retaking. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ACME Fine Art 2016\">{{cite web |url=http://www.acmefineart.com/modern/show-eisner-harrison-orlowsky-press/ |title=EIsner / Harrison / Orlowsky |format= |work=ACME Fine Art |date=2016-01-20 |accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gleason Fine Art\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gleasonfineart.com/gallery/category/dorothy-eisner-1906-1984 |title=Dorothy Eisner (1906-1984) |format= |work=Gleason Fine Art |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Federation of modern painters and sculptors 2018\">{{cite web |url=https://artterms.artopium.com/f/Federationofmodernpaintersandsculptors.htm |title=Federation of modern painters and sculptors |work=Artopium's Art Dictionary |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"The Opportunity Gallery\">{{cite web |url=https://warholstars.org/abstract-expressionism/artists/rothko/mark_rothko.html |title=The Opportunity Gallery |work=WarholStars |accessdate=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Delphic Studio\">{{cite web |url=https://libraryguides.lib.iup.edu/c.php?g=419334&p=2864182 |title=Artists Biographies A-C - WPA Meets IUP : A Glimpse Into America's Artistic Past |format= |work=LibGuides at Indiana University of PA |accessdate=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AskArt Dorothy Eisner\">{{cite web |url=https://www.askart.com/artist/Dorothy_McDonald_Eisner/101224/Dorothy_McDonald_Eisner.aspx?sthp=dorothy%20eisner |title=Dorothy Eisner |format= |work=AskArt |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tworkov Papers AAA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/jack-tworkov-papers-13402/biographical-note |title=Biographical Note &#124; A Finding Aid to the Jack Tworkov papers, circa 1926-1993 &#124; Digitized Collection &#124;  |format= |work=Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution |accessdate=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n<!-- newspapers -->\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jul 1922\">{{cite news |title=Salons of America a New Art Society |author= |work=The New York Times |location= |date=1922-07-03 |page=12 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Brooklyn Daily Eagle Nov 1927\">{{cite news |title=Opportunity Gallery Has Second Exhibition |author= |work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle |location=Brooklyn, New York |date=1927-11-20 |page=GE |quote=The Opportunity Gallery at the Art Center, whose raison d'\u00eatre is to give the talented unknown an opportunity for free display, is holding its second exhibition of the season... The policy on which the gallery operates is that each exhibition must be the selection of a one-man jury. In order to give all types of artistic expression an equal chance, there are modern and conservative jurors as well as ones who pursue the golden mean. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jan 1930\">{{cite news |title=A Round of Galleries |author=Ruth Green Harris |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1930-01-26|page=117 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 1932\">{{cite news |title=The Week In New York: A Roster of New Exhibitions |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-20 |page=X9 |quote=In her first one-many show, Dorothy Eisner is exhibiting paintings largely of Southern mountain life. Her color lacks warmth and sometimes inclines to drabness, but she has caught in her paintings something of the life and bearing of the mountaineer. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Post Nov 1932\">{{cite news |title=Marin Paintings and Water Colors |author= |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-09 |page=3 |quote=At the Morton Galleries Dorothy Eisner is holding an exhibition of paintings. She is a young artist who has apparently a considerable command of technical facility and the ability to develop a subject freshly and spontaneously, as her painting, \"The Hammock,\" attests. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Sun Nov 1932\">{{cite news |title=Art Displays in Varied Mood |author= |work=New York Sun |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-17 |page= |quote=As social documents, revelations of the life somewhere in the southern mountains, several of the canvases that Dorothy Eisner is showing at the Morton Galleries are vastly entertaining. \"Bird in Buzzard Out\" and the \"Fiddlers' Convention,\" for example. As paintings, \"Curley,\" \"The Hammock\" and the \"Cider Press\" seem to present the young artist at her not too accomplished best. When it comes to that \"Self-Portrait\" one is left in some doubt whether modesty or humor prompted it. Something could be said for either point of view. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 21 1932\">{{cite news |title=Art: Two Important Shows |author=T.C.L. |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1932-11-21 |page=26 |quote=In the canvases at her first one-man show at the Morton Galleries, Dorothy Eisner is portraying some aspects of life in the Southern mountain region of this country. Writers have been far in advance of artists in discovering the possibilities of subject-matter in this section. It is not the beauties of mountain landscape that have attracted Miss Eisner, but rather the individuality of people and the interest of their pastimes. A \"Fiddlers' Convention\" and a dance called \"Bird in Buzzard Out\" Miss Eisner evidently watched closely, for she caught something of the characteristic bearing of the Southern mountaineer. Individuals, too, she has portrayed in portrait studies. Although there is some authentic quality of the South in these paintings, they incline toward drabness of color, and the figures have not enough animation to make them live in paint. Most successfully realized are several still-lifes. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times May 1933\">{{cite news |title=The Etchings of Georges Rouault |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1933-05-07 |page=X8 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Oct 1933\">{{cite news |title=Henry V. Poor's Paintings |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1933-10-24 |page=19 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Dec 1933\">{{cite news |title=The Dance in Art Theme of Exhibit: College Association Offers for View 100 Examples in Various Mediums |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1933-12-13 |page=21 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Sun Mar 1934\">{{cite news |title=Attractions in Other Galleries |author= |work=New York Sun |location=New York, New York |date=1934-03-31 |page=13 |quote=Miss Eisner... paints citizens who have a good deal of the soil upon their clothes. She paints them rather roughly, but with a curious instinct for balance that makes the panels, as a whole, attractive. Her most successful improvisation is called 'Franklin's View.' It shows a man, carelessly attired, fishing in a romantic spot, but whether were a portrait of the man or of the place, could not be ascertained. Such things are unimportant anyway when you like the picture. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1934\">{{cite news |title=Seen in the Galleries: Comment on Some of the Exhibitions That Have Opened Recently in This City |author=Howard Devree |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1934-04-01 |page=X9 |quote=Two One-Woman Shows  Oils by Grace Bliss Stewart and Dorothy Eisner are on exhibition at the Delphic Studios...  Dorothy Eisner is gaining strength and sureness, as her Carolina canvases attest. These seem more original and suggest that the artist was more interested in them than in her New York pictures. Her mountain people are convincingly delineated. She makes excellent use of warm reds, in a palette generally low. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Post Jan 1936\">{{cite news |title=O'Keeffe Works Highly Spirited |author= |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1936-01-11 |page=2 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jan 1937\">{{cite news |title=Giotto 600 Years After |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1937-01-17 |page=161 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1937\">{{cite news |title=American Artists Congress |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1937-04-25 |page=171 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Post Feb 1938\">{{cite news |title=Women Artists in Annual Show at Grant Studio |author= |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1938-02-05 |page=30 |quote=Dorothy Eisner has made quite a thing of a 'North Carolina Dough Board.' Its strength of design and color in large scale execution, make it the outstanding canvas of the show. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1938\">{{cite news |title=Moritz Eisner, 84, a Retired Chemist |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1938-06-20 |page=15 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Jun 1940\">{{cite news |title=News and Notes of Art |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1940-06-19 |page=21 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times May 1942\">{{cite news |title=Exhibition is Held by Art Federation; Modern Painters and Sculptors Have Large Display at Their Second Annual Show |author=Edward Alden Jewell |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1942-05-22 |page=24 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Dec 1954\">{{cite news |title=Woodstock |author= |work=Kingston Daily Freeman |location=Kingston, New York |date=1954-12-15 |page=5 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Jun 1956\">{{cite news |title=The Putnam Story |author=Max Lerner |work=New York Post |location=New York, New York |date=1956-06-24 |page=8 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Feb 1961\">{{cite news |title=Art Openings in the Galleries |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1960-02-12 |page=X20 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kingston Daily Freeman Aug 1961\">{{cite news |title=Do You Remember |author=Sophie Miller |work=Kingston Daily Freeman |location=Kingston, New York |date=1961-08-30 |page=12 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Nov 1966\">{{cite news |title=What's New in Art: In the Museums Lectures |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1961-11-27 |page=D18 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Apr 1969\">{{cite news |title=Display ad: Cisneros Gallery |author= |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1969-04-06 |page=D26 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"New York Times Sep 1982\">{{cite news |title=Jack Tworkov, Painter And Art Teacher, Dead |author=Michael Brenson |work=New York Times |location=New York, New York |date=1982-09-06 |page=32 |quote=Like others of his generation, however, Mr. Tworkov never accepted the idea of pure abstraction. 'I'm trying to make an analogy to the figure,' he said. Mr. Tworkov believed what the next generation of abstract painters would fight against tooth and nail: 'Every painter has a subject whether or not there are objects in his paintings.' }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Boston Globe Nov 2002\">{{cite news |title=Author Tells How He Took on Goliath GM and Won |author=Rich Barlow |work=Boston Globe |location=Boston, Massachusetts |date=2002-11-17 |page=H2 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Portland Press Herald Oct 2008\">{{cite news |title=Shows at Saco Museum, Ogunquit Museum of American Art |author=Bob Keyes |work=Portland Press Herald |location=Portland, Maine |date=2008-10-19 |page=C6 |quote= Her canvases are fluid, orderly and distinct. She painted whatever came before her, be it a horse, a stack of fishing gear, a desk and chair, or even something as mundane as a game of croquet. But she painted with great spirit, and the work on display in Ogunquit seems to express her personality: bold colors, quick strokes and a certain sense of place. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bangor Daily News Mar 2009\">{{cite news |title=Inspiring Isles; Portland Museum of Art highlights the Diversity of a Creative Crew from Maine's Cranberry Isles |author=Jessica Bloch |work=Bangor Daily News |location=Bangor, Maine |date=2009-03-20 |page=7 |quote=In 'Desk II,' Eisner painted an orange desk with a boat schedule, an August calendar, a list of names including Heliker, LaHotan and Kienbusch, and a big black phone prominently displayed &mdash; as if she\u2019s about to invite friends or plan her next party. We get a clue about what that party might have been like in 'Croquet and Hats,' with a line of croquet mallets, balls and a straw hat, awaiting the next round of lawn games. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Boothbay Register May 2017\">{{cite news |title=Dorothy Eisner show at Gleason Fine Art |author=Marty Gleason |work=Boothbay Register |location=Boothbay Harbor, Maine |date=2017-05-24 |page= |url=https://www.boothbayregister.com/article/dorothy-eisner-show-gleason-fine-art/86670 |accessdate=2020-04-15 |quote=Dorothy Eisner's artistic career spanned seven decades. From her Greenwich Village studio, she traveled widely, including to the American West, Mexico, and Europe. However, it was her discovery in 1960 of Cranberry Island, an enchanting small island off Mount Desert and its vibrant community of artists, that was the beginning of Eisner's passion for Maine \u2013 a passion that lasted for 24 summers, until the very end of her life. Eisner relished involving herself in the local art scene. In New York, she exhibited broadly and worked tirelessly to further the careers of her fellow artists. Eisner's time on Cranberry was no different. She befriended and worked with many artists, including William Kienbusch, Carl Nelson, and John Heliker, all of whom summered on Cranberry Island. }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisner, Dorothy}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Women painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Delabrede", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life and family", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorothy_Eisner"}
{"title_page": "British hip hop", "text_new": "{{short description|British genres of hip hop}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox music genre <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Music genres -->\n| name = British hip hop\n| bgcolor = darkblue\n| color = white\n| stylistic_origins = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Urban contemporary|urban]]|[[garage house]]|[[Dub music|dub]]}}\n| cultural_origins = Early to mid-1980s, United Kingdom\n| instruments = {{hlist|[[Turntablism|Turntable]]|[[synthesizer]]|[[rapping]]|[[drum machine]]|[[sampler (musical instrument)|sampler]]|[[guitar]]}}\n| derivatives = [[Trip hop]]\n| subgenres = {{hlist|[[Chap hop]]|[[road rap]]|[[UK drill]]|[[UK trap]]|Britcore (British hardcore hip hop)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/pp4q4k/remembering-britcore-the-uks-forgotten-music-scene|title=The UK's Forgotten Rap Scene Deserves Your Attention|first=Nick|last=Chester|date=2 June 2014|access-date=4 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804035015/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/pp4q4k/remembering-britcore-the-uks-forgotten-music-scene|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| fusiongenres = \n| regional_scenes = \n| popularity = Mid-1980s until today\n| other_topics = {{hlist|[[Drum and bass]]|[[Grime (music genre)|grime]]|[[dubstep]]|[[UK garage]]|[[gangsta rap]]|[[Drill (music genre)|drill]]|[[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[afroswing]]}}\n| other_names = {{hlist|UK rap|British rap|Brit-hop|UK hip hop}}\n}}\n'''British hip hop''', also known as '''UK rap''', is a [[music genre|genre of music]], and a culture that covers a variety of styles of [[hip hop music]] made in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"brithop\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4455862.stm |title=BBC News website: Is UK on Verge of Brithop boom |first=Ian |last=Youngs |date=21 November 2005 |accessdate=1 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827113142/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4455862.stm |archive-date=27 August 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |work=The Times |title=Home grown \u2013 profile \u2013 British hip-hop \u2013 music'' |first=Angus |last=Batey |date=26 July 2003}}</ref> It is generally classified as one of a number of styles of [[urban music]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/urban/ |title=BBC Website \u2013 Music: Urban |accessdate=1 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061103104354/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/urban/ |archive-date=3 November 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref> British hip hop can also be referred to referred to as '''Brit-hop''', a term coined and popularised mainly by ''[[British Vogue]]'' magazine and the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/video/vogue-meets-the-brit-hop-generation|title=Vogue Meets The Brit-Hop Generation \u2013 British Vogue|accessdate=15 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917122128/http://www.vogue.co.uk/video/vogue-meets-the-brit-hop-generation|archive-date=17 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/gallery/london-grime-scene-loyle-carner-section-boyz-nadia-rose|title=Vogue Meets London's Rising Music Stars \u2013 British Vogue|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023210602/http://www.vogue.co.uk/gallery/london-grime-scene-loyle-carner-section-boyz-nadia-rose|archive-date=23 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4455862.stm|title=The Brithop Boom \u2013 BBC|date=21 November 2005|accessdate=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403121324/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4455862.stm|archive-date=3 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> British hip hop was originally influenced by the [[Deejay (Jamaican)|dub/toasting]] introduced to the United Kingdom by Jamaican migrants in the 1950s\u201370s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/windrush/articles/sound-systems|title=Sound systems|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-02-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420065549/https://www.bl.uk/windrush/articles/sound-systems|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> who eventually developed uniquely influenced rapping (or speed-toasting) in order to match the rhythm of the ever-increasing pace and aggression of Jamaican-influenced [[Dub music|dub]] in the UK. Toasting and [[Sound system (Jamaican)|soundystem]] culture was also influential in genres outside of hip hop that still included [[rapping]] - such as [[Grime (music genre)|grime]], [[Jungle music|jungle]], and [[UK garage]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/01/inside-grime-true-history-dan-hancox-dj-target-wiley-dizzee-rascal-stormzy|title='You can't escape its inspiration': inside the true history of grime|date=2018-06-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018161811/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/01/inside-grime-true-history-dan-hancox-dj-target-wiley-dizzee-rascal-stormzy|archive-date=18 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2016/07/06/roots-and-future-documentary-black-british-music-jungle-garage-grime-dubstep/|title=Hear a documentary on black British music from jungle to dubstep|date=2016-07-06|website=FACT Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108224525/https://www.factmag.com/2016/07/06/roots-and-future-documentary-black-british-music-jungle-garage-grime-dubstep/|archive-date=8 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, ''[[The Times]]'' described British hip hop's broad-ranging approach:\n\n<blockquote>...\"UK rap\" is a broad sonic church, encompassing anything made in Britain by musicians informed or inspired by hip-hop's possibilities, whose music is a response to the same stimuli that gave birth to rap in New York in the mid-Seventies.<ref name=\"times\" /></blockquote>\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nAs in the US, British hip hop emerged as a scene from [[graffiti]] and [[breakdancing]], and then through to DJing and [[rapping]] live at parties and club nights, with its supporters predominantly listening to and influenced by American hip hop. Unlike in the US, the British hip hop scene was cross-racial from the beginning, as various ethnic groups in Britain tend not to live in segregated areas, even in areas with a high percentage of non-white individuals. Such places allow youth to share culture with one another, including musical genres such as hip hop.<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Urban Breakbeat Culture: Repercussions of Hip-Hop in the United Kingdom\", pp. 86\u2013101 in Global Noise: Rap and Hip Hop Outside of the USA, edited by Tony Mitchell. Middletown, CT: Wesleyan University Press.|first=David|last=Hesmondhalgh}}</ref>\n\nCross pollination through migrating [[West Indies|West Indians]] helped develop a community interested in the music. The integration of [[Sound system (Jamaican)|sound systems]] represent a distinct British Caribbean influence. Sound systems allowed for powerful syncopated bass runs and the ability to bring this sound to different venues creating a club culture.<ref>Hesmondhalgh, DJ and Melville, C (2002) Urban Breakbeat Culture \u2013 Repercussions of Hip-Hop in the United Kingdom. In: Global Noise: Rap and Hip Hop Outside the USA. Wesleyan University Press.</ref> There were, however, British tunes starting to appear. The first ever British hip hop tune released on record was \"Christmas Rapping\" by Dizzy Heights (Polydor, 1982) and not (contrary to popular belief) \"London Bridge\" by [[Newtrament]] (Jive Records, 1983);.<ref name=\"low\">{{cite web|url=http://www.low-life.fsnet.co.uk/ukhiphop/story/early_doors.htm |title=Low Life/British hip hop, UK hip hop: the story find |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010071345/http://www.low-life.fsnet.co.uk/ukhiphop/story/early_doors.htm |archivedate=10 October 2006 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThere were earlier pop records which dabbled with rap \u2014 such as [[Adam and the Ants]]' \"[[Ant Rap]]\" (CBS, 1981) and [[Wham!]]'s \"[[Wham Rap! (Enjoy What You Do)]]\" (Inner Vision, 1982) \u2014 but these are often considered pop appropriations of US rap.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ogg|first1=Alex|title=Paid in full? an introduction to brit-hop, grime and UK rap|date=2011|publisher=Andrews UK Ltd.|location=Luton|isbn=1908354046|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3qS6BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=inauthor%3A%22Alex%20Ogg%22&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2016-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419194905/https://books.google.com/books?id=3qS6BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=inauthor%253A%22Alex%20Ogg%22&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Punk band [[the Clash]] had earlier dabbled with rap on the single \"[[The Magnificent Seven (song)|The Magnificent Seven]]\" from their album ''[[Sandinista!]]'' (CBS, 1980), and a later single \"[[This is Radio Clash]]\" (1981).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monthlyreview.org/2003/06/01/let-fury-have-the-hour-the-passionate-politics-of-joe-strummer/|title=Monthly Review {{!}} \u2018Let Fury Have the Hour\u2019: The Passionate Politics of Joe Strummer|last=Movements|first=Antonino D\u2019AmbrosioTopics:|date=2003-06-01|website=Monthly Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106091520/https://monthlyreview.org/2003/06/01/let-fury-have-the-hour-the-passionate-politics-of-joe-strummer/|archive-date=6 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThen [[Sex Pistols]] manager [[Malcolm McLaren]]'s \"[[Buffalo Gals (Malcolm McLaren song)|Buffalo Gals]]\" (Charisma, 1982), featuring the New York hip hop group [[World's Famous Supreme Team]], was the breakthrough hit that introduced the genre to the United Kingdom<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://old.manchesterconfidential.co.uk/Entertainment-and-Sport/Music/HomeGrown-the-story-of-UK-hip-hop|title=HomeGrown: the story of UK hip-hop|website=Manchester Confidential|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> \u2014 McLaren's ''[[Duck Rock]]'' album as a whole experimented with many musical styles from around the world. \"Buffalo Gals\" and another track from the album, \"World's Famous\" which also featured the group, used techniques which have been established in hip hop in the United States, such as [[sampling (music)|sampling]] and [[scratching]]. McLaren even included a song referencing the '[[Double Dutch (jump rope)|Double Dutch]]' dance that was popular among breakdancing crews in New York at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/nn974m/double-dutchs-forgotten-hip-hop-origins-456|title=Double Dutch's Forgotten Hip-Hop Origins|last=Schwartzberg|first=Lauren|date=2015-03-31|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001205746/https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/nn974m/double-dutchs-forgotten-hip-hop-origins-456|archive-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOver the next few years, more UK hip hop and [[electro music|electro]] music was released: ''Street Sounds Electro UK'' (Street Sounds, 1984), which was produced by [[Greg Wilson (DJ)|Greg Wilson]] and featured an early appearance from MC Kermit, who later went on to form the Wilson produced [[Ruthless Rap Assassins]]; [[Herbie the Mastermind|The Rapologists]]' \"Kids Rap/Party Rap\" (Billy Boy, 1984) and Grandmaster Richie Rich's \"Don't Be Flash\" (Spin Offs, 1985).<ref name=\"The Vinyl Factory - Richie Rich\">{{cite web |title=The 10 records that helped British hip hop find its own voice |url=https://thevinylfactory.com/features/the-10-records-that-helped-british-hip-hop-find-its-own-voice/ |website=[[The Vinyl Factory]] |accessdate=24 June 2018 |date=17 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624150550/https://thevinylfactory.com/features/the-10-records-that-helped-british-hip-hop-find-its-own-voice/ |archive-date=24 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Releases were still few and far between, and the scene remained predominantly underground.[[File:Tim Westwood 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Westwood's official [[YouTube]] channel, Tim Westwood TV, has over 395 million video views and over 750,000 subscribers. The channel has videos of freestyles & interviews from some of the most successful hip hop artists including [[Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Eminem]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Nas]] and [[Lil Wayne]].]]\n\nAlthough record labels began to take note of the underground scene throughout the 1980s and 1990s, radio play and publicity were still a difficulty in helping the fledgling scene to grow, and the scene only managed to survive through word of mouth and the patronage of [[pirate radio]] stations around the country. Mainstream radio did play British hip hop on occasion, supported by such well-known DJs as [[Dave Pearce]], [[Tim Westwood]], and [[John Peel]].<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1493022/john-peel-legendary-dj-and-champion-of-acts-from-bowie-to-franz-ferdinand-dies/|title=John Peel, Legendary DJ And Champion Of Acts From Bowie To Franz Ferdinand, Dies|last=Montgomery|first=James|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526151054/http://www.mtv.com/news/1493022/john-peel-legendary-dj-and-champion-of-acts-from-bowie-to-franz-ferdinand-dies/|archive-date=26 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixcloud.com/colinmillar/old-school-uk-hip-hop-radio-sessions-volume-5/|title=Mixcloud|website=Mixcloud|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111224014909/http://www.mixcloud.com/colinmillar/old-school-uk-hip-hop-radio-sessions-volume-5/|archive-date=24 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBritish hip hop in the 1980s was not just confined to music and break-dancing, but also involved the spread of New York City-style graffiti \u2014 another [[Four elements of hip hop|integral element of American hip hop culture]] \u2014 to London and other UK inner-city areas, both on walls and trains. The most direct influence was, however, on graffiti painted in [[London Underground]] trains. Teenagers from inner London and other European cities who were into electro-hip hop and had family and other links to New York City had by the mid-1980s taken up some of the traditions of subway graffiti and exported them home, although legendary New York writers like Brim, Bio, and Futura had themselves played a significant role in establishing such links when they visited London in the early-to-mid-'80s and 'put up pieces' on or near the west London end of the Metropolitan Line. Almost as significantly, just when subway graffiti was on the decline in New York City, some British teenagers who had spent time with family in Queens and the Bronx returned to London with a \"mission\" to Americanize the London Underground through painting New York City-style graffiti on trains. These small groups of London 'train writers' adopted many of the styles and lifestyles of their New York City forebears, painting graffiti train pieces and in general 'bombing' the system, but favoring only a few selected underground lines seen as most suitable for train graffiti. Although on a substantially smaller scale than what had existed in New York City, graffiti on London Underground trains became seen as enough of a problem by the mid-1980s to provoke the British Transport Police to establish its own graffiti squad modeled directly on and in consultation with that of the New York City MTA. At the same time, graffiti art on London Underground trains generated some interest in the media and arts, leading to several art galleries putting on exhibitions of some of the art work (on canvass) of a few London train writers as well as TV documentaries on London hip hop culture like the BBC's ''Bad Meaning Good'', which included a section featuring interviews with London train writers and a few examples of their pieces.\n\nWhile many early rappers from the UK, such as [[Derek B]], imitated the styles and accents of their US heroes, there were many who realised that to merely transpose US forms would rob UK hip-hop of the ability to speak for a disenfranchised British constituency in the way that US hip-hop so successfully spoke to, and for, its audience. Attempts were made by UK rappers to develop styles more obviously rooted in British linguistic practices \u2014 [[Rodney P]] of the [[London Posse]] deliberately chose a London accent \u2014 although many succeeded only in adopting a slurred hybrid that located the rap \"somewhere in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean\".<ref>Hesmondhalgh, David and Caspar Melville. \"Urban Breakbeat Culture: Repercussions of Hip-Hop in the United Kingdom.\" In Global Noise: Rap and Hip-Hop Outside the USA, 86\u2013110. Middletown: Wesleyan University Press, 2001.</ref>\n\n===Development: Late '80s\u2013early '90s===\nThe first UK record label devoted to releasing UK hip hop acts was founded in 1986. [[Simon Harris (musician)|Simon Harris]]' [[Music of Life]] label was home to rapper [[Derek B]], the first UK rapper to achieve chart success. He even collaborated with [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]] on his album ''[[Bullet from a Gun (album)|Bullet from a Gun]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/derek-b-rapper-and-producer-who-became-the-first-uk-hip-hop-artist-to-infiltrate-the-british-pop-1864852.html|title=Derek B: Rapper and producer who became the first UK hip-hop artist to|date=2010-01-12|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106090734/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/derek-b-rapper-and-producer-who-became-the-first-uk-hip-hop-artist-to-infiltrate-the-british-pop-1864852.html|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and was the first British rapper to appear on ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Michaels|first=Sean|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/nov/17/british-rapper-derek-b-dies|title=British rapper Derek B dies at 44|date=2009-11-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228130415/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/nov/17/british-rapper-derek-b-dies|archive-date=28 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBuilding on Derek B's success, [[Music of Life]] went on to sign groups such as [[Hijack (hip hop group)|Hijack]], the [[Demon Boyz]], [[Hardnoise]] (later Son of Noise) and [[MC Duke]]. Their ''Hard as Hell'' series mixed homegrown talent like Thrashpack and the [[She Rockers]] with US artists such as [[Professor Griff]]. Music of Life was swiftly followed by other labels such as [[Mango Records]] and Kold Sweat. Another successful British hip-hop artist that emerged from Music of Life was [[Asher D (Jamaican-British rapper)|Asher D]], whose Jamaican origins showed through in his vocal style.[[File:Slick Rick - The Ruler.jpg|thumb|259x259px|Slick Rick is commonly ranked as one of the greatest rappers of all time.]]\nMoving away from its US roots, British hip hop started to develop its own sounds: acts like [[Hijack (group)|Hijack]], [[II Tone Committee]], [[Hardnoise]], and [[Silver Bullet (rapper)|Silver Bullet]] developed a fast and [[hardcore hip hop|hardcore]] style, while many other acts took influences from elsewhere. [[Caveman (group)|Caveman]] and [[Outlaw Posse]] developed a jazz influenced style, whilst MC Mell'O' mixed [[jazz]] and hardcore. [[London Posse]], [[Black Radical Mk II]] and DJ Ruf Cut And Tuf C were more influenced by [[reggae]] and [[disco]] whilst the [[Wee Papa Girl Rappers]], [[Cookie Crew]] and [[Monie Love]] achieved chart success with more radio friendly hip hop. However, despite the chart success of some British-born hip hop artists \u2014 for example [[Monie Love]], [[Slick Rick]], [[Young MC]] and [[MF Doom]], who all moved to the US \u2014 the majority of the scene was still underground and small scale.\n\nKinetic Effect joined the scene in the early 1980s and was part of rap outfit 2 the Top as D-Koy; later, in 1991, he teamed with Insane Macbeth to record \"Borderin' Insanity\" (released in 1993) and in 1995, he recorded \"Man Bites Dog\"/\"The Effect of Fear\"<ref name=\"Heroes of UK Hip Hop\">[http://www.heroesofukhiphop.com/Kinetic.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204163244/http://www.heroesofukhiphop.com/Kinetic.htm|date=4 February 2012}}</ref> Their song \"The Rhythm I Give 'Em\" made the UK Top 10 Hip Hop chart. Other notable rappers of this era included London Rhyme Syndicate, Cash Crew, Shogun MC, MC Untouchable and Dee Lawal.<ref name=\"Disco Scratch: Roots of the UK Hip Hop Scene\">{{cite web |url=http://discoscratch.co.uk/2010/06/11/dsr8-1989-special |title=Radio 8 \u2013 1989 Special |publisher=Disco Scratch |date=2010-06-11 |accessdate=2014-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330124721/http://discoscratch.co.uk/2010/06/11/dsr8-1989-special/ |archivedate=30 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, [[Positive Beat Records]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/label/Positive+Beat+Records |title=Positive Beat Records \u2013 CDs and Vinyl at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028213606/http://www.discogs.com/label/Positive+Beat+Records |archive-date=28 October 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> came out of the hotbed of early UK hip hop, [[Ladbroke Grove]] in London with two releases. The label followed up the single \"It's Getting Rough\" by Rocky X and D-D Dance<ref>{{cite web |url=http://top80.pl/disc/release/1338179/RockyX/(It%27s+Getting)+Ruff |title=Italo Disco, Euro Disco, Muzyka, Ludzie, Radio, Forum, Klimat, Czat |publisher=TOP80.PL |date= |accessdate=2014-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430073902/http://top80.pl/disc/release/1338179/RockyX/(It%27s+Getting)+Ruff |archive-date=30 April 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> with the Various Artists ''Known 2 Be Down''<ref>[http://www.raphistory.net/database?inc=records&operation=details&ID=3078] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724025952/http://www.raphistory.net/database?inc=records&operation=details&ID=3078|date=24 July 2011}}</ref> album. This featured Sir Drew (of KREW and [[Newtrament]]), MC Flex, [[She Rockers]], Rapski and more of West London's finest rap talents.\n\nOther notable labels at the time included [[Liberty Grooves]] <ref>Ear To The Ground Magazine, Issue 1 1993</ref> in Tooting, South London. The label itself started in late 1989 with the first release in 1990 by [[Whirlwind D]] & [[Johnny F]] of [[Solid n Mind]]. Other artists included [[Gutter Snypes]] <ref>Rap Trade Magazine, June 1994 Issue 6, Publisher: Pure Impact</ref>, True Style and [[DJ Noize]]. Liberty Grooves was also a shop and many notable artists such as MC Mell O and [[Braintax]] would perform there. \n\nIn 1988, Rapski released \"The Connection\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Rapski-The-Connection/release/963594 |title=Rapski \u2013 The Connection (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503033600/http://www.discogs.com/Rapski-The-Connection/release/963594 |archive-date=3 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> on 12\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://top80.pl/disc/label/Positive+Beat+Records |title=Italo Disco, Euro Disco, Muzyka, Ludzie, Radio, Forum, Klimat, Czat |publisher=TOP80.PL |date= |accessdate=2014-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430182155/http://top80.pl/disc/label/Positive+Beat+Records |archive-date=30 April 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The track was taken from ''Known 2 Be Down'' and was an early example of mixing hip hop and [[reggae]] in a (London) style. More was to come in the early 1990s in the form of [[MC Reason]] (a.k.a Voice of Reason) with \"Symbolise\"/\"HouseQuake\" and [[Jonie D]] with \"Which Base\"/\"Ride On\" which was performed live on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in 1991.\n\nA mindset began to develop \u2014 typified by the [[Gunshot (band)|Gunshot]] tune \"No Sell Out\" (1991), or [[Hardnoise|Son of Noise]]'s \"Poor But Hardcore\" (1992) \u2014 that distrusted successful artists who did not utilise the hardcore style most associated with the scene. [[Silver Bullet (rapper)|Silver Bullet]]'s chart success was applauded due to an uncompromisingly rapid delivery, whereas Derek B and [[Rebel MC]] were scorned when their more pop influenced styles earned them success. Such artists were often branded \"sell outs\". As the scene grew, it became less common for British rappers to imitate US accents (those who did were often ridiculed) and British rap became more assured of its identity.\n\n''[[Hip Hop Connection]]'' \u2014 the first major British hip hop magazine \u2014 was founded in 1989 and by the early 1990s the British hip hop scene seemed to be thriving. Not only was there a firm base of rappers in London such as Blade, [[Black Radical Mk II]], [[Overlord X]] and Bushkiller (including Sirus) \u2014 but many distinct scenes developed nationally.\n\nBirmingham and the West Midlands gave rise to [[Credit to the Nation]], whose MC Fusion would espouse conscious anti-racist, sexist and homophobic lyrics. The band would also find some brief mainstream success with their [[indie rock]] crossover sound. Leeds spawned [[Braintax]] and Breaking the Illusion (who together founded [[Low Life Records]]) as well as [[Nightmares on Wax]]. Greater Manchester gave birth to the [[Ruthless Rap Assassins]], Krispy 3 (later Krispy), the [[Kaliphz]], [[Jeep Beat Collective]] and [[MC Tunes]].\n\nBristol's scene has a long history going right back to the early '80s where links were made with outfits from New York. [[The Fearless Four (group)|The Fearless Four]] came over in 1984 along with graffiti legends the [[Tats Cru]] and [[Rock Steady Crew]].  Bristol (specifically the [[St Pauls, Bristol|St. Pauls]] area) produced The Wild Bunch (later better known as [[Massive Attack]]), [[Nellee Hooper]] who went on to produce for [[Soul II Soul]]. The city has also produced notable DMC DJs Mad Cut and DJ Quest. The city later became the home of [[trip hop]] with artists like [[Tricky (musician)|Tricky]] and [[Portishead (band)|Portishead]].\n\n[[Caveman (group)|Caveman]] signed to a major label \u2014 [[Profile Records]], the label home of [[Run\u2013D.M.C.]] \u2014 and Kold Sweat came into their own, discovering groups like SL Troopers, [[Dynametrix]], Unanimous Decision and Katch 22, whose \"Diary of a Blackman\" was banned by [[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] for using a sound clip from the [[British National Front|National Front]].\n\nIn 1991, [[Hijack (hip hop group)|Hijack]] released ''The Horns of Jericho'' (Rhyme Syndicate Records, 1991) on [[Ice-T]]'s recently formed Rhyme Syndicate label. The first single, \"The Badman Is Robbin'\", was a top 40 hit and they went on sell more than 30,000 albums.\n\nBritish hip hop was affected by the record industry clamping down on [[sampling (music)|sampling]], beginning to charge for the use of samples and prosecuting those who used them without permission. Larger US acts could afford to license samples and still turn a profit for their labels, a luxury not available to many smaller UK artists. One such victim of this was [[Milton Keynes]] group [[the Criminal Minds]]. Their first two releases, the 1990 mini-album ''Guilty as Charged'' and a 1991 EP ''Tales from the Wasteland'' were bogged down by potential sample clearance problems and thus were only ever made available in small numbers, yet rate amongst some of the finest pieces of UK hip hop recorded. As [[breakbeat hardcore]] music started to become very popular in the UK in the early 1990s, the Criminal Minds turned their attention to making this type of music instead.\n\nThe UK hip hop boom never achieved its predicted commercial success. Hijack's ''The Horns of Jericho'' was never released in the US, while record companies dropped artists, citing poor sales and lack of interest. [[Mango Records]] closed down, and the British public began to turn their affections to [[Jungle music|jungle]], a fusion of breakbeat hardcore, hip hop and reggae. Other acts and styles developed from the hip hop scene, resulting in new genres to describe them \u2014 for example [[Massive Attack]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/70844.stm |title=BBC News website, Massive Attack on the net |date=29 March 1998 |accessdate=2 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040509115510/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/70844.stm |archive-date=9 May 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref> with [[trip hop]], or [[Galliano (band)|Galliano]], [[Us3]] and [[Urban Species]] with [[acid jazz]].\n\nIn the period between 1992 and 1995, the only groups to make much impact were Gunshot amd [[The Brotherhood (rap group)|the Brotherhood]]. \nGunshot's 1992 album ''Patriot Games'' was a landmark with tracks such as \"Mind of a Razor\" and \"World War 3\" becoming British hardcore classics.  Formed in the '80s, the Brotherhood released their first record, simply called ''Brotherhood EP'', as a white label in 1991. They went on to release ''Wayz of the Wize'' in 1992, then ''Untitled 93'' and ''XXIII'' in 1993, and ''Hip Hop N' Rap'' in 1994, all on the Bite It! label. None of the records sold in huge numbers but they managed to gain airplay on the [[Tim Westwood]] show and DJ 279's show on [[Choice FM]], gaining them a solid following across the UK. Bite It! also released tracks from artists such as Pauly Ryan and the Scientists of Sound.\n\n===New generation: Late '90s\u2013early '00s===\nFollowing an initial flurry of interest from major record labels in the 1980s, by the early 1990s the scene had moved underground after record companies pulled back. In the mid-1990s hip hop in the UK started to experiment and diversify \u2014 often mutating into different genres entirely, such as [[trip hop]] and began making inroads into the US market.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklists.com/q101-1997.html |title=Q101 Top 101 of 1997 |publisher=Rocklists.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924091722/http://www.rocklists.com/q101-1997.html |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs the old rappers left the scene, a new generation, raised on hip hop and [[electronica]], was coming of age: [[The Herbaliser]] released ''Remedies'' ([[Ninja Tune]], 1995), [[Mr. Scruff]] released the \"Frolic EP Pt 1\" (Pleasure Music, 1995), [[Mark B]] released \"Any More Questions?\" (Jazz Fudge, 1995) and [[DJ Skitz]] released \"Where My Mind Is At/Blessed Be The Manor\" (Ronin Records, 1996) featuring a young rapper called [[Roots Manuva]] on guest vocals who had previously released the single \"Next Type of Motion\" (Sound of Money, 1995).\n\nRecord labels that attempted to merge British hip hop style and sensibilities with modern dance music began to emerge, like [[Rae & Christian|Mark Rae]]'s [[Grand Central Records|Grand Central]] (home to Aim, Rae & Christian, and Fingathing, among others) or [[DJ Vadim]]'s Jazz Fudge. Increasingly, these artists managed to avoid the issues surrounding sampling by making music themselves (bands such as the [[Stereo MCs]] began playing instruments and sampling their own tunes) or searching out more obscure records where a most cost effective licensing deal could be arranged.\n\nBritish hip hop began to go through a renaissance,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/reviews/1482738.stm |title=BBC News website: British hip hop renaissance |first=Barney |last=Rowntree |date=10 August 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2006}}</ref> its style shifting from the hardcore template of its youth and moving into more melodic territory.\n\nThe Brotherhood managed to broker a major deal with Virgin Records in 1995.  Continuing their relationship with Trevor Jackson as their producer, they released 3 singles \u2018Alphabetical Response\u2019, \u2018One Shot\u2019, \u2018Punk Funk\u2019 and their album ''[[Elementalz]]'', all in 1996.  Their work was met with critical acclaim and they toured solidly with American artists including Cypress Hill, The Roots and WuTang, but big record sales seemed to be very elusive and they parted ways with Virgin in 1998.\n[[File:MF Doom The Arches 2.jpg|thumb|255x255px|MF Doom has been ranked as one of the greatest rappers of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/rappers-music-greatest-celebrities-tupac|title=11 Rappers Who Should Be Added To Everyones Playlists|date=2018-11-05|website=The Odyssey Online|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>]]\nIn late 1996 [[Will Ashon]] started up his new [[Ninja Tune]] backed label [[Big Dada]] and planned a roster of performers. Bandit of Birmingham's MSI/Asylum crew informed Will of [[Juice Aleem]] that he was contemplating who could truly represent the ethos of the new label. Ashon was impressed with the demo and agreed to have Aleem on board. The results of this were the first release of the now famous record label: in 1997 Juice featured on Big Dada record label's first ever release[2], \"Misanthropic\", under the pseudonym \"Alpha Prhyme\", a collaboration between himself and [[Luke Vibert]].\n\nIn 1998 [[Mark B]] and Blade released \"Hitmen for Hire EP\", which featured guest appearances from [[Lewis Parker (musician)|Lewis Parker]] and [[Mr Thing]] (of the [[Scratch Perverts]]). The EP was a success, and led to the successful 2001 album ''The Unknown'', which despite never charting in the UK top 75, was still a top 100 success and an even bigger success within its genre. Also, the album spawned the 2001 top 40 single \"Ya Don't See the Signs\", which was a remix by [[Feeder (band)|Feeder]] frontman [[Grant Nicholas]], after the title track was a top 75 hit and Blade with Mark B supported Feeder. The same year, Bristol's Hombr\u00e9 label released the \"2012 EP\" from [[Aspects (band)|Aspects]], a benchmark release within the movement. [[Roots Manuva]], [[Blak Twang]], [[Mud Family]], [[Ti2bs]], [[Task Force (band)|Task Force]], [[Phi Life Cypher]], MSI & Asylum, [[Jeep Beat Collective]] and [[Ty (rapper)|Ty]] all came to the public's attention, while veteran acts [[Rodney P]], [[Demon Boyz|Mike J]], and MC Mell'O' returned to the scene. In 1999, MF Doom released his debut studio album ''[[Operation: Doomsday]]'' which has since been ranked as one of the greatest hip hop albums of all time.\n\n===Underground to mainstream: '00s to 2010s===\nA new generation of artists emerged following the turn of the century, including [[Jehst]], [[Skinnyman]], [[Nicky Spesh]], [[Foreign Beggars]] and Usmaan whom specialise in UK Hiphop/boombap. Notable artists influenced by the boombap sound included the likes of [[Chester P]], [[Rodney P]], [[Braintax]], [[Blak Twang]], [[DanimaL]], [[Lewis Parker (musician)]] and [[Blak Twang|Blak Twang.]] At the same time, a new style of [[electronic music]] emerged in the early 2000s, derivative of [[UK Garage]] and [[jungle]], with influences from [[Dancehall]], [[Drum and bass]] and [[hip hop]]. The new genre was dubbed [[Grime (music)|grime]] (sometimes called eskibeat or sublow) and effectively superseded UK hip hop in both popularity and the mainstream conscious. Notable grime acts include [[Dizzee Rascal]], [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]], [[Kano (rapper)|Kano]], [[Lethal Bizzle]], [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[Skepta]], [[Jme (musician)|Jme]], [[Jammer (rapper)|Jammer]], [[Shystie]], [[Ghetts]] and [[Devlin (rapper)|Devlin]]. Grime music saw some early success in America with Wiley, Kano and Dizzee Rascal, all releasing music across the atlantic. Grime is generally considered to be distinct from hip-hop due to its roots primarily being genres such as UK garage and jungle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2015/11/grime-hip-hop|title=Deeper Than Rap: Grime is Not a Subgenre of Hip-Hop|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914112019/https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2015/11/grime-hip-hop|archive-date=14 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/skepta-grime-and-urban-british-youth-language-a-guide-65611|title=Skepta, grime and urban British youth language: a guide|last=|first=|date=|website=The Conversation|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008174156/http://theconversation.com/skepta-grime-and-urban-british-youth-language-a-guide-65611|archive-date=8 October 2019|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/53gam8/grime-is-approaching-the-breakthrough-moment-hip-hop-reached-in-the-90s|title=Grime is Approaching the Breakthrough Moment Hip-Hop Reached in the 90s|last=|first=|date=2016-12-21|website=Vice|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105013003/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/53gam8/grime-is-approaching-the-breakthrough-moment-hip-hop-reached-in-the-90s|archive-date=5 November 2019|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":05\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/grime-time-what-it-is-and-where-to-find-it-a3247511.html|title=Grime time: What it is and where to find it|last=|first=|date=2016-05-13|website=Standard|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025044957/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/grime-time-what-it-is-and-where-to-find-it-a3247511.html|archive-date=25 October 2019|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"complex2\">{{Cite web|url=http://uk.complex.com/music/2016/06/hip-hop-dancehall-breaking-down-the-origins-of-grime/dizzee-talks-hip-hop-rosenberg|title=Hip-Hop Or Dancehall? Breaking Down The Grime Scene's Roots|website=Complex UK|language=en|accessdate=5 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206103917/http://uk.complex.com/music/2016/06/hip-hop-dancehall-breaking-down-the-origins-of-grime/dizzee-talks-hip-hop-rosenberg|archive-date=6 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2001, [[Roots Manuva]] claimed that British hip hop \"is more healthy\" than American hip-hop, and is about making the music than is it about exploiting wealth or hitting it rich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/roots-manuva-hip-hop-gets-back-to-its-roots-662924.html|title=Roots Manuva: Hip hop gets back to its roots \u2013 Features, Music \u2013 The Independent|website=Web.archive.org|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430124830/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/roots-manuva-hip-hop-gets-back-to-its-roots-662924.html|archivedate=30 April 2009|accessdate=2016-08-09|df=dmy}}</ref>[[File:Flo-dan, Wiley (34882237).jpg|alt=|thumb|240x240px|Wiley was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2018 New Year Honours]] for services to Music.]]Success followed [[The Streets]]' 2002 album ''[[Original Pirate Material]]'', and he became one of the first of the new breed of British hip hop artists to gain respectable sales, though his verbal style resulted in him being shunned by many artists in the scene. Such success has caused a surge in media exposure of other British hip hop acts. Welsh rap group [[Goldie Lookin Chain]] also achieved chart success with their tongue-in-cheek take on hip-hop. Key records such as [[Skinnyman]]'s [[Council Estate of Mind]], and [[Klashnekoff|Klashnekoff's]] [[The Sagas Of...]] were released, cementing the reputations of the artists and opening up the floor for new artists to emerge. Labels [[Low Life Records]], run by prominent political rapper [[Braintax]], and Young N' Restless started and became the starting point for many.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-04-09-london-hip-hop-new-york-in-1994-15-year-anniversary|title=London Hip-Hop's New York in \u201894: The 15-Year Anniversary|last=Oliver|first=M.|website=DJBooth|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105153131/https://djbooth.net/features/2019-04-09-london-hip-hop-new-york-in-1994-15-year-anniversary|archive-date=5 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the same time, just as [[UK garage|Garage]] was losing momentum, [[Grime (music genre)|grime]] was creating interest. Wiley's [[Treddin' on Thin Ice]] was a cornerstone of the genre, and one-time friend Dizzee Rascal won a Mercury Music Prize for his debut [[Boy in da Corner]]. From then on, grime artists were the only MC's for interested record labels, and UK Hip-Hop's momentum dried up.[[File:Skepta & P Diddy (& Chipmunk) Backstage at orange rock corps.png|thumb|280x280px|Chipmunk (left) and Skepta (right) with American rapper [[Sean Combs]] in 2011. Combs has also given recognition to Stormzy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/diddy-shouts-out-stormzy|title=Diddy shouts out Stormzy|last=|first=|date=|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510215716/http://grmdaily.com/diddy-shouts-out-stormzy|archive-date=10 May 2019|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>|alt=]]A new generation of young socially [[conscious hip-hop]] musicians emerged as a counter to the grime scene that many in the UK Hip Hop scene perceived as commercial. These rappers strived to bring attention to both positivity and lyricism as well as the injustices of war, gentrification and racism, following in the tradition of conscious rappers such as [[Nas]], [[Mos Def]] and [[Talib Kweli]]. Amongst this new generation included artists such as [[Klashnekoff]], [[Akala (rapper)|Akala]], [[Lowkey]] and the Poisonous Poets. \n\nThe mid-2000s saw the emergence of Road rap, a genre that took influences from American gangsta rap and focused on crime, gang, or violent themes. Road rap was pioneered by artists such as [[PDC (gang)|PDC]] and [[Giggs (rapper)|Giggs]]' SN1 crew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/grime-dubstep/7901-grime-dubstep/|title=Grime / Dubstep|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424054128/https://pitchfork.com/features/grime-dubstep/7901-grime-dubstep/|archive-date=24 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 2000s, [[Grime (music genre)|grime music]] has entered into a period of stagnation.<ref name=\":3042\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anothermanmag.com/life-culture/10370/a-brief-history-of-grime-as-told-by-dj-target|title=A Brief History of Grime, as Told by DJ Target|last=AnotherMan|website=AnotherMan|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913222453/https://www.anothermanmag.com/life-culture/10370/a-brief-history-of-grime-as-told-by-dj-target|archive-date=13 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":272\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/10/01/the-surprising-survival-of-grime|title=The Surprising Survival of Grime|last=Hsu|first=Hua|date=2018-09-24|access-date=2019-09-13|language=en|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909050605/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/10/01/the-surprising-survival-of-grime|archive-date=9 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This led to an emergence of acts that, while influenced by or initially started out making grime, were moving into a more commercialised, hip-hop influenced form of music. Artists from this new wave included [[N-Dubz]], [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[Tinie Tempah]], and [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]] (later known as Chip) who emerged in the late 2000s to great commercial success. Tinchy Stryder scored two number ones with songs [[Number 1 (Tinchy Stryder song)|Number 1]] and [[Never Leave You]] and became the best-selling British solo artist of 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fmq4 |title=Music \u2013 Review of Tinchy Stryder \u2013 Catch 22 |publisher=BBC |date=2009-08-17 |accessdate=2014-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109182218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fmq4 |archive-date=9 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following year continued the success of the previous, with acts like [[Professor Green]] and [[Tinie Tempah]] breaking through to even bigger commercial success and also critical appreciation. The debut album from [[Tinie Tempah]] called [[Disc-Overy]] went to number one in the UK album chart and was certified platinum on 1 March 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.jumpoff.tv/2011/03/03/tinie-tempah-discovery-goes-platinum/ |title=JumpOff.TV |publisher=Uk.jumpoff.tv |date=2009-02-05 |accessdate=2014-02-24 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He also won a [[Brit Award]] for his number one single \"[[Pass Out (song)|Pass Out]]\". Rapper [[Plan B (musician)|Plan B]] found success with his 2010 Hip Hop and Soul fusion album [[The Defamation of Strickland Banks]], followed by the soundtrack album ''[[Ill Manors (album)|Ill Manors]]'' in 2012, both of which peaked at number 1 in the [[UK Albums Chart]]. In 2014, Scottish alternative hip-hop trio [[Young Fathers]] won the Mercury Music Prize for their album [[Dead]]. The album entered the UK chart at 35 after they won the award. [[Riz Ahmed]], also known as Riz MC, was featured in the song \"[[Immigrants (We Get the Job Done)]]\" in ''[[The Hamilton Mixtape]]'', which topped the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/12/19/rogue-one-star-riz-ahmed-shares-childhood-star-wars-drawings/|title=Rogue One star Riz Ahmed shares childhood Star Wars drawings: 'Keep your inner child alive'|work=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=22 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221214501/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/12/19/rogue-one-star-riz-ahmed-shares-childhood-star-wars-drawings/|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2017 MTV Video Music Awards]] (VMAs), \"Immigrants\" won the award for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Video with a Social Message|Best Fight Against the System]].<ref name=\"vmas\">{{cite web|url=http://people.com/music/mtv-vmas-complete-winners-list/|title=See the Complete MTV VMAs 2017 Winners List|work=People|access-date=20 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921020257/http://people.com/music/mtv-vmas-complete-winners-list/|archive-date=21 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010 and onwards ===\nThe early 2010s saw the emergence of UK [[afrobeats]], led by artists such as [[Mista Silva]], Kwamz, [[Fuse ODG]], and Timbo.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/xwddaq/why-this-is-such-an-exciting-time-for-the-afrobeats-scene-in-the-uk|title=why this is such an exciting time for the afrobeats scene in the uk|last=McQuaid|first=Ian|date=2017-03-24|website=I-D|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721164205/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/xwddaq/why-this-is-such-an-exciting-time-for-the-afrobeats-scene-in-the-uk|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/04/25/j-hus-fader-cover-story-interview-afrobeats|title=J Hus Is The Sound Of Diaspora's Boomerang|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108232841/https://www.thefader.com/2017/04/25/j-hus-fader-cover-story-interview-afrobeats|archive-date=8 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/53ndxk/j-hus-interview-2017-common-sense|title=No One Is Like J Hus|last=Bassil|first=Ryan|last2=Lewis|first2=Jake|date=2017-05-12|website=Vice|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722030122/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/53ndxk/j-hus-interview-2017-common-sense|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Around the same time, artists such as [[Sneakbo]] and Timbo were incorporating melodic rap and Caribbean influences into their music. The foundation set by these artists would later be a major influence on [[Afroswing]], a genre that emerged around 2014 derivative of UK afrobeats while carrying influences from [[grime music|grime]], [[dancehall]], UK hip hop, and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/01/a-brief-history-of-afro-tinged-british-rap|title=Saluting The Pioneers: A Brief History Of Afro-Tinged Rap In The UK|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527045035/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/01/a-brief-history-of-afro-tinged-british-rap|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe early 2010s also saw the emergence of an underground UK hip hop scene emulating the earlier wave of 2000s rappers such as Jehst, Task Force, King Kashmere, MysDiggi and Skinnyman. With complex lyrics and rhyme schemes and '90s New York [[boom bap]] influenced production, [[High Focus Records]] was instrumental in bringing this sound to a wider audience. The label was founded in 2010 by London rapper Fliptrix<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://nationofbillions.com/the-rise-rise-of-high-focus-records|title=The Rise & Rise Of High Focus Records|website=A Nation of Billions|access-date=2020-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619110810/https://nationofbillions.com/the-rise-rise-of-high-focus-records|archive-date=19 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and key members of the larger High Focus crew have included [[The Four Owls]], Dirty Dike, [[Ocean Wisdom]], Jam Baxter and Dabbla. \n\nArtists from the label have managed to build a sizeable following despite remaining underground, having performed to crowds of 25,000+ across Europe<ref name=\":10\" />, played the famous [[Reading and Leeds Festivals|Reading and Leeds]] festivals in the UK<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gigwise.com/videos/94371/|title=NSFW: Dirty Dike talks drugs, dream jobs and getting a reaction|website=www.gigwise.com|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> and seen many tracks reaching multiple millions of views on YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCsdSVUYgClqB4zGU_yfQSAw|title=HighFocusTV|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121211812/https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCsdSVUYgClqB4zGU_yfQSAw|archive-date=21 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, The Four Owls collaborated with highly respected<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/lectures/dj-premier-you-know-my-steez|title=DJ Premier|website=www.redbullmusicacademy.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109201349/https://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/lectures/dj-premier-you-know-my-steez/|archive-date=9 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> US producer [[DJ Premier]] for their track ''Think Twice'' . [[Brit Awards|BRIT Award]] winning singer-songwriter [[Rag'n'Bone Man]] also released two albums on the label in 2011 and 2014 - \"Put That Soul on Me\" (a collaboration with Dirty Dike) and \"Dog n Bone\" with Four Owls member and rapper/producer Leaf Dog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.high-focus.com/home/artists/rag-n-bone-man/|title=Rag'n'Bone Man|last=Focus|first=High|website=Official Website of High Focus Records|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726092813/http://www.high-focus.com/home/artists/rag-n-bone-man/|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> These albums are what eventually led to his signing with major label [[Columbia Records]], however Rag'n'Bone Man has continued to feature on High Focus records releases such as the track \"Mask\" from Jam Baxter's album Touching Scenes in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wordplaymagazine.com/blog-1/2018/11/19/jam-baxter-mask-feat-ragnbone-man-amp-og-rootz-prod-by-chemo|title=Jam Baxter - Mask Feat. Rag'n'Bone Man & OG Rootz Prod. by Chemo|website=WORDPLAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\nBy 2014, grime music was also experiencing a resurgence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/student/student-life/music-film/grime-music-is-now-the-sound-of-british-youth-and-things-are-only-beginning-a6747216.html|title=Grime is the now sound of British youth - and things are only beginning|date=2015-11-24|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003906/https://www.independent.co.uk/student/student-life/music-film/grime-music-is-now-the-sound-of-british-youth-and-things-are-only-beginning-a6747216.html|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> While hip hop did not immediately benefit from this, the rise of grime has been credited for re-opening the doors for competing genres such as hip hop and afroswing that were also on the rise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-45017057|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509182724/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-45017057|url-status=dead|archive-date=2019-05-09|title=Is grime dead? Or has it 'just gone back underground'? - BBC News|date=2019-05-09|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Acts that would rise within the hip hop scene within the following years include [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]], [[Kojey Radical]], [[Slowthai]], [[Little Simz]], and [[Loyle Carner]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/33396/1/meet-the-artists-shaping-the-uk-hip-hop-scene|title=Meet the artists shaping the UK hip hop scene|last=Dazed|date=2016-10-18|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003837/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/33396/1/meet-the-artists-shaping-the-uk-hip-hop-scene|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/10-rising-uk-hip-hop-acts-you-should-be-listening-to-right-now-1427595393.html|title=10 Rising UK Hip Hop Acts You Should Be Listening to Right Now|date=2015-07-06|website=PAPER|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003844/https://www.papermag.com/10-rising-uk-hip-hop-acts-you-should-be-listening-to-right-now-1427595393.html|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djmag.com/news/dave-wins-2019-mercury-prize-debut-album-psychodrama|title=Dave wins the 2019 Mercury Prize with debut album &#039;Psychodrama&#039;|date=2019-09-19|website=DJMag.com|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003854/https://djmag.com/news/dave-wins-2019-mercury-prize-debut-album-psychodrama|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Dave released a \"Blackbox freestyle\" in 2015 which helped him rise to prominence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/dave-interview-rapper-2157944-2157944|title=Dave: the genre-splicing rapper talks meeting Drake and his debut album|date=2017-11-10|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724003807/https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/dave-interview-rapper-2157944-2157944|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The following year, Dave was noticed by Canadian rapper Drake, who later featured on a remix of his song \"Wanna Know\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2016-11-01-drake-impact-on-wanna-know|title=Does the Drizzy Effect Exist?|last=Bradley|first=Brent|website=DJBooth|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003837/https://djbooth.net/features/2016-11-01-drake-impact-on-wanna-know|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/24/dave-the-streatham-rapper-getting-props-from-drake|title=A rapper called Dave: the \u2018normal\u2019 Streatham boy who\u2019s on Drake\u2019s radar|last=Collins|first=Hattie|date=2017-03-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003900/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/24/dave-the-streatham-rapper-getting-props-from-drake|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Skepta 2 F.I.B. 2016.jpg|alt=|thumb|303x303px|Skepta's [[Konnichiwa (Skepta album)|''Konnichiwa'']] (2016) won the Mercury Prize and was named the Best Album of 2016 by [[Apple Music]].]][[File:Stormzy - Openair Frauenfeld 2019 05.jpg|thumb|200x200px|Stormzy's ''Gang Signs & Prayer'' is certified [[BPI certification|Platinum]] by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI).|alt=|left]][[Stormzy]], an artist that came up out of the grime scene, released his debut album, ''[[Gang Signs & Prayer]]'', on 24 February 2017. The album was a mixture of grime, hip-hop, and R&B,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/facts/stormzy/debut-album/|title=Stormzy's debut album 'Gang Signs & Prayers' is released on 23rd February 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=Capital Xtra|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216204442/http://www.capitalxtra.com/features/facts/stormzy/debut-album/|archive-date=16 February 2018|access-date=}}</ref> and was the first 'grime' album to reach number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]]. In February 2018, ''Gang Signs & Prayer'' won [[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]] at the [[2018 Brit Awards]]. He has reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] a total of two times; firstly as part of \"Artists for Grenfell\" on 23 June 2017 with song \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)#Artists for Grenfell Tower charity single|Bridge Over Troubled Water]]\", and secondly with his own solo single \"[[Vossi Bop]]\", which debuted at number-one upon its entry, ahead of \"[[Me!]]\" by [[Taylor Swift]] featuring [[Brendon Urie]] by some 500 combined sales.<ref name=\"Noisey\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/neanbb/stormzy-number-one-vossi-bop-stream-buy-2019|title=Stream \"Vossi Bop,\" Buy \"Vossi Bop\" and Get Stormzy to Number 1|website=[[Noisey]]|last=Mokoena|first=Tshepo|date=30 April 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503204359/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/neanbb/stormzy-number-one-vossi-bop-stream-buy-2019|archive-date=3 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSkepta, who also emerged from the grime scene, began collaborating with American hip hop group [[ASAP Mob]]. He featured with [[ASAP Rocky]] on the song \"[[Praise the Lord (Da Shine)]]\", the second single from his third studio album ''[[Testing (album)|Testing]]'' on 26 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/2018/5/31/20824909/the-story-behind-a-ap-rocky-s-praise-the-lord-da-shine-is-incredible|title=The story behind A$AP Rocky's \"Praise the Lord (Da Shine)\" is incredible|last=Bristout|first=Ralph|date=2018-05-31|website=REVOLT|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003854/https://www.revolt.tv/2018/5/31/20824909/the-story-behind-a-ap-rocky-s-praise-the-lord-da-shine-is-incredible|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the third collaboration between both artists, following Skepta's appearance on ''[[Cozy Tapes Vol. 1: Friends]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.konbini.com/en/entertainment-2/asap-mob-drop-cozy-tapes-vol-1-featuring-skepta/|title=A$AP Mob Drop 'Cozy Tapes Vol. 1' Featuring Skepta And More|website=Konbini - All Pop Everything!|language=fr|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003849/https://www.konbini.com/en/entertainment-2/asap-mob-drop-cozy-tapes-vol-1-featuring-skepta/|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and ASAP Rocky's appearance on Skepta's ''Vicious EP'' in 2017, which also featured [[ASAP Nast]], [[Lil B]], and [[Smoke Boys|Section Boys]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/10/30/skepta-drops-vicious-ep|title=Skepta drops surprise Vicious EP|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710125338/https://www.thefader.com/2017/10/30/skepta-drops-vicious-ep|archive-date=10 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The song was successful in a number of countries, peaking at number 45 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and number 18 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. It was later certified [[RIAA certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI). Skepta also collaborated with American rapper [[Playboi Carti]] on the single \"Lean 4 Real\" from his debut studio album [[Die Lit]], also released in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://versus.uk.com/2018/05/listen-skepta-playboi-cartis-new-banger-lean-4-real/|title=Listen to Skepta and Playboi Carti's New Banger, \"Lean 4 Real\"|date=2018-05-11|website=VERSUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003850/https://versus.uk.com/2018/05/listen-skepta-playboi-cartis-new-banger-lean-4-real/|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Dave did a freestyle on American radio station [[KPWR|Power 106 Los Angeles]] which has accumulated over 1,000,000 views on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/up-and-coming-uk-rapper-dave-kills-la-leakers-freestyle-news.31111.html|title=Up-And-Coming UK Rapper Dave Kills LA Leakers Freestyle|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219003846/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/up-and-coming-uk-rapper-dave-kills-la-leakers-freestyle-news.31111.html|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, Dave achieved his first UK number-one hit with \"[[Funky Friday]]\" which featured British rapper [[Fredo (British rapper)|Fredo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/daves-funky-friday-ft-fredo-debuts-at-number-1-im-speechless-right-now-__24437/|title=Dave \"speechless\" as Funky Friday debuts at Number 1|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107163221/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/daves-funky-friday-ft-fredo-debuts-at-number-1-im-speechless-right-now-__24437/|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Dave's debut album, ''[[Psychodrama (album)|Psychodrama]]'' (2019), debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and became the most-streamed first-week British rap album in the UK with a total of 23.6 million streams. The album was highly acclaimed and won Dave a [[Mercury Prize]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/19/dave-wins-mercury-prize-2019-album-psychodrama|title=Mercury prize 2019: rapper Dave wins for 'exceptional' Psychodrama|last=Snapes|first=Laura|date=2019-09-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216113634/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/19/dave-wins-mercury-prize-2019-album-psychodrama|archive-date=16 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSlowthai released his debut studio album, ''[[Nothing Great About Britain]],'' in 2019. The album was nominated for the [[Mercury Prize]]. He performed at the 2019 Mercury Prize ceremony, where he controversially held a fake severed head of British Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/rapper-slowthai-holds-up-fake-boris-johnson-head-on-stage-at-mercury-prize-ceremony-11814567|title=Rapper slowthai holds up fake Boris Johnson head on stage at Mercury Prize ceremony|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206151253/https://news.sky.com/story/rapper-slowthai-holds-up-fake-boris-johnson-head-on-stage-at-mercury-prize-ceremony-11814567|archive-date=6 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Little Simz also released ''[[Grey Area (album)|Grey Area]]'' in 2019 to much acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/little-simz-grey-area-review-2453838|title=Little Simz \u2013 'Grey Area' review|date=2019-02-25|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128041322/https://www.nme.com/reviews/little-simz-grey-area-review-2453838|archive-date=28 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Road rap==\nRoad rap (also known as British gangsta rap or simply UK rap) is a genre of music pioneered in [[South London]], primarily in [[Brixton]] and [[Peckham]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/nepwa8/tiny-boost-comeback-interview-2018|title=Tiny Boost Is Rapping for All the Streets and the People in Them|last=Bassil|first=Ryan|last2=Garcia|first2=Francisco|date=2018-11-13|website=Vice|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033250/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/nepwa8/tiny-boost-comeback-interview-2018|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2015/05/27/20-essential-road-rap-tracks/|title=20 Essential Road Rap Tracks|last=aidanbnsn|date=2015-05-27|website=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033249/https://www.factmag.com/2015/05/27/20-essential-road-rap-tracks/|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The genre was pioneered by groups such as [[PDC (gang)|PDC]], SMS (South Muslim Soldiers), Northstar and artists such as [[Giggs (rapper)|Giggs]] and [[K Koke]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/grime-dubstep/7901-grime-dubstep/|title=Grime / Dubstep|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424054128/https://pitchfork.com/features/grime-dubstep/7901-grime-dubstep/|archive-date=24 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/01/influential-uk-rap-mixtapes/|title=7 Mixtapes That Laid UK Rap\u2019s Foundations|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221074920/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/01/influential-uk-rap-mixtapes/|archive-date=21 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The genre came to the fore as a backlash against the perceived commercialisation of [[Grime (music)|grime]] in the mid-late 2000s in London.<ref name=\"factmag.com\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.factmag.com/2012/04/27/end-of-the-road-the-rise-of-road-rap-and-the-uncertain-future-of-the-hardcore-continuum/ |title=End of the road: the rise of road rap and the uncertain future of the hardcore continuum |publisher=Factmag.com |date=2012-04-27 |accessdate=2015-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812053450/http://www.factmag.com/2012/04/27/end-of-the-road-the-rise-of-road-rap-and-the-uncertain-future-of-the-hardcore-continuum/ |archive-date=12 August 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The genre came to prominence around 2007 with the rise of Giggs.<ref name=\":2\" /> Road rap retained the explicit depictions of violence and British gang culture found in some early grime music and combines it with a musical style more similar to American [[gangsta rap]] than the [[Sound system (DJ)|sound system]] influenced music of grime, dubstep, UK garage, jungle, reggae and dub.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web |author=Dan Hancox |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/aug/12/rap-riots-professor-green-lethal-bizzle-wiley |title=Rap responds to the riots: 'They have to take us seriously' &#124; Music |publisher=Theguardian.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226150625/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/aug/12/rap-riots-professor-green-lethal-bizzle-wiley |archive-date=26 December 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGangs played a large part in the genre, with gangs such as Mashtown based in [[Hackney, London|Hackney]], Star Gang (formed by [[Tottenham Mandem]] members), the [[Peckham Boys]] based in Peckham (with its various subsets such as SN1, PYG, and OPB) and [[Gas Gang (Brixton gang)|GAS Gang]], based in Brixton, becoming notable in the road rap scene during the 2000s.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/peckham-boys-black-gang|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121217145757/https://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/peckham-boys-black-gang|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-12-17|title=Peckham Boys (PB) - www.londonstreetgangs.com|date=2012-12-17|website=archive.fo|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe road rap scene centres around mixtape releases and YouTube videos with some of the genres more popular acts getting mainstream recognition.<ref name=\"factmag.com\" /> The genre has been criticised for the relentless nihilism and violence in its lyrics as well as its links to gangs and gun crime with many rappers serving prison sentences.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" /><ref>[http://djsemtex.com/blog/2010/01/08/giggs-nme-interview/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521235215/http://djsemtex.com/blog/2010/01/08/giggs-nme-interview/|date=21 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/rapper-kyze-jailed-for-shooting-178357 |title=Rapper Kyze jailed for shooting \u2013 Mirror Online |publisher=Mirror.co.uk |date=2011-04-18 |accessdate=2015-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515043730/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/rapper-kyze-jailed-for-shooting-178357 |archive-date=15 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In keeping with grime, road rap has suffered from preemptive policing with Giggs claiming that the [[Metropolitan Police]] have set out to deny him the opportunity to make a living from music having banned him from touring.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sam Wolfson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/05/giggs-when-will-it-stop?CMP=twt_gu |title=Giggs: prison, police harassment, cancelled tours \u2013 When Will It Stop &#124; Music |publisher=Theguardian.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826122022/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/05/giggs-when-will-it-stop?CMP=twt_gu |archive-date=26 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2011, Stigs was served the first ever gang injunction that banned him from rapping about anything that may encourage violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/22/the-war-against-rap-censoring-drill-may-seem-radical-but-its-not-new|title=The war against rap: censoring drill may seem radical but it's not new|last=Hancox|first=Dan|date=2018-06-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161711/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/22/the-war-against-rap-censoring-drill-may-seem-radical-but-its-not-new|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 2010s, the American genre [[Drill music|drill]] began to emerge in the UK, pushed by artists such as 150, 67, and [[Smoke Boys|Section Boyz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/gypwa7/uk-gangsta-drill-road-rap-67-section-boyz-giggs|title=Don\u2019t Call It Road Rap: When Drill, UK Accents and Street Life Collide|last=McQuaid|first=Ian|date=2017-06-14|website=Vice|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718211023/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/gypwa7/uk-gangsta-drill-road-rap-67-section-boyz-giggs|archive-date=18 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> UK drill has been referred to as subgenre of road rap due to the influence it's had on the genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/different-types-of-hip-hop-guide|title=A guide to the many styles of hip-hop, from hyphy to horrorcore|website=Red Bull|language=en|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033246/https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/different-types-of-hip-hop-guide|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bigissue.com/culture/music/police-have-banned-a-london-rap-group-from-making-drill-music/|title=Police have banned a London rap group from making drill music|date=2018-06-19|website=The Big Issue|language=en|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033249/https://www.bigissue.com/culture/music/police-have-banned-a-london-rap-group-from-making-drill-music/|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5355f564-288a-11e9-88a4-c32129756dd8|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033248/https://www.ft.com/content/5355f564-288a-11e9-88a4-c32129756dd8|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Road rap also went on to influence [[afroswing]], which emerged in the mid-2010s.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNotable road rap artists include:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Blade Brown]]\n*[[Fredo (British rapper)|Fredo]]\n*[[Giggs (rapper)|Giggs]]\n*[[Jaja Soze]]\n*[[K Koke]]\n*[[Krept & Konan]]\n*[[Nines (rapper)|Nines]]\n*[[Sneakbo]]\n{{div col end}}Notable road rap groups include:{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Gas Gang (Brixton gang)|GAS Gang]]<ref name=\"20 Essential Road Rap Tracks\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2015/05/27/20-essential-road-rap-tracks/|title=20 Essential Road Rap Tracks|date=27 May 2015|access-date=4 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033249/https://www.factmag.com/2015/05/27/20-essential-road-rap-tracks/|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[PDC (gang)|PDC]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/nepwa8/tiny-boost-comeback-interview-2018|title=Tiny Boost Is Rapping for All the Streets and the People in Them|first=Francisco|last=Garcia|date=13 November 2018|access-date=4 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804033250/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/nepwa8/tiny-boost-comeback-interview-2018|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Peckham Boys|PYG (Peckham Young Gunners)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/22/the-war-against-rap-censoring-drill-may-seem-radical-but-its-not-new|title=The war against rap: censoring drill may seem radical but it's not new|first=Dan|last=Hancox|date=22 June 2018|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=4 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161711/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/22/the-war-against-rap-censoring-drill-may-seem-radical-but-its-not-new|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"20 Essential Road Rap Tracks\"/>\n* Roadside G's<ref name=\"20 Essential Road Rap Tracks\"/>\n*[[Peckham Boys|SN1 (Spare No-1)]]<ref name=\"20 Essential Road Rap Tracks\"/>\n*[[Usual Suspects Gang]]<ref name=\"20 Essential Road Rap Tracks\"/>{{div col end}}\n\n== UK drill ==\n\n===Stylistic origins===\nUK drill<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2018/01/uk-drill-sl-harlem-spartans-67-essay|title=Get Familiar with UK Drill, the New Sound Exploding on the Streets of London|work=PigeonsandPlanes|access-date=2018-03-18|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319090713/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2018/01/uk-drill-sl-harlem-spartans-67-essay|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/35706/1/uk-drill-artists-and-crews|title=Inside UK Drill, London\u2019s Hyper-Local DIY Sound|last=Dazed|date=2017-04-25|work=Dazed|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309135634/http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/35706/1/uk-drill-artists-and-crews|archive-date=9 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/04/27/uk-drill-chicago-brixton/|title=From Chicago to Brixton: The Surprising Rise of UK Drill|date=2017-04-27|work=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324130941/http://www.factmag.com/2017/04/27/uk-drill-chicago-brixton/|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> is a subgenre of drill music and [[road rap]] that originated in the South London district of [[Brixton]] from 2012 onwards. Borrowing heavily from the style of [[Chicago]] [[drill music]], UK drill artists often rap about violent and hedonistic criminal lifestyles.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/67-interview-this-is-not-a-gang-this-is-a-logo-this-is-a-company-this-is-a-brand-a3620276.html|title=67 Interview: 'This Is Not a Gang. This Is a Brand'|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319090523/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/67-interview-this-is-not-a-gang-this-is-a-logo-this-is-a-company-this-is-a-brand-a3620276.html|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Typically, those who create this style of music are affiliated with gangs or come from socioeconomically-deprived neighborhoods where crime is a way of life for many.<ref name=\":0\" /> UK drill music is closely related to road rap, a British style of gangsta rap that became popular in the years prior to the existence of drill. <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":22\"/><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/gypwa7/uk-gangsta-drill-road-rap-67-section-boyz-giggs|title=Don\u2019t Call It Road Rap: When Drill, UK Accents and Street Life Collide|date=2017-06-14|work=Noisey|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en-uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319084907/https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/gypwa7/uk-gangsta-drill-road-rap-67-section-boyz-giggs|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Musically, UK drill often exhibits violent language and provocative lyrics.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThere is common debate about which Brixton and surrounding area group initially pioneered the UK drill sound. Those associated with gangs 150 and Uptop and a majority of fans of the genre believe that Angell Town Estate, Brixton, is the true birthplace of UK drill, particularly rappers Stizzy Stickz, Grizzy, M Dargg & Perm being dedicated exponents of the early style, along with and mentored by former members of [[PDC (gang)|PDC]] (Peel Dem Crew / Poverty Driven Children).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/angell-town-the-exgang-members-who-have-turned-their-lives-around-and-are-inspiring-others-to-do-the-a3071326.html|title=Angell Town: The ex-gang members who have turned their lives around and are inspiring others to do the same|work=London Evening Standard|access-date=2015-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815105252/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/angell-town-the-exgang-members-who-have-turned-their-lives-around-and-are-inspiring-others-to-do-the-a3071326.html|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Red Bull\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/uk-drill-FAQ-history-artists-and-future|title=UK drill FAQ: History, facts & future of the rap genre|work=Red Bull|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806213411/https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/uk-drill-FAQ-history-artists-and-future|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, on the flip side, it is argued that group 67 of the New Park Road area and surroundings furthered the sound enough to make UK drill an exclusively British export, and finally distance it from the initial Chicago sound it seemed to heavily draw inspiration from in its early days and foundation. Producers Carns Hill<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/10/carns-hill-trench-interview|work=[[Complex (Magazine)|Complex]]|title=According To UK Rap Producer Carns Hill, His 'Drill' Sound Happened Almost By Accident|date=12 Oct 2017|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102708/https://www.complex.com/music/2017/10/carns-hill-trench-interview|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> (who crafted instrumentals for many of 67's early songs), and QUIETPVCK (who worked closely by 150, 410 & Uptop members in their early era) are widely considered to be two of the main pioneering producers of the genre with their unique and innovative alternatives to the Chicago Drill sound.<ref name=\"Red Bull\"/>\n\nUK drill has developed a different production style than Chicago, taking influence from earlier British genres such as [[Grime (music genre)|grime]] and [[UK garage]], so much so that it has been called \"the New Grime\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://theblackscotsman.wordpress.com/2016/07/25/meet-mazza/|title=Meet Mazza : The Producer Taking Drill To A New Level|date=2016-07-25|access-date=2018-03-19|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319084854/https://theblackscotsman.wordpress.com/2016/07/25/meet-mazza/|archive-date=2018-03-19|language=en-US}}</ref> and drill producer Carns Hill has commented that it needs a new name. AXL Beats explained that the 808's and fast-tempo snares are derivative of grime music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/drake-war-drill-producer-axl-beats-interview|title=How Drake Ended Up Rapping on a Drill Beat: An Interview With \u201cWar\u201d Producer AXL Beats|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226010742/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/drake-war-drill-producer-axl-beats-interview|archive-date=26 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Mazza, a UK drill producer, disagreed with the \"new grime\" label, maintaining that although drill and grime share the same energy, rawness, and originated in a similar fashion, the two genres are distinct in their own ways.<ref name=\":5\" /> Both genres typically utilize a tempo of approximately 140 [[Beats per minute|bpm]].<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2018/01/uk-drill-sl-harlem-spartans-67-essay|title=Get Familiar With UK Drill, the New Sound Exploding on the Streets of London|website=Complex|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611131706/https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2018/01/uk-drill-sl-harlem-spartans-67-essay|archive-date=2019-06-11|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/04/27/uk-drill-chicago-brixton/|title=From Chicago to Brixton: The Surprising Rise of UK Drill|date=2017-04-27|work=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|access-date=2018-03-19|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324130941/http://www.factmag.com/2017/04/27/uk-drill-chicago-brixton/|archive-date=2018-03-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":23\" /> Autotune, unlike American drill, is largely absent within UK drill, with British drill artists utilising a much harsher, stripped-back delivery indebted to grime and earlier road rap. UK drill rappers have also taken on a more allusive, ironic lyrical style; taken on mainly because of the attention attracted from the mainstream media, and also the police; due to its previously much more brazen and direct nature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThough a majority of UK drill artists hail from the capital (which can be attributed in part due to the much larger population of London, in comparison to other British cities), it is not restricted to London alone as the genres sole production hub in terms of emerging talents and dissemination of the sound. Artists around the country have appeared and become prominent creators within the scene, such as SmuggzyAce and S.White of [[Birmingham]] group \"23 Drillas\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/watch-23-drillas-rappers-taunt-15176772|title=23 Drillas rappers taunt armed police after gangsters jailed|date=2018-09-24|access-date=2019-04-27|language=en-US|website=Birmingham Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427133823/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/watch-23-drillas-rappers-taunt-15176772|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and Samurai of [[Manchester]] group \"40\", picking up traction and views for their musical work online via video sharing and music streaming platforms and becoming generally accepted outside of the origins of the main London scene, helping expand the genres reach across the country. Another notable artist whose journey began outside of London is Scouse Trappin Tremz (often shortened to just Scouse Tremz or Tremz) of [[Liverpool]], who has frequently collaborated with North London rapper A1FromThe9.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=clFobsTnwEA|title=P110 \u2013 Tremz Ft. A1FromThe9 \u2013 Too illa [Net Video]|date=2016-02-15|people=Tremz & A1fromThe9|language=|publisher=P110 Media|trans-title=|access-date=2019-04-27|ref=|quote=|medium=}}</ref>\n\n===Culture===\nA notable activity popularized among UK drill fans is speculating on social media about which drill artist has been sent to prison or what information can be gathered about which \"GM\" (gang member) has been violated (disrespected / degraded) by whom, adding to what is known as the \"scoreboard\" (how many people a particular group have collectively stabbed). The commonly used terms ''\"3 The Mandem\"'' and also ''\"Fresh out the can\"'' are observably used by UK Drill rappers, the first one meaning to ''\"Free those in prison\"'' and the latter referring to people ''\"Recently out of / released from prison\"''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nUK drill groups often engage in disputes with each other, sometimes violent, often releasing multiple disrespectful tracks. Notable disputes include [[Zone 2 (music group)|Zone 2]] versus Moscow 17,<ref name=\":22\"/> 150 versus [[67 (rap group)|67]],<ref name=\":22\"/> [[OFB (group)|OFB]]/NPK<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/thugs-rap-i-you-coffin-20945919 |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127233645/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/thugs-rap-i-you-coffin-20945919 |archive-date=27 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> versus WG/N9 and SMG versus 814 (a member of 814, Showkey, was stabbed to death in 2016 in an unrelated incident<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/peckham-murder-15yearold-arrested-after-rapper-showkey-stabbed-to-death-in-peckham-a3313846.html|title=Teenager arrested after 16-year-old stabbed to death|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319090320/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/peckham-murder-15yearold-arrested-after-rapper-showkey-stabbed-to-death-in-peckham-a3313846.html|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>).\n\nUK drill received widespread attention outside of Britain in 2017 when comedian [[Michael Dapaah]] released the novelty song \"[[Man's Not Hot]]\". The track samples a beat made by UK drill producers GottiOnEm and Mazza; it was first used by drill group 86 on its song \"Lurk\", and later [[67 (rap group)|67]] with \"Let's Lurk\" featuring [[Giggs (rapper)|Giggs]].<ref name=\"Scotsman\">{{Cite web|url=https://theblackscotsman.wordpress.com/2016/07/25/meet-mazza/|title=Meet Mazza : The Producer Taking Drill To A New Level|last=Scotsman|first=Author The Black|date=2016-07-25|language=en|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319084854/https://theblackscotsman.wordpress.com/2016/07/25/meet-mazza/|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/a3m7nk/uk-drill-holiday-guide|title=A Guide to Explaining UK Drill to Your Family Over the Holidays|last=Bassil|first=Ryan|last2=Mokoena|first2=Tshepo|date=2018-12-20|website=Vice|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807014009/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/a3m7nk/uk-drill-holiday-guide|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/bj9378/welcome-to-the-golden-age-of-drill|title=welcome to the golden age of drill|last=McQuaid|first=Ian|last2=Lanigan|first2=Roisin|date=2019-06-21|website=I-D|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802213148/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/bj9378/welcome-to-the-golden-age-of-drill|archive-date=2 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy & legal issues===\nThe genre's violent lyrics have been cited by police, MPs, journalists and others in positions of potentially significant influence as the reason for a climb in the rate of knife crimes in London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/drill-music-london-stabbings-shootings-rap-67-abra-cadabra-comment-government-a8305516.html|title=Inside UK drill, the demonised rap representing a marginalised generation|date=2018-04-15|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425033428/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/drill-music-london-stabbings-shootings-rap-67-abra-cadabra-comment-government-a8305516.html|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/drill-the-demonic-music-linked-to-rise-in-youth-murders-0bkbh3csk|title=Drill, the \u2018demonic\u2019 music linked to rise in youth murders|last=Andrew&nbsp;Gilligan|first=Shingi Mararike, Tom Harper and|date=2018-04-08|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en|issn=0956-1382|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425114511/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/drill-the-demonic-music-linked-to-rise-in-youth-murders-0bkbh3csk|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In one instance, then 17-year-old rapper Junior Simpson, better known as M-Trap, who had written lyrics about knife attacks, was part of a four-person group that stabbed a 15-year-old boy to death, for which he received a life sentence.<ref name=Beaumont-Thomas/> Judge Anthony Leonard QC told Simpson, \"You suggested [the lyrics] were just for show but I do not believe that, and I suspect you were waiting for the right opportunity for an attack.\"<ref name=Beaumont-Thomas>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/apr/09/uk-drill-music-london-wave-violent-crime|title=Is UK drill music really behind London's wave of violent crime?|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|date=2018-04-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614042904/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/apr/09/uk-drill-music-london-wave-violent-crime|archive-date=14 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[YouTube]] reported that it had deleted more than half of the \"violent\" music videos identified by senior police officers as problematic. Metropolitan Police Commissioner [[Cressida Dick]] blamed some videos for fuelling a surge in murders and violent crime in London, singling out drill music. YouTube said that more than 30 clips had been removed. The cause of the deletion of UK drill videos drive from a stop and search done on the West London gang 1011, where they were reported to be on a ''ride out'' to retaliate against the opposition. Banning drill caused outrage in the community and caused a slight lull in production of the music.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-44281586|work=[[BBC News]]|title=YouTube deletes 'violent' music videos|date=29 May 2018|access-date=21 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727235656/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-44281586|archive-date=27 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]]'' magazine stated in an article on UK Drill producers M1OnTheBeat & MKThePlug:\n<blockquote>...\"Drill is this generation\u2019s furious response against the Conservative government\u2019s decimation of state support for the most vulnerable communities under austerity\".<ref name=\"FACT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.factmag.com/2018/08/02/mk-the-plug-and-m1-on-the-beat-are-uk-drills-brightest-hope/|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]]|title=Making the banned: MK The Plug and M1 On The Beat are UK drill\u2019s brightest hope|date=12 Aug 2018|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713230018/https://www.factmag.com/2018/08/02/mk-the-plug-and-m1-on-the-beat-are-uk-drills-brightest-hope/|archive-date=13 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn late 2018, [[South London]]-born drill MC and aspiring [[2020 London mayoral election|Mayor of London]] Drillminister created a track called 'Political Drillin' which was broadcast on [[Channel 4 News]] and used comments made by UK [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]'s attempting to highlight their own hypocrisy in using violent language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/drill-mc-violent-quotes-mps-track-political-drilling-2392949|title=A drill MC highlights hypocrisy against genre by using violent quotes from MPs in new track \u2018Political Drilling\u2019|first=Rhian|last=Daly|date=23 October 2018|via=www.nme.com|access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202151209/https://www.nme.com/news/music/drill-mc-violent-quotes-mps-track-political-drilling-2392949|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\nUK drill has spread outside of the United Kingdom, with artists and groups in other countries rapping in styles and using slang terms heavily influenced by UK drill music, and using UK drill instrumentals produced by British producers. Ireland, the Netherlands, and Australia in particular have developed drill scenes that are heavily indebted to UK drill music, with artists such as [[OneFour]] in Australia<ref name=\":82\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/a3x58j/behind-the-scenes-with-onefour-australias-first-drill-rappers|title=Behind The Scenes With OneFour: Australia's First Drill Rappers|last=Fazal|first=Mahmood|last2=Butler|first2=Gavin|date=2019-08-01|website=Vice|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807011410/https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/a3x58j/behind-the-scenes-with-onefour-australias-first-drill-rappers|archive-date=2019-08-07|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>, Chuks & J.B2 from Dublin, Ireland<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/yw7p8b/irish-drill-music|title=could irish drill music be the next big thing?|last=Dunn|first=Frankie|last2=Gannon|first2=Colin|date=2018-11-21|website=I-D|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715140827/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/yw7p8b/irish-drill-music|archive-date=2019-07-15|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>, and 73 De Pijp from The Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parool.nl/gs-b71f546d|title=De opkomst van Amsterdamse drillrap: \u2018Er is een overlap met criminaliteit\u2019|last=Vugts|first=Paul|date=2019-12-27|website=Het Parool|language=nl-NL|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>. [[New York City|New York]] drill music began rising to prominence in the late 2010s. New York drill, primarily based in [[Brooklyn]], has taken influence from UK drill with artists such as [[Pop Smoke]], Sheff G, and 22Gz collaborating with UK drill producers such as AXL Beats, Yoz Beats, and 808Melo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/sheff-g-made-drill-the-sound-of-brooklyn/|title=Sheff G Made Drill the Sound of Brooklyn|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807011410/https://pitchfork.com/levels/sheff-g-made-drill-the-sound-of-brooklyn/|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/music/pop-smoke-final-interview-uk-drill/|title=Pop Smoke Shouted Out The UK\u2019s Top Drill Producers In His Final Interview|date=2020-02-24|website=UPROXX|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> 808Melo produced \"Welcome to the Party\" for Pop Smoke, which received a considerable amount of attention. Pop Smoke created a 9 track project produced entirely by 808 Melo and Trap House Mob (a team of UK based producers).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/8/pop-smoke-welcome-to-the-party-remix-nicki-minaj|title=Nicki Minaj Remixes Pop Smoke's \"Welcome to the Party\" - HYPEBEAST|website=hypebeast.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820202034/https://hypebeast.com/2019/8/pop-smoke-welcome-to-the-party-remix-nicki-minaj|archive-date=20 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kazimagazine.com/music/reviews/pop-smokes-debut-meet-the-woo-is-an-introduction-to-a-new-sound-in-new-york-city-hip-hop/|title=Pop Smoke\u2019s Debut \"Meet The Woo\" Is An Introduction To A New Sound In New York City Hip-Hop|last=Bundy|first=Tee|date=2019-07-30|website=KAZI. MAGAZINE|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807011411/https://kazimagazine.com/music/reviews/pop-smokes-debut-meet-the-woo-is-an-introduction-to-a-new-sound-in-new-york-city-hip-hop/|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Artists in Spain making drill music have also taken on influence by its British counterpart, with various references and similar production to UK drill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trenchtrenchtrench.com/features/drillers-without-borders-5-drill-scenes-flourishing-outside-of-the-uk|title=Drillers Without Borders|website=trenchtrenchtrench.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807011411/https://trenchtrenchtrench.com/features/drillers-without-borders-5-drill-scenes-flourishing-outside-of-the-uk|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCanadian musician [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] did a \"Behind Barz\" freestyle for [[Link Up TV]] in 2018 where he rapped over a UK drill beat. Drake also credited UK drill artist Loski as an influence for his 2018 album, ''[[Scorpion (Drake album)|Scorpion]]''.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/19/why-drake-fell-in-love-with-the-uk-and-vice-versa|title=Why Drake fell in love with the UK (and vice versa)|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|date=2018-07-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120015143/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/19/why-drake-fell-in-love-with-the-uk-and-vice-versa|archive-date=20 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heartafact.com/drake-is-officially-a-uk-citizen/|title=Drake is officially a UK Citizen|date=2019-04-17|website=Heartafact|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225051823/https://heartafact.com/drake-is-officially-a-uk-citizen/|archive-date=25 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Drake released \"War\". The song used UK drill's production style and was produced by British producer AXL Beats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://versus.uk.com/2019/12/drake-uk-drill-new-freestyle-track-war/|title=Drake Is Doing up UK Drill on New Freestyle Track \"War\"|date=2019-12-24|website=VERSUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/drake-new-song-war-biggest-takeaways|title=5 Biggest Takeaways From Drake's New Song \"War\"|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224214544/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/drake-new-song-war-biggest-takeaways|archive-date=24 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Drake's flow in both instances was reminiscent of UK drill artists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://versus.uk.com/2019/12/drake-uk-drill-new-freestyle-track-war/|title=Drake Is Doing up UK Drill on New Freestyle Track \"War\"|date=2019-12-24|website=VERSUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref><ref name=\":03\" />\n\n===Chart success & transition into mainstream===\n[[Unknown T]]'s song \"Homerton B\" charted after its August 2018 release; and in doing so, became technically the first ever \u2018UK drill\u2019 single to officially enter the charts. The song entered at number 83 on the [[Official Singles Chart]] Top 100 on 28 August 2018, then peaked at 48 in September 2018; putting him in the running with the likes of [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[Travis $cott]], [[Nicki Minaj]] & [[Eminem]]; world-renowned artists who also charted closely in this period, which was unheard of for a UK drill song at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/54130/unknown-t/|work=Official Charts Company (OCC)|title=UNKNOWN T \u2013 full Official Chart History \u2013 Official Charts Company|date=11 July 2019|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322042536/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/54130/unknown-t/|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nUK drill group [[67 (rap group)|67]] had two entries into the official charts, however unlike the Unknown T entry, this was the albums chart and not the singles chart. They reached number 66 in the Official Albums Chart with the mixtape ''Let\u2019s Lurk'' and number 71 with the mixtape ''The Glorious Twelfth''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48446/67/|work=Official Charts Company (OCC)|title=67 \u2013 full Official Chart History \u2013 Official Charts Company|date=11 July 2019|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412123821/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48446/67/|archive-date=12 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Although considered a predominantly trap based album which implements some drill features and elements, [[Section Boyz]] mixtape ''[[Don't Panic (Section Boyz album)|Don't Panic]]'' reached number 37 in the [[UK Albums Chart]], later peaking at number 36 in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48395/section-boyz/|work=Official Charts Company (OCC)|title=SECTION BOYZ \u2013 full Official Chart History \u2013 Official Charts Company|date=11 July 2019|access-date=14 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602000326/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48395/section-boyz/|archive-date=2 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe above entries set off a [[snowball effect]] of UK drill song entries into the Official Singles Charts, and artists being propelled closer to the British mainstream. As the songs entered the charts, more people began to find out and talk about UK drill again, thus attracting new fans to the genre, and attracting both positive and negative media attention for various reasons, keeping the genre in the limelight, and bursting the bubble the genre was confined within. This also opened up drill to UK artists of other genres more, to begin rapping over drill style instrumentals and experimenting with sounds inside of the genre, as opposed to their usual styles.\n\nIn 2020, [[DigDat]] released ''Ei8ht Mile''. The mixtape scored the biggest opening week of all time for a UK drill album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/officialcharts/status/1220769242028609540|title=Big news for @DigDat8 \u2013 his new mixtape Ei8ht Mile scores the biggest opening week for a UK drill album:|last=Charts|first=Official|date=2020-01-24|website=@officialcharts|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n'''Notable UK drill singles & albums charting in the Top 100 (between 2015\u20132019)''':<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/|work=Official Charts Company (OCC)|title=Official Charts \u2013 Home of the Official UK Top 40 Charts|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806163721/https://www.officialcharts.com/|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Artist\n! Title\n! Peak\n! Type\n! Entry\n|-\n| [[Section Boyz]]\n| ''Don't Panic''\n| '''36'''\n| Album\n| 1 October 2015\n|-\n| [[67 (rap group)|67]]\n| ''Let's Lurk''\n| '''66'''\n| Album\n| 22 September 2016\n|-\n| 67\n| ''Glorious Twelfth''\n| '''71'''\n| Album\n| 27 July 2017\n|-\n| Loski\n| ''Call Me Loose''\n| '''44'''\n| Album\n| 26 April 2018\n|-\n| [[Headie One]]\n| ''The One Two''\n| '''32'''\n| Album\n| 5 July 2018\n|-\n| [[Unknown T]]\n| \"Homerton B\"\n| '''48'''\n| Single\n| 6 September 2018\n|-\n| DigDat\n| \"Air Force\"\n| '''20'''\n| Single\n| 27 September 2018\n|-\n| [[Smoke Boys]]\n| ''Don't Panic II''\n| '''60'''\n| Album\n| 1 November 2018\n|-\n| Russ\n| \"Gun Lean\"\n| '''09'''\n| Single\n| 3 January 2019\n|-\n| DigDat & Loski\n| \"No Cap\"\n| '''51'''\n| Single\n| 28 February 2019\n|-\n| Loski\n| ''Mad Move''\n| '''41'''\n| Album\n| 14 March 2019\n|-\n| Russ & Tion Wayne\n| \"Keisha & Becky\"\n| '''07'''\n| Single\n| 4 April 2019\n|-\n| RV & Headie One\n| ''Drillers & Trappers 2''\n| '''21'''\n| Album\n| 4 April 2019\n|-\n| RV & Headie One\n| \"Match Day\"\n| '''86'''\n| Single\n| 4 April 2019\n|-\n| Digga D\n| \"No Diet\"\n| '''20'''\n| Single\n| 2 May 2019\n|-\n| Hardy Caprio & DigDat\n| \"Guten Tag\"\n| '''18'''\n| Single\n| 16 May 2019\n|-\n| Digga D\n| ''Double Tap Diaries''\n| '''11'''\n| Album\n| 30 May 2019\n|-\n| Digga D\n| \"P4DP\"\n| '''54'''\n| Single\n| 30 May 2019\n|-\n| Digga D & Russ\n| \"Mr Sheeen\"\n| '''63'''\n| Single\n| 4 July 2019\n|-\n| [[Kenny Allstar]]\n| \"Friday\" (ft. DigDat)\n| '''62'''\n| Single\n| 18 July 2019\n|-\n| Krept & Konan\n| \"I Spy\" (ft. Headie One & K-Trap)\n| '''18'''\n| Single\n| 25 July 2019\n|-\n| Headie One\n| ''Music x Road''\n| '''05'''\n| Album\n| 5 September 2019\n|-\n| Headie One\n| \"Hard To Believe\"\n| '''79'''\n| Single\n| 26 September 2019\n|-\n| Poundz\n| \"Opp Thot\"\n| '''33'''\n| Single\n| 24 October 2019\n|-\n| Dave\n| \"Paper Cuts\"\n| '''15'''\n| Single\n| 21 November 2019\n|-\n\n|}\n\n===Notable artists===\nNotable groups in UK drill music include:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*150<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/drill-music-london-stabbings-shootings-rap-67-abra-cadabra-comment-government-a8305516.html|title=Inside UK drill, the demonised rap representing a marginalised generation|date=29 May 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=24 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425033428/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/drill-music-london-stabbings-shootings-rap-67-abra-cadabra-comment-government-a8305516.html|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*23 Drillas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/notorious-drill-gang-stand-cash-15626704|title=Notorious 'drill' gang stand to cash in through Google Play|first=Josh|last=Layton|date=5 January 2019|website=birminghammail|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025023/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/notorious-drill-gang-stand-cash-15626704|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*410<ref name=\"Skengdo and AM: the drill rappers\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/31/skengdo-and-am-the-drill-rappers-sentenced-for-playing-their-song|title=Skengdo and AM: the drill rappers sentenced for playing their song|first=Dan|last=Hancox|date=31 January 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809083127/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/31/skengdo-and-am-the-drill-rappers-sentenced-for-playing-their-song|archive-date=9 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[67 (rap group)|67]]\n*[[Ghetto Boys|814]]<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/08/08/drill-music-linked-violent-crime-london-7812930/|title=What is drill music and why is it linked to violent crime in London?|date=8 August 2018|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806064345/https://metro.co.uk/2018/08/08/drill-music-linked-violent-crime-london-7812930/|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*86<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/a3m7nk/uk-drill-holiday-guide|title=A Guide to Explaining UK Drill to Your Family Over the Holidays|first=Tshepo|last=Mokoena|date=20 December 2018|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807014009/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/a3m7nk/uk-drill-holiday-guide|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Block 6<ref>{{C