pril 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*LTH (Lower Tulse Hill)<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/these-artists-have-a-story-to-tell-music-producer-rejects-calls-to-ban-drill-music-videos-from-the-a3991851.html|title='Knife crime epidemic is bigger problem than just drill music'|date=16 November 2018|website=Evening Standard|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501171947/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/these-artists-have-a-story-to-tell-music-producer-rejects-calls-to-ban-drill-music-videos-from-the-a3991851.html|archive-date=1 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*M20<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/teenage-drill-rapper-jailed-for-stabbing-boy-15-outside-chicken-shop-11775822|title=Teenage drill rapper jailed for stabbing boy, 15, outside chicken shop|website=Sky News|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025011/https://news.sky.com/story/teenage-drill-rapper-jailed-for-stabbing-boy-15-outside-chicken-shop-11775822|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Tottenham Mandem|NPK]] (Northumberland Park Killers)<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\"/>\n*[[OFB (group)|OFB (Original Farm Boys)]]\n*Silwood Nation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45824358|title=Drill rapper jailed over county lines scam|first=Michael|last=Buchanan|date=12 October 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=12 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811142450/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45824358|archive-date=11 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Siraq/727<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2017/04/27/uk-drill-chicago-brixton/|title=From Chicago to Brixton: The surprising rise of UK drill|date=27 April 2017|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529054414/https://www.factmag.com/2017/04/27/uk-drill-chicago-brixton/|archive-date=29 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Russ (UK rapper)|SMG/Splash/M Splash]]\n*[[Zone 2 (music group)|Zone 2]]\n{{div col end}}\n\nNotable artists of UK drill include:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*A1FromThe9<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/uk-drill-rappers-snapchat-usernames/|title=UK Drill Rappers Snapchat Usernames: The Ultimate List|website=Capital XTRA|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807022756/https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/uk-drill-rappers-snapchat-usernames/|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Abra Cadabra<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*ASAP<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Blanco<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*BT<ref name=\"newyorker.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/letter-from-the-uk/the-soundtrack-to-londons-murders|title=The Soundtrack to London\u2019s Murders|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=The New Yorker|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724013810/https://www.newyorker.com/news/letter-from-the-uk/the-soundtrack-to-londons-murders|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Burner<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*CB<ref name=\"thetimes.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/do-drills-lyrics-inspire-knife-crime-or-give-voice-to-a-generation-thats-been-let-down-nqqvjzqdv|title=Do drill\u2019s lyrics inspire knife crime? Or give voice to a generation that\u2019s been let down?|first=Ben|last=Machell|date=4 May 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025017/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/do-drills-lyrics-inspire-knife-crime-or-give-voice-to-a-generation-thats-been-let-down-nqqvjzqdv|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Digga D<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*DigDat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/artists/future/news/digdat-song-uk-drill-collab/|title=Future's Collab With UK Drill Rapper DigDat Teased In New Video|website=Capital XTRA|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025011/https://www.capitalxtra.com/artists/future/news/digdat-song-uk-drill-collab/|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[67 (rap group)|Dimzy]]\n*Drillminister <ref>{{cite news|url=https://drillminister.com/2018/11/05/rapper-proves-mps-know-the-drill-on-violent-talk/|work=[[Drillminister]]|title=Rapper proves MPs know the drill on violent talk|date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n*Frosty <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/drill-artist-frosty-who-sang-16128869 |work=Surrey Live |title=Making the banned: Drill artist Frosty who sang about drug dealing jailed over Guildford county lines operation \u2013 Get Surrey |date=15 Aug 2019 |access-date=15 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102706/https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/drill-artist-frosty-who-sang-16128869 |archive-date=15 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*GB<ref name=\"respect-mag.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://respect-mag.com/2019/02/mayhem-grizzy-justin-bieber/|title=NEW VIDEO: Uptop\u2019s Mayhem & Grizzy Join Forces on \"Justin Bieber\"|date=20 February 2019|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025014/https://respect-mag.com/2019/02/mayhem-grizzy-justin-bieber/|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Grizzy<ref name=\"respect-mag.com\"/>\n*[[Headie One]]\n*Incognito<ref name=\"respect-mag.com\"/>\n*K-Trap<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/20/one-to-watch-k-trap-drill-big-mood|title=One to watch: K Trap|first=Tara|last=Joshi|date=20 July 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025009/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/20/one-to-watch-k-trap-drill-big-mood|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*KO<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Kwengface<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*[[67 (rap group)|LD]]\n*Loski<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Liquez<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Mayhem<ref name=\"NEW VIDEO: Uptop\u2019s Mayhem & Grizzy\">{{cite web|url=https://respect-mag.com/2019/02/mayhem-grizzy-justin-bieber/|title=\"NEW VIDEO: Uptop's Mayhem & Grizzy Join Forces on \"Justin Bieber\"\"|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025014/https://respect-mag.com/2019/02/mayhem-grizzy-justin-bieber/|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*MizOrMac<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*NitoNB<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Perm<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*PS<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Q2T<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-moral-panic-against-uk-drill-is-deeply-misguided/|title=The Moral Panic Against UK Drill Is Deeply Misguided|website=Pitchfork|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725034847/https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-moral-panic-against-uk-drill-is-deeply-misguided/|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Rampz<ref name=\"London drill rapper killed in knif\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/aug/02/london-drill-rapper-killed-in-knife-attack-admitted-musics-effect-on|title=London drill rapper killed in knife attack admitted music's effect on crime|first=Ian|last=Cobain|date=2 August 2018|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807025009/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/aug/02/london-drill-rapper-killed-in-knife-attack-admitted-musics-effect-on|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Rendo<ref name=\"newyorker.com\"/>\n*[[Russ (UK rapper)|Russ]]\n*RV<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Sav'O<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Sav12<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Screwloose<ref name=\"London drill rapper killed in knif\"/>\n*Scribz<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*[[Skengdo & AM]]<ref name=\"thetimes.co.uk\"/>\n*Showkey<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\"/> \n*Taze<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*Trizzac<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n*[[Unknown T]]\n*V9<ref name=\"capitalxtra.com\"/>\n{{div col end}}\n\nNotable and well-known producers of the genre include: QUIETPVCK, Carns Hill, M1OnTheBeat, [[Tre Mission]], Ghosty, 808Melo, Nyge, AXL Beats, [[Zeph Ellis]], HL8, MKThePlug, MikaBeats, D Proffit, BKay, GottiOnEm, JB104, Mazza, & Tweeko, amongst an abundance of others.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rwdmag.com/loski-returns-with-hazards-2-0-ahead-of-new-mad-moves-project/|work=[[RWD Magazine]]|title=Loski returns with \u2018Hazards 2.0\u2019 ahead of new \u2018Mad Moves\u2019 project \u2013 RWD|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102709/http://rwdmag.com/loski-returns-with-hazards-2-0-ahead-of-new-mad-moves-project/|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/10/carns-hill-trench-interview|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|title=According To UK Rap Producer Carns Hill, His 'Drill' Sound Happened Almost By Accident|date=12 Oct 2017|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102708/https://www.complex.com/music/2017/10/carns-hill-trench-interview|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"i-D/Vice\">{{cite news|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/bj9378/welcome-to-the-golden-age-of-drill|work=i-D/Vice|title=Welcome to the Golden Age of Drill: Meet London's drill godfathers|date=21 June 2019|access-date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802213148/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/bj9378/welcome-to-the-golden-age-of-drill|archive-date=2 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/merky-ace-war-is-normal|work=[[Complex (Magazine)|Complex]]|title=Merky Ace Dropped His Debut Album 'War Is Normal' And It's A Lot|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102709/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/merky-ace-war-is-normal|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://versus.uk.com/2019/07/rv-fire-in-the-booth/|work=Versus|title=RV Unleashes Cold 'Fire In The Booth' Debut Freestyle|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815104227/https://versus.uk.com/2019/07/rv-fire-in-the-booth/|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://genius.com/a/who-is-20-year-old-brooklyn-drill-rapper-pop-smoke-with-viral-hits-welcome-to-the-party-meet-the-woo-mpr-flexing|work=Genius|title=Who Is 20-Year-Old Brooklyn Drill Rapper Pop Smoke With Viral Hits \"Welcome To The Party,\" \"Meet The Woo,\" \"MPR,\" & \"Flexing\"|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102707/https://genius.com/a/who-is-20-year-old-brooklyn-drill-rapper-pop-smoke-with-viral-hits-welcome-to-the-party-meet-the-woo-mpr-flexing|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://versus.uk.com/2019/08/fire-boots-nyge/|work=Versus|title=Fire in the Boots: Nyge|date=14 August 2019|access-date=15 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815102708/https://versus.uk.com/2019/08/fire-boots-nyge/|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/d-proffit-headie-one-rv-drillers-and-trappers|work=GRM Daily|title=D Proffit enlists Headie One & RV for animated \"Drillers & Trappers\" video - Videos - GRM Daily|date=31 October 2018|access-date=16 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816191233/http://grmdaily.com/video/d-proffit-headie-one-rv-drillers-and-trappers|archive-date=16 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/drake-war-drill-producer-axl-beats-interview|work=[[Complex_(magazine)|Complex]]|title=How Drake Ended Up Rapping on a Drill Beat: An Interview With \u201cWar\u201d Producer AXL Beats|access-date=25 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226004933/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/drake-war-drill-producer-axl-beats-interview|archive-date=26 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==UK trap==\nThere are a number of more American-influenced trap artists such as the group [[Smoke Boys]] (formerly Section Boyz), and also rappers like TE dness, S Loud, [[M Huncho]], Nafe Smallz, K-Trap, and [[SL (rapper)|SL]] (formerly Slimz) plus many more. Many of these artists gained influences from the American trap scene and deciding to add the UK sound and flavour to the genre. Many of them talk about braggadocious lifestyles they live and how it affects their music. In several interviews before, [[M Huncho]] has described his more tone-down, melodic style and moderately humbler approach when it comes to lyrics as his own derivative take on UK [[trap music]], in a genre he has personally dubbed as \"trapwave\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nationofbillions.com/welcome-to-the-trapwave-m-huncho|work=A Nation Of Billions|title=Welcome To The TrapWave: M Huncho|date=29 May 2018|access-date=4 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604120145/https://nationofbillions.com/welcome-to-the-trapwave-m-huncho|archive-date=4 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Wolverhampton artist [[Scarlxrd]] implements an energetic aesthetic and tone with explosively brazen screaming vocals, and dark yet reflectively intense and meaningful lyricism in an essentially self-pioneered style known as \"[[Rap metal#Trap metal|trap-metal]]\" or \"ragecore\"; a fusion of trap music and screaming vocals. Scarlxrd has cited some of his main inspirations and influences as including the likes of [[Eminem]], [[Bring Me the Horizon]], [[Limp Bizkit]], [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Travi$ Scott]] and [[Linkin Park]], among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/scarlxrd-bring-me-the-horizons-legacy-inspires-me/|work=Kerrang|title=SCARLXRD: \"BRING ME THE HORIZON\u2019S LEGACY INSPIRES ME\"|date=27 February 2019|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806082026/https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/scarlxrd-bring-me-the-horizons-legacy-inspires-me/|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/video/2019/05/scarlxrd-interview/|work=XXL|title=Scarlxrd Ditches YouTuber Lifestyle and His Black Mask for Screamo Success|date=25 May 2019|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190519003815/https://www.xxlmag.com/video/2019/05/scarlxrd-interview/|archive-date=19 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ZSgIYzwOYw|work=PopkillerTV|title=SCARLXRD \u2013 interview: \"My style is a mix of Eminem, Travis Scott and Slipknot\" (05.2018) \u2013 YouTube|date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nNotable British trap artists and groups include:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[D-Block Europe]]\n*[[Fredo (rapper)|Fredo]]\n*[[M Huncho]]\n*[[Octavian (rapper)|Octavian]]\n*[[Scarlxrd]]\n*[[SL (rapper)|SL]] (formerly Slimz)\n*[[Smoke Boys]] (formerly Section Boyz)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Backlash against commercialisation==\nSince grime's post-millennial boom period coincided with UK hip-hop's, the eagerly anticipated commercial breakout of the latter did not happen. Instead, acts such as [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[Tinie Tempah]], [[N-Dubz]] and [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]] were signed to major labels and their traditional sound tweaked to fit a pop sensibility. However the lineage of these, and many UK rappers, is unquestionably grime rather than UK hip-hop.\n\nThere is a common belief within the underground hip hop community that true hip hop is music relevant primarily to the disenfranchised listeners, rather than the mass market. Because of the belief that mainstream acts are paid large sums of money by the major labels to make music tailored to the current mass market, these artists often face a backlash and accusations of 'selling out' from the underground community.<ref>{{cite news|title=British hip-hop heads out of the underground|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/british-hip-hop-heads-out-of-the-underground-1958279.html|accessdate=10 October 2016|work=The Independent|date=30 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010215230/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/british-hip-hop-heads-out-of-the-underground-1958279.html|archive-date=10 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nThe growth of British hip hop was given a boost when in 2002, the BBC launched a digital radio station [[BBC Radio 1Xtra|1Xtra]] devoted to \"new black music\" including hip hop, [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[UK garage]], [[dancehall]], [[Grime music|grime]] and drum and bass,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/1xtra/ |title=BBC Website: 1xtra |accessdate=1 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061104060217/http://www.bbc.co.uk/1xtra/ |archive-date=4 November 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref> however 1Xtra does not play exclusively British hip hop. The cable and satellite channel, Channel AKA (formerly Channel U, now known as [[Now 70s]]) also had the profile of British hip hop and grime.\nYouTube was also a very important outlet for upcoming and significant artists. Channels include [[Link Up TV]], [[GRM Daily]], [[SB.TV]], Pressplay Media and [[Mixtape Madness]].\n\n==Women==\nWomen have contributed to hip hop's evolution in Britain from the beginning.<ref>Chang, Jeff. \"Future Shock\", \"Future Shock\", January 2004. Accessed 14 March 2008.</ref> Female British hip hop artists include [[Alesha Dixon]], [[Baby Blue (rapper)|Baby Blue]], [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]], [[Kate Tempest]], [[Lady Leshurr]], [[Lady Sovereign]], [[Little Simz]], [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]], [[Monie Love]], [[Nadia Rose]], [[Shystie]], [[No Lay]], [[Stefflon Don]], Mercury prize winners [[Ms. Dynamite]] and [[Speech Debelle]] and music producer [[Mizz Beats]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/usa-arts-music-women-in-hip-hop-feature.htm |title=Our work in arts |publisher=British Council |date= |accessdate=2014-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102062725/http://www.britishcouncil.org/usa-arts-music-women-in-hip-hop-feature.htm |archive-date=2 January 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other British female rappers have included [[Cookie Crew]], [[She Rockers]], [[Wee Papa Girl Rappers]], [[NoLay]], [[C-Mone]] and [[Envy (English rapper)|Envy]].\n\n[[Neneh Cherry]], born in Stockholm, moved to England when she was 14 years old, and contributed to early British hip hop. ''[[Raw Like Sushi]]'' (1989) was solely produced by English producers and was a massive hit in both the UK and US. Cherry continues to produce and release music today.\n\nWomen in hip hop often confront a large amount of sexist stereotyping; however some female British hip hop artists such as Lady Sovereign and M.I.A. have achieved success both in the UK and US. Artists such as Kate Tempest, Ms Dynamite, M.I.A. and Speech Debelle have also become known for political and social commentary in their music. Singer, songwriter and rapper Estelle said of the difficult position of female rappers: \"I think they get a tough ride because some of them don\u2019t see themselves above and beyond the bullshit and no one\u2019s really given them that break.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adabra|first1=Michelle|title=Interview \u2013 Estelle|url=https://www.britishhiphop.co.uk/features/interviews/estelle.html|website=www.britishhiphop.co.uk|accessdate=10 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419194856/https://www.britishhiphop.co.uk/features/interviews/estelle.html|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Afroswing]]\n*[[Drill music|Drill]]\n*[[Gangsta rap]]\n*[[Grime (music)|Grime]]\n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n*[[Trap music|Trap]]\n*[[Music of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Scottish hip hop|Scottish hip-hop]]\n*[[UK garage]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.spifftv.com Source for UK hip hop artists]\n\n{{hiphop}}\n{{Music of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Black British topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:British Hip Hop}}\n[[Category:British hip hop| ]]\n[[Category:Black British music|Hip-hop]]\n[[Category:British styles of music]]\n[[Category:Hip hop]]\n", "name_user": "Ukhiphopfanatic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Previous authors criminally failed to include some of the pioneering artists of uk-hiphop/boombap musical culture. Interestingly, previous authors included notable grime artists but not UK hip-hop (this is a uk hiphop wikipage). Henceforth, I added said individuals.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_hip_hop"}
{"title_page": "Lower Canada", "text_new": "{{short description|19th century British colony in present-day Quebec}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox country\n|native_name = {{native name|fr|Province du Bas-Canada}}\n|conventional_long_name = Province of Lower Canada\n|common_name = Lower Canada\n|era       = [[Canada under British rule|British Era]]\n|status    = Colony\n|empire    = United Kingdom\n|government_type    = [[Ch\u00e2teau Clique]] [[oligarchy]]<br /> under a <br />[[Constitutional monarchy]]\n\n|event_start = [[Constitutional Act of 1791]]\n|year_start  = 1791\n|date_start  = 26 December\n|event_end   = [[Act of Union 1840]]\n|year_end    = 1841\n|date_end    = 10 February\n\n|event1      =\n|date_event1 =\n|event2      =\n|date_event2 =\n|event3      =\n|date_event3 =\n\n|p1 = Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Great Britain (1707-1800).svg\n|s1 = Province of Canada\n|flag_s1 = Flag of the United Kingdom.svg\n|s2 = Colony of Newfoundland\n|flag_s2 = Flag of the United Kingdom.svg\n|today={{Plainlist|* \n{{flag|Canada}}\n* &nbsp;'''\u221f'''{{flag|Quebec}}\n* &nbsp;'''\u221f'''{{flag|Newfoundland and Labrador}}}}\n|flag        = \n|flag_type   = [[Red Ensign|Civil ensign]] (1801 onward)\n|image_flag  = Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n|symbol_type_article=\n|symbol_type  =\n|image_coat   =\n|image_map    = \u00c9volution territoriale du Bas-Canada.gif\n|image_map_caption  = \n|capital          = [[Quebec City]]\n|national_motto   =\n|national_anthem  =\n|common_languages = [[Canadian French|French]], [[Canadian English|English]]\n|religion         =\n|currency         = [[Canadian pound]]\n\n<!--- Titles and names of the first and last leaders and their deputies --->\n|leader1                = [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]\n|year_leader1           = 1791\u20131820\n|leader2                = [[George IV of the United Kingdom|George IV]]\n|year_leader2           = 1820\u20131830\n|leader3                = [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]]\n|year_leader3           = 1830\u20131837\n|leader4                = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n|year_leader4           = 1837\u20131841\n|title_leader = [[List of British Monarchs#House of Hanover|Sovereign]]\n|deputy1      = See [[Lieutenant-Governors of Quebec#Lieutenant-Governors of Lower Canada|list of Lieutenant-Governors]]\n|year_deputy1 =\n|title_deputy = [[Lieutenant-Governor (Canada)|Lieutenant-Governor]] and [[Executive Council of Lower Canada]]\n|legislature  = Parliament of Lower Canada\n|house1       = [[Legislative Council of Lower Canada|Legislative Council]]\n|house2       = [[Legislative Assembly of Lower Canada|Legislative Assembly]]\n\n<!--- Area and population of a given year --->\n|stat_year1 = 1839<ref name=openl>{{cite web|title=The emigrant's handbook of facts concerning Canada, New Zealand, Australia, Cape of Good Hope, &c|url=https://archive.org/stream/cihm_95282#page/n35/mode/2up|publisher=Open Library|accessdate=22 December 2013|pages=2\u20133}}</ref>\n|stat_area1 = 534,185\n|stat_pop1  = {{circa}} 700,000\n|stat_year2 =\n|stat_pop2  =\n|political_subdiv=\n|footnotes  =\n}}\nThe '''Province of Lower Canada''' ({{lang-fr|province du Bas-Canada}}) was a [[British colonization of the Americas|British colony]] on the lower [[Saint Lawrence River]] and the shores of the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]] (1791\u20131841). It covered the southern portion of the current Province of [[Quebec]] and the [[Labrador]] region of the current Province of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] (until the Labrador region was transferred to Newfoundland in 1809).<ref name=\"marianopolis\">{{cite web |year=2007 |url = http://faculty.marianopolis.edu/c.belanger/NFLDHistory/Quebec-NewfoundlandLabradorBoundaryIssue.htm|title = Labrador\u2013Canada Boundary |publisher = marianopolis| accessdate =20 March 2008 |quote=Labrador Act, 1809. \u2013 An imperial act (49 Geo. III, cap. 27), 1809, provided for the re-annexation to Newfoundland of 'such parts of the coast of Labrador from the River St John to Hudson's Streights, and the said Island of Anticosti, and all other smaller islands so annexed to the Government of Newfoundland by the said Proclamation of the seventh day of October one thousand seven hundred and sixty-three (except the said Islands of Madelaine) shall be separated from the said Government of Lower Canada, and be again re-annexed to the Government of Newfoundland.'}}</ref>\n\nLower Canada consisted of part of the former colony of [[Canada (New France)|Canada]] of [[New France]], conquered by Great Britain in the [[Seven Years' War]] ending in 1763 (also called the [[French and Indian War]] in the United States). Other parts of New France conquered by Britain became the Colonies of [[Nova Scotia]], [[New Brunswick]], and [[Prince Edward Island]].\n\nThe Province of Lower Canada was created by the ''[[Constitutional Act 1791]]'' from the partition of the British colony of the [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] (1763\u20131791)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/lower-canada |title=Lower Canada |author=Fernand Ouellet |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |date=March 4, 2015 |accessdate=August 18, 2019 }}</ref> into the Province of Lower Canada and the [[Upper Canada|Province of Upper Canada]]. The prefix \"lower\" in its name refers to its geographic position farther downriver from the headwaters of the [[St. Lawrence River]] than its contemporary Upper Canada, present-day southern Ontario.\n\nLower Canada was abolished in 1841 when it and adjacent Upper Canada were [[Union of Upper and Lower Canada|united]] into the [[Province of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/province-of-canada-1841-67 |title=Province of Canada 1841\u20131867 |author=James Maurice Stockford Careless |author2=Richard Foot |work=The Canadian Encyclopedia |publisher=Historica Canada |date=March 4, 2015 |accessdate=August 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Rebellion==\n{{Main|Lower Canada Rebellion}}\nLike Upper Canada, there was significant political unrest. Twenty-two years after the invasion by the Americans in the [[War of 1812]], a rebellion now challenged the British rule of the predominantly French population. After the [[Lower Canada Rebellion|Patriote Rebellion]] in the [[Rebellions of 1837\u20131838]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/durham-report|title=Durham Report|author=David Mills|author2=Richard Foot|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|date=March 20, 2017|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref> were crushed by the [[British Army]] and [[Loyal (Lower Canada)|Loyal]] volunteers, the [[Constitutional Act 1791|1791 Constitution]] was suspended on 27 March 1838 and a [[Special Council of Lower Canada|special council]] was appointed to administer the colony. An abortive attempt by revolutionary [[Robert Nelson (insurrectionist)|Robert Nelson]] to declare a [[Republic of Lower Canada]] was quickly thwarted.\n\nThe provinces of Lower Canada and Upper Canada were combined as the [[United Province of Canada]] in 1841, when the ''[[Act of Union 1840]]'' came into force. Their separate legislatures were combined into a single parliament with equal representation for both constituent parts, even though Lower Canada had a greater population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/act-of-union|title=Act of Union|author=Jacques Monet, SJ|author2=Richard Foot|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|date= \tMarch 4, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=center>\nfile:WilliamLyonMackenzie.jpeg|[[William Lyon Mackenzie]], [[Upper Canada Rebellion|rebellion]] chief in [[Upper Canada]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrimoine-culturel.gouv.qc.ca/rpcq/detail.do?methode=consulter&id=19028&type=pge#.W_M2PPniaUk|title=Mackenzie, William Lyon - R\u00e9pertoire du patrimoine culturel du Qu\u00e9bec|website=www.patrimoine-culturel.gouv.qc.ca|accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> \nFile:Louis-Joseph Papineau by William Notman.jpg|[[Louis-Joseph Papineau]], [[Lower Canada Rebellion|rebellion]] chief in Lower Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/louis-joseph-papineau|title=Louis-Joseph Papineau|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n\n==Constitution==\n[[File:Constitution-of-lower-canada.png|thumb|left|[[Constitution]] of Lower Canada in 1791]]\nThe Province of Lower Canada inherited the mixed set of French and English institutions that existed in the Province of Quebec during the 1763\u20131791 period and which continued to exist later in Canada-East (1841\u20131867) and ultimately in the current Province of Quebec (since 1867).\n\n{{clear|left}}\n\n==Population==\n{{main|Population of Canada}}Lower Canada was populated mainly by [[Canadiens]], an [[ethnic group]] who trace their ancestry to [[French people|French]] colonists who settled in [[Canada (New France)|Canada]] from the 17th century onward.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Population of Lower Canada, 1806 to 1841\n! Year || Census estimate<ref>[http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/98-187-x/4064809-eng.htm Censuses of Canada. 1665 to 1871], Statistics of Canada, Volume IV, Ottawa, 1876</ref> \n|-\n|1806 || 250,000\n|-\n|1814 || 335,000\n|-\n|1822 || 427,465\n|-\n|1825 || 479,288\n|-\n|1827 || 473,475\n|-\n|1831 || 553,134\n|-\n|1841 || 650,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n[[File:Qu\u00e9bec I-185-1-a.svg|thumbnail|left|125px|Current route marker seen along the ''Chemin'']]\nTravelling around Lower Canada was mainly by water along the [[St. Lawrence River]]. On land the only long-distance route was the [[Chemin du Roy]] or King's Highway, built in the 1730s by [[New France]].<ref name=\"lecheminduroy.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lecheminduroy.com/en/history|title=History - Le Chemin du Roy|website=Le Chemin du Roy|accessdate=19 November 2018|quote= summary of the original french version}}</ref> The King's Highway was, in addition to the mail route, the primary means of long-distance passenger travel until steamboats (1815) and railways (1850s) began to challenge the royal road.<ref name=\"lecheminduroy.com\"/> The royal road's importance waned after the 1850s and would not re-emerge as a key means of transportation until the modern [[Highways in Quebec|highway system of Quebec]] was created in the 20th century.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|History}}\n{{col div|colwidth=23em}}\n*[[Canada East]], period after the ''[[Act of Union 1840]]''\n*[[Former colonies and territories in Canada]]\n*[[French and Indian War]]\n* [[French and Indian Wars]]\n*[[French colonial empire]]\n*[[List of lieutenant governors of Quebec]]\n*[[National Patriots' Day]]\n*[[Ottawa River timber trade]]\n*[[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)]]\n* [[Rebellion]]\n*[[Republic of Lower Canada]]\n*[[The Canadas]]\n*[[Timeline of Quebec history]]\n*[[Upper Canada]]\n{{col div end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Robert Christie (Quebec politician)|Robert Christie]]. ''A History of the Late Province of Lower Canada'', Quebec City: T. Cary/R. Montreal: Worthington, 1848\u20131855 (Internet Archive: [https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Christie%2C%20Robert%22 All 6 volumes])\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Garneau]]. ''History of Canada : from the time of its discovery till the union year'', Montreal : J. Lovell, 1860 (Internet Archive: [https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Garneau%2C%20F.-X%22 All 3 Volumes])\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons-inline}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|Lower Canada}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/lower-canada|title=Lower Canada|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]}}\n*[https://www.britannica.com/place/Canada-East Lower Canada - Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]\n*[http://histoire-du-quebec.ca/gouverneurs-bas-canada/ Gouvernors of Lower Canada - ''Histoire du Qu\u00e9bec'']{{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/politics-government/canadian-confederation/Pages/lower-canada.aspx  Lower Canada - Library and Archives Canada]\n*[http://www.bibliotheque.assnat.qc.ca/guides/fr/documents-politiques-et-parlementaires-du-quebec/139-bas-canada-1791-1838- Lower Canada - Quebec Parliament library]{{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Canadian colonies}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n{{coord missing|Quebec}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1841 disestablishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Lower Canada| ]]\n[[Category:History of Quebec by location]]\n[[Category:British North America]]\n[[Category:Former British colonies and protectorates in the Americas]]\n[[Category:1791 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1791]]\n[[Category:1841 disestablishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1791 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1791 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1841]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th century British colony in present-day Quebec}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox country\n|native_name = {{native name|fr|Province du Bas-Canada}}\n|conventional_long_name = Province of Lower Canada\n|common_name = Lower Canada\n|era       = [[Canada under British rule|British Era]]\n|status    = Colony\n|empire    = United Kingdom\n|government_type    = [[Ch\u00e2teau Clique]] [[oligarchy]]<br /> under a <br />[[Constitutional monarchy]]\n\n|event_start = [[Constitutional Act of 1791]]\n|year_start  = 1791\n|date_start  = 26 December\n|event_end   = [[Act of Union 1840]]\n|year_end    = 1841\n|date_end    = 10 February\n\n|event1      =\n|date_event1 =\n|event2      =\n|date_event2 =\n|event3      =\n|date_event3 =\n\n|p1 = Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Great Britain (1707-1800).svg\n|s1 = United Province of Canada\n|flag_s1 = Flag of the United Kingdom.svg\n|s2 = Colony of Newfoundland\n|flag_s2 = Flag of the United Kingdom.svg\n|today={{Plainlist|* \n{{flag|Canada}}\n* &nbsp;'''\u221f'''{{flag|Quebec}}\n* &nbsp;'''\u221f'''{{flag|Newfoundland and Labrador}}}}\n|flag        = Red Ensign\n|flag_type   = Civil ensign\n|image_flag  = Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n|symbol_type_article=\n|symbol_type  =\n|image_coat   =\n|image_map    = \u00c9volution territoriale du Bas-Canada.gif\n|image_map_caption  = \n|capital          = [[Quebec City]]\n|national_motto   =\n|national_anthem  =\n|common_languages = [[Canadian French|French]], [[Canadian English|English]]\n|religion         =\n|currency         = [[Canadian pound]]\n\n<!--- Titles and names of the first and last leaders and their deputies --->\n|leader1                = [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]\n|year_leader1           = 1791\u20131820\n|leader2                = [[George IV of the United Kingdom|George IV]]\n|year_leader2           = 1820\u20131830\n|leader3                = [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]]\n|year_leader3           = 1830\u20131837\n|leader4                = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n|year_leader4           = 1837\u20131841\n|title_leader = [[List of British Monarchs#House of Hanover|Sovereign]]\n|deputy1      = See [[Lieutenant-Governors of Quebec#Lieutenant-Governors of Lower Canada|list of Lieutenant-Governors]]\n|year_deputy1 =\n|title_deputy = [[Lieutenant-Governor (Canada)|Lieutenant-Governor]] and [[Executive Council of Lower Canada]]\n|legislature  = Parliament of Lower Canada\n|house1       = [[Legislative Council of Lower Canada|Legislative Council]]\n|house2       = [[Legislative Assembly of Lower Canada|Legislative Assembly]]\n\n<!--- Area and population of a given year --->\n|stat_year1 = 1839<ref name=openl>{{cite web|title=The emigrant's handbook of facts concerning Canada, New Zealand, Australia, Cape of Good Hope, &c|url=https://archive.org/stream/cihm_95282#page/n35/mode/2up|publisher=Open Library|accessdate=22 December 2013|pages=2\u20133}}</ref>\n|stat_area1 = 534,185\n|stat_pop1  = {{circa}} 700,000\n|stat_year2 =\n|stat_pop2  =\n|political_subdiv=\n|footnotes  =\n}}\nThe '''Province of Lower Canada''' ({{lang-fr|province du Bas-Canada}}) was a [[British colonization of the Americas|British colony]] on the lower [[Saint Lawrence River]] and the shores of the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]] (1791\u20131841). It covered the southern portion of the current Province of [[Quebec]] and the [[Labrador]] region of the current Province of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] (until the Labrador region was transferred to Newfoundland in 1809).<ref name=\"marianopolis\">{{cite web |year=2007 |url = http://faculty.marianopolis.edu/c.belanger/NFLDHistory/Quebec-NewfoundlandLabradorBoundaryIssue.htm|title = Labrador\u2013Canada Boundary |publisher = marianopolis| accessdate =20 March 2008 |quote=Labrador Act, 1809. \u2013 An imperial act (49 Geo. III, cap. 27), 1809, provided for the re-annexation to Newfoundland of 'such parts of the coast of Labrador from the River St John to Hudson's Streights, and the said Island of Anticosti, and all other smaller islands so annexed to the Government of Newfoundland by the said Proclamation of the seventh day of October one thousand seven hundred and sixty-three (except the said Islands of Madelaine) shall be separated from the said Government of Lower Canada, and be again re-annexed to the Government of Newfoundland.'}}</ref>\n\nLower Canada consisted of part of the former colony of [[Canada (New France)|Canada]] of [[New France]], conquered by Great Britain in the [[Seven Years' War]] ending in 1763 (also called the [[French and Indian War]] in the United States). Other parts of New France conquered by Britain became the Colonies of [[Nova Scotia]], [[New Brunswick]], and [[Prince Edward Island]].\n\nThe Province of Lower Canada was created by the ''[[Constitutional Act 1791]]'' from the partition of the British colony of the [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] (1763\u20131791)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/lower-canada |title=Lower Canada |author=Fernand Ouellet |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |date=March 4, 2015 |accessdate=August 18, 2019 }}</ref> into the Province of Lower Canada and the [[Upper Canada|Province of Upper Canada]]. The prefix \"lower\" in its name refers to its geographic position farther downriver from the headwaters of the [[St. Lawrence River]] than its contemporary Upper Canada, present-day southern Ontario.\n\nLower Canada was abolished in 1841 when it and adjacent Upper Canada were [[Union of Upper and Lower Canada|united]] into the [[Province of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/province-of-canada-1841-67 |title=Province of Canada 1841\u20131867 |author=James Maurice Stockford Careless |author2=Richard Foot |work=The Canadian Encyclopedia |publisher=Historica Canada |date=March 4, 2015 |accessdate=August 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Rebellion==\n{{Main|Lower Canada Rebellion}}\nLike Upper Canada, there was significant political unrest. Twenty-two years after the invasion by the Americans in the [[War of 1812]], a rebellion now challenged the British rule of the predominantly French population. After the [[Lower Canada Rebellion|Patriote Rebellion]] in the [[Rebellions of 1837\u20131838]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/durham-report|title=Durham Report|author=David Mills|author2=Richard Foot|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|date=March 20, 2017|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref> were crushed by the [[British Army]] and [[Loyal (Lower Canada)|Loyal]] volunteers, the [[Constitutional Act 1791|1791 Constitution]] was suspended on 27 March 1838 and a [[Special Council of Lower Canada|special council]] was appointed to administer the colony. An abortive attempt by revolutionary [[Robert Nelson (insurrectionist)|Robert Nelson]] to declare a [[Republic of Lower Canada]] was quickly thwarted.\n\nThe provinces of Lower Canada and Upper Canada were combined as the [[United Province of Canada]] in 1841, when the ''[[Act of Union 1840]]'' came into force. Their separate legislatures were combined into a single parliament with equal representation for both constituent parts, even though Lower Canada had a greater population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/act-of-union|title=Act of Union|author=Jacques Monet, SJ|author2=Richard Foot|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|date= \tMarch 4, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=center>\nfile:WilliamLyonMackenzie.jpeg|[[William Lyon Mackenzie]], [[Upper Canada Rebellion|rebellion]] chief in [[Upper Canada]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrimoine-culturel.gouv.qc.ca/rpcq/detail.do?methode=consulter&id=19028&type=pge#.W_M2PPniaUk|title=Mackenzie, William Lyon - R\u00e9pertoire du patrimoine culturel du Qu\u00e9bec|website=www.patrimoine-culturel.gouv.qc.ca|accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> \nFile:Louis-Joseph Papineau by William Notman.jpg|[[Louis-Joseph Papineau]], [[Lower Canada Rebellion|rebellion]] chief in Lower Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/louis-joseph-papineau|title=Louis-Joseph Papineau|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n\n==Constitution==\n[[File:Constitution-of-lower-canada.png|thumb|left|[[Constitution]] of Lower Canada in 1791]]\nThe Province of Lower Canada inherited the mixed set of French and English institutions that existed in the Province of Quebec during the 1763\u20131791 period and which continued to exist later in Canada-East (1841\u20131867) and ultimately in the current Province of Quebec (since 1867).\n\n{{clear|left}}\n\n==Population==\n{{main|Population of Canada}}Lower Canada was populated mainly by [[Canadiens]], an [[ethnic group]] who trace their ancestry to [[French people|French]] colonists who settled in [[Canada (New France)|Canada]] from the 17th century onward.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Population of Lower Canada, 1806 to 1841\n! Year || Census estimate<ref>[http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/98-187-x/4064809-eng.htm Censuses of Canada. 1665 to 1871], Statistics of Canada, Volume IV, Ottawa, 1876</ref> \n|-\n|1806 || 250,000\n|-\n|1814 || 335,000\n|-\n|1822 || 427,465\n|-\n|1825 || 479,288\n|-\n|1827 || 473,475\n|-\n|1831 || 553,134\n|-\n|1841 || 650,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n[[File:Qu\u00e9bec I-185-1-a.svg|thumbnail|left|125px|Current route marker seen along the ''Chemin'']]\nTravelling around Lower Canada was mainly by water along the [[St. Lawrence River]]. On land the only long-distance route was the [[Chemin du Roy]] or King's Highway, built in the 1730s by [[New France]].<ref name=\"lecheminduroy.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lecheminduroy.com/en/history|title=History - Le Chemin du Roy|website=Le Chemin du Roy|accessdate=19 November 2018|quote= summary of the original french version}}</ref> The King's Highway was, in addition to the mail route, the primary means of long-distance passenger travel until steamboats (1815) and railways (1850s) began to challenge the royal road.<ref name=\"lecheminduroy.com\"/> The royal road's importance waned after the 1850s and would not re-emerge as a key means of transportation until the modern [[Highways in Quebec|highway system of Quebec]] was created in the 20th century.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|History}}\n{{col div|colwidth=23em}}\n*[[Canada East]], period after the ''[[Act of Union 1840]]''\n*[[Former colonies and territories in Canada]]\n*[[French and Indian War]]\n* [[French and Indian Wars]]\n*[[French colonial empire]]\n*[[List of lieutenant governors of Quebec]]\n*[[National Patriots' Day]]\n*[[Ottawa River timber trade]]\n*[[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)]]\n* [[Rebellion]]\n*[[Republic of Lower Canada]]\n*[[The Canadas]]\n*[[Timeline of Quebec history]]\n*[[Upper Canada]]\n{{col div end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Robert Christie (Quebec politician)|Robert Christie]]. ''A History of the Late Province of Lower Canada'', Quebec City: T. Cary/R. Montreal: Worthington, 1848\u20131855 (Internet Archive: [https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Christie%2C%20Robert%22 All 6 volumes])\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Garneau]]. ''History of Canada : from the time of its discovery till the union year'', Montreal : J. Lovell, 1860 (Internet Archive: [https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Garneau%2C%20F.-X%22 All 3 Volumes])\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons-inline}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|Lower Canada}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/lower-canada|title=Lower Canada|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]}}\n*[https://www.britannica.com/place/Canada-East Lower Canada - Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]\n*[http://histoire-du-quebec.ca/gouverneurs-bas-canada/ Gouvernors of Lower Canada - ''Histoire du Qu\u00e9bec'']{{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/politics-government/canadian-confederation/Pages/lower-canada.aspx  Lower Canada - Library and Archives Canada]\n*[http://www.bibliotheque.assnat.qc.ca/guides/fr/documents-politiques-et-parlementaires-du-quebec/139-bas-canada-1791-1838- Lower Canada - Quebec Parliament library]{{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Canadian colonies}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n{{coord missing|Quebec}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1841 disestablishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Lower Canada| ]]\n[[Category:History of Quebec by location]]\n[[Category:British North America]]\n[[Category:Former British colonies and protectorates in the Americas]]\n[[Category:1791 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1791]]\n[[Category:1841 disestablishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1791 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1791 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1841]]\n", "name_user": "Blairall", "label": "safe", "comment": "revised my prior edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_Canada"}
